> And I\'m sure that as (I am told) many mosques have a plaque or other
> indicator indicating the direction of of Mecca now, offworld mosques
> might well have some sort of indicator controlled by a computer. 
> 
> For personal use, something incorporating a gps type system might work.

Of course, since praying "toward" Mecca even on Earth involves praying
along the great circle leading there (you don\'t stand on your head if
you\'re 170 degrees away, in other words), one would probably see the same
sort of practical correction applied here.  You\'d aim for the point on the
horizon directly above or below the current location of Sol in the sky.

A complication here is that mosques are often built (on Terra) so that
their orientation naturally focuses on the direction of Mecca.  The Saudi
embassy in Washington DC is a lovely example; it has a sort of outer
curtain wall which is aligned with the street and adjoining lots, but the
building inside (which includes a mosque) is rotated about 30 degrees so
that the front doors are pointed at Mecca.  Makes for a rather striking
effect.

Needless to say, this couldn\'t be done if the direction to Mecca changed
on a daily cycle.  This alone might lead to most \'mainstream\' Muslims
accepting a compromise in which some on-planet location -- first landing
point, first mosque constructed, location of a shard of the Kaaba -- is
taken as "local Mecca" for prayer purposes.  Of course, there would be
ultra-orthodox Muslims who insist on praying toward Mecca itself.  They
would thus do the five daily prayers in five directions, spinning through
a circle each day.  I might imagine their picking up the nickname
"Dervishes" for this.

It may not be long (on historical timescales) before real-world Moslems
need to face part of this issue.  On the Moon, the direction to Mecca from
any point on the surface is fixed (plus or minus about three degrees,
which is fairly neglibile.  However, the daily cycle of prayer would pose
a problem.  Do you pray five times over the lunar day, or the terran?  If
the latter, do you do it by Mecca time, or GMT, or whatever time is being
kept in the base?  With the latter two, how do you decide what latitude\'s
sunrise and sunset to use?

> I do agree that the direction would too little to worry about when
> taking even a jump 6 in the Marches. I was being a bit disingenious
> with regard to prayers in jump, knowing that some scholars will nitpick
> doctrines to death, and it might be argued that one couldn\'t know the
> right direction while in jump.

I would imagine that there would arise a fatwah for this, like "toward the
bow".  Again, there would be dissenters.

> Think there\'s a chance that for those places, they\'d go by the
> calculated time of the new moon?

Some Moslem countries use a calculated new moon standard today.  In fact,
one of the elements of the BCCI banking scandal a few years back involved
a scheme that went awry because of differences on this issue.  I don\'t
remember the specific countries involved, but both were to end a banking
holiday at hilal, the next sighting of the new moon.  Country A used
calculation, and ended the holiday on the predicted date.  Country B used
observation, and its official observers failed to spot the moon and
extended the holiday one day.  As a result, a key transaction failed to go
through between the two countries, causing a ripple of unmade payments
which led to exposure of (that part of) BCCI\'s machinations.

ObTrav should be clear... :)

