    'body' => '>>From what I understand from 3rd parties, the people who wrote designs for
>Fighting Ships of the Shattered Imperium didn\'t pay much attention to the
>rules; therefore, some (many?) of the designs are badly flawed.

Regardless of that fact, the highest armor value on the MT chart is 120,
which translates to something like 32,400 cm of hard steel (I don\'t have
the book in front of me, but it\'s somewhere close). The BBs make use of the
highest armor value available.

Hugely armored ships don\'t suffer performance problems in MT because mass
doesn\'t figure into manuever drive calculations in the vehicle construction
system. It was all based on *volume* (as in High Guard). You allocate a
certain number of manuever drive units per volume tonnage of the ship, and
you can get 6G acceleration, regardless of whether the ship is a svelt
fighterboat or a lumbering armored dreadnaught from hell.

So even if they paid attention to the rules the designs would be flawed,
because the rules themselves were flawed.

Still, your right. It\'s MegaErrata.

However, I think the ship illos look cool (big fan of Roger Raupp here) --
for the most part much better than Fighting Ships, IMHO. And there is a
much wider variety of vessels than in FS. I thought there might be some
passing interest in GT versions of front-line cap ships therein. And I was
home sick and bored. ;-)

I simply can\'t wait for GT: Starships. <salivating>

Ciao,

Joseph R. Dietrich
