    'from' => 'Glenn Goffin gmgoffin@yahoo.com',
    'body' => '>From: Kenji Schwarz <schwarz@fas.harvard.edu>
>Why can\'t people just learn that history is about 
>FACTS and not "interpretation"?????

That\'s directly contrary to what I learned as ahistory
major.  

First, what\'s the difference?  Where does the fact end
and the interpretation begin?  

Is it a fact or is it interpretation that the
Communists had X million men under arms, and the
Nationalists had Y million?  Choosing where to draw
the line for defining "under arms" is a question of
interpretation -- or is it?  What if each political
entity had its own definition of under arms?  Does
that make it more of a fact or more interpretation?

Second, facts by themselves don\'t provide anything
useful.  Facts are automatically interpreted to form
an understanding.  If the reporter of the facts does
not interpret them viva voce, he or she is actually
interpreting them sub silentio through arrangement and
presentation -- and the reader is doing the same
thing.  That\'s why historians typically state their
theses first -- "this paper seeks to show that the
Communists hindered the Japanese more than the
Nationalists did".  Full disclosure reminds the reader
read the facts and interpretations critically.

Third, one of the major functions of history is to
remember what happened; one professor called us
"society\'s professional rememberers."  We as humans
don\'t remember raw facts, or if we do, we don\'t
usually apply them well.  We remember stories.  It
seems that we\'re almost hard-wired to do that. 

- --Glenn

