In one of the Fuzzy books, there was a remark to the effect that
you could find a precedent for _anything_ in Colonial law.  Some
examples that I recall:

In the Fuzzy trial (People of the Colony of Zarathustra v.
Holloway and Kellogg), after Kellogg committed suicide, Leslie
Coombs, Kellogg\'s lawyer (and the legal counsel for the Chartered
Zarathustra Company) made a statement to the effect "You can\'t go
through the farce of trying a dead man", and Holloway\'s lawyer,
Gus Brannhard, immediately came up with a precedent for doing
just that.

Also, the issue of sapience = talk-and-build-a-fire as an
identity was knocked down on the basis of another precedent in
Colonial law, an infanticide case.  The defense argument in that
case was that murder was defined as the deliberate killing of a
sapient being; a sapient being is one that can talk and build a
fire; a human infant can do neither; therefore, a human infant is
not sapient, and therefore cannot be murdered.  This case
established that T&BaF is proof-positive, but an apparent
inability is not proof-contrary.

Have at it, folks; your pet legal theories no doubt have _some_
examples - both for and against - _somewhere_ in the Eleven
Thousand Worlds...
