>> 
>> I\'d *love* to see them do something like that. But they won\'t. Not if
>> their lawyers hear about it in time.
>> 
>> You see, there\'s a *clear* legal precedent on *that* trick, dating back
>> to a consultant who rigged his software to wip a company\'s mainframe if
>> they didn\'t pay his bill on time (or some such). 
>
> Ah, but their shrinkware license, the one that says, \'if you break this 
> seal, 
> you agree to our licensing terms\', *also* says that the product is *not* 
> warranted to be or do *anything* on anybody\'s computer, and MS is *not* to 
> be 
> held liable for any data loss, computer malfs, or mother in law visits that 
> may occur from attempted useage of the software.

Contracts of adhesion aren\'t worth the paper they are printed on. And
in fact, many of them, like Microsoft\'s, tend to violate the law in
other ways (such as copyright law, which grants rights that are not
negotiable to the purchaser of a copyrighted work, said rights typical
being "denied" by the "license").

Their *sole* purpose is to discourage buyers from trying to claim their
*actual* legal rights, and thus save MS a lot of legal fees. 

Also, MS *cannot* use a contract to wiggle out of *deliberate* damage
caused by their software. 

>> The court ruled that he\'d have been within his rights to have his
>> software quit working, destroying the data (and other programs) which
>> did *not* belong to him was \\n\'t acceptable, Therefore he came under
>> the laws for malicious destruction of the files. 
>> 
>> MS would lose *bigtime* in court over a stunt like that. 
>
> I don\'t think so.  I think they could get away with contending that they\'re 
> not responsible for damages resulting from illegal useage of their software, 
> especially in regards to their shrinkware license.

Again, the shrinkware license is *not* a valid contract, in that
there\'s *no* way to negotiate it. Ask a lawyer about "contracts of
adhesion". It takes a small miracle to get them upheld. That\'s why the
software companies tried to get a law passed that *made* shrinkwrap
licenses legally binding. They got it passed in Louisana, but last I\'d
heard it\'d been ruled against in court decisions.

And as I recall, that decision I referred to earlier *does* say that
the programmer *is* responsible for damages his software *deliberately*
causes, even if the "trigger" for the damage is an illegal act on the
part of the person using the software. 

In the case in question the "illegal act" was continuing to use the
software without paying for it. And that\'s *exactly* what would be
going on in our hypothetical scenario with MS servers.

