    'from' => 'Glenn Goffin gmgoffin@yahoo.com',
    'body' => '>From: Walter Smith <SmithW@HARTWICK.EDU>

>The appearance was of multiple attempts to "get" the 
>officers, a semblance of legal maneuvering to avoid 
>the protections against double jeapardy. The Feds did

>not push for an appeal, therefore they must have seen

>no *legal* grounds for overturning the court\'s
> decision.  

That\'s correct:  There were no legal grounds for
overturning the trial court\'s decision, which was a
jury verdict for acquittal.  The government can never
appeal from an acquittal after trial.  The result of
winning such an appeal would be a new trial over the
same crime:  that is, double jeopardy.

Double jeopardy, as understood in the United States,
has always meant that the government cannot try a
defendant twice for the same crime, and the doctrine
has always recognized that more than one government
with prosecution power exists.  That is, the federal
government and each state\'s government (if it has
jurisdiction) can prosecute the same defendant for the
same crime.  

- --Glenn

