>>United States Federal Government to charge the officers with
>>violating Mr. King\'s civil rights. It looked like the government
>>had decided that this high-profile, emotionally charged circus
>>of a case needed a guilty verdict for spin purposes, and tried to
>>create a guilty verdict themselves when the courts in California
>>did not do so.
>
>         Would you then completely rule out the possibility that
>         certain human beings in the federal government thought 
>         that the officers broke the law?

It doesn\'t matter *what* they thought. The offficers had been acquiited
in a court of law. And legally, that made them immune for *any*
prosecution for the *actions* involved. Not merely the crime that they
were tried for, but for any other crime that that set of actions might
fall under.

That\'s the whole *basis* for "double jeopardy". The British
government\'s habit of retrying people on different charges for the same
*act* until they got a conviction is one of the things that led to the
American Revolution. 

>  It might be interesting
>         to have a TU world with competing systems of law, where
>         jurisdictions overlap and the courts go out of their way
>         to embarrass the other courts.  Players caught in the
>         middle might have a bad time ;)

Heck, just have one without the double jeopardy rule. Strict or loose.
(Strict "no retrial for the same *act* once acquitted", loose "no
retrial for the same *charge*")

That second one ought to surprise the heck out of players.

"But they already tried him on that charge and found him innocent!"
"Yes, but the government decided that a retrial was in order. Perfectly
legal...."

