    'topic' => 're: Wild Blue Claims',
    'body' => '>From: Walter Smith <SmithW@HARTWICK.EDU

>While I agree that historians must interpret, they 
>must show that their interpretation logically and 
>justifiably follows from the facts. 

Agreed.  Of course, that\'s inextricably intertwined
with presentation of the facts.  

>There has been considerable danger, at least lately 
>in the United States, that historians and other 
>social scientists will start with the interpretation 
>and *then* start putting the facts together, with 
>predictable results.

(1) "at least lately in the United States":  The
danger has been long recognized.  Herodotus himself is
called both the father of history and the father of
lying.  

(2) No one is a blank slate.  The faceless historians
and social scientists you mention studied history and
have read a lot of interpretations and facts and
developed their rhetorical and analytical skills.  The
process of producing historical work ordinarily starts
with choosing a subject with which the historian has
some familiarity, and therefore also some
preconceptions.  To work in a totally unfamiliar area
is generally not an efficient use of one\'s time.  

The next part is research, which may challenge those
preconceptions.  In fact, research is a constant
process of interpreting what you\'re seeing and trying
to fit it into context or changing the context -- the
preconceptions -- so that the facts found in research
can be explained.  

obTrav:  Don\'t forget Dev Landrel.

- --Glenn

