> stories. Heinlein\'s "Orphans of the Sky" has a generation ship that has
> descended into barbarism after a mutiny among the crew killed too many
> people.
>
> Then there\'s Brian Aldiss\'s "Starship" where we have another generation
> ship where things have gone badly wrong. Though it takes a while to
> realize that\'s the setting. In this case, they are on the way *back*
> from a coplonizing trip that didn\'t work out. And things have gone
> wrong because of something they picked up.
>
> Oh yeah, I knew there was at least one more! Delany\'s "The Ballad of
> Beta 2" (this and "Babel-17" are Delany books for people who don\'t like
> his better known books). It\'s pretty short, but it deals with a culture
> on generation ships as well. It\'s got a sort of "anthropologist" doing
> a followup to an earlier "cultural survey" of the culture on a fleet
> fleet of generation ships that had been discovered many, many years
> back in orbit around a star that wasn\'t theor original destination.
> It\'s got nice touches such as vocabulary shifts as succeeding
> generations found new uses for words that didn\'t have a referent in
> their "world" ("sand" was what they called interstellar high radiation
> areas, being mostly in low g or no g "arms" shifted to mean "limb", and
> "sore feet" was a term describing the way they felt in a normal g area.
>
