predominantly British slang;
  Knocked-up: Either tired (after a hard work-out, run, manual labour) or
being preggers (pregnant)
  Fanny: Works both ways, depending on whom you are talking to... either
backside (errrr... bum) or a woman\'s front bottom.  I have never heard of a
man having a fanny as part of his anatomy for some reason... so perhaps it\'s
also gender specific?
  Aussies have "Condoms"... it\'s in the adverts and on the wrappers.
However, we know of the term "rubber" and apply it in humorous fashion
whenever we wish to be difficult (the old, "Can I borrow your rubber?"
question can have a mile made from it if you consider what might be returned
if the rubber borrowed was a condom!).
  Those little board mates that you place under a beverage to either sop the
moisture from a cold drink, or protect a table from the heat of a hot one,
are called "drink coasters" or just "coaster" (those things you put under
the chairs of a lounge/couch to protect the carpet are also coasters) in
Aussie, I believe they are "drink mats" in the U.K.... don\'t know what they
are in the US?

ObTrav: Dirtside performing routine maintenance, the Engineer calls the town
party to "Grab a set of \'coasters\' for the vertical slide flange, these ones
are shot!" (Coasters being a pair of small rubber rings).  The steward, part
of the town party knows coasters are a type of glass cocktail drinking
containers, but is cosmopolitan enough to guess that the engineer is
speaking about some kind of glass cups for the flange-thingie and rocks on
down to the ship\'s engineering supply store and tells the clerk what he
needs... only to be given a set of expensive,
non-refundable/non-exchangeable star ship grade gaskets and being assured
that this is what the engineer must be talking about as they are clearly
labelled "AG-4818567 Coasters, Starship Grade, Type-B"...

