figures are different without reverse-engineering both versions.

>Question: Why do
>spinal mounts use cf/50 for volume, when they would seem to be completely
>enclosed in the hull (after all, the ship is built around it) and thus
>subject to the cf/20 requirement?

You\'d have to ask David Pulver, or I\'ll ask him when I get a chance. I
think he felt it was a better approximation of Traveller that way --
weapons in streamlined turrets also ignore that rule -- but I couldn\'t say
for sure.

>>The surface area of turrets and bays is calculated for just that portion
>>which is outside the hull proper.
>
>Except that a turret is 3 spaces, right? Plus 1 in the hull for crewstation
>and turning mechanism? The surface area of 800 would seem to suggest that
>the turret is armored in it\'s entirety, as if it were completely
>free-standing cube seperate from the hull (1,500 cf = 800 sf surface area,
>according to GV). The 50-space bays are the same.

An abstraction, to prevent having to calculate just how big the hole in the
hull is. VE2 treats all superstructures this way, including wings, arms and
legs, wheels, etc.

>I actually came pretty close to the canonical size [of a Type T], with a
>damage of 6d x 16,700. ...
>
>Another question: What are good ballpark figures for warship armor? 

Are you aware that there has been a change to the way damage is calculated
for beam weapons 1-Gj and over? Damage now increases as 10*(Output
energy)^1/3, instead of (Output energy)^1/2. Your damage figures are
probably high, therefore.

With that in mind, here are the armor guidelines I proposed for GT:
Imperial Navy. Since the authors haven\'t complained, I infer that they have
been accepted. They were designed mostly for playability, but also on the
theory that the Imperial Navy Ship Board (or whoever) wouldn\'t pay for
designs that were clearly over-armored for their intended mission. I\'ve
made no attempt whatever to relate these values to previous version in a
quantitative fashion.

"Turrets for all types should have a minimum DR 100 and maximum DR of 500
at TL8, doubled every TL thereafter, or 1/2 the armor of the ship,
whichever is less. Note that this is upward of 96 *stons* of armor per turret.

"Scouts, escorts, and auxiliaries should be resistant to turret weapons:
minimum armor DR 100, maximum DR 1,000 at TL8, doubled every TL thereafter.
These ships may or may not carry nuclear dampers or meson screens (in the
same range of DR), depending on their role and TL. Auxiliaries converted
from civilian use will have the minimum armor possible, to save weight and
money.

"Cruisers and carriers should carry nuclear dampers and be immune to turret
weapons and resistant to bay weapons: minimum DR 6,000, maximum DR 10,000
at TL8, plus DR 3,000 (min)/5,000 (max) per TL thereafter, both armor and
meson screens.

"Battleships and battleriders should carry nuclear dampers and may have
black globe forcefields (if available). Their armor and meson screens
should be immune to bay weapons and resistant to spinal mounts: minimum DR
10,000 at TL 8, plus DR 5,000 per TL thereafter; absolute maximum DR
80,000. Fleet tenders are generally constructed as dispersed hulls, and so
effectively cannot be armored."

