Just think big men (when 6\'2" was considered very tall, and you had to be 
taller to join a heavy cavalry regiment than the Grenadier Guards) on big 
horses (to carry the weight). The idea is that heavy horse was more efficient 
in their role as battlefield shock troops. I read an excellent analogy of 
this in Charles Grant\'s book on Fontenoy. He said a typical trooper\'s horse 
back then was the size of a kettle drum horse today (a lot closer to the 
Medieval Great Horse). Heavy cavalry was incredibly expensive to buy, train 
and maintain. This was part of the reason you never saw them on our side of 
the pond (and the ridiculous cost to ship them across the Atlantic, and the 
fact the topography was totally unsuited to the employment of large numbers 
of cavalry). Ironically by the Civil War (US) there was much more "Cavalry 
country" (low rolling hills that have been deforested) due to development but 
Cavalry doctrine was in the midst of serious doctrinal change (who the h---- 
wants to charge Spencers?).

