    'body' => '> From: Christopher Thrash <thrash@io.com>

< snipping of a disquisition on Nuclear Damper technology>

> Sorry for the exhaustive treatment, but we may as well be clear on

For what?  You pretty much cleared up a muddy subject

> what was said on the subject. There _is_ an area of effect in CT, but
> small enough to encompass only one missile at a time. The time
> required to render a warhead harmless is short enough that many
> engagements are possible, but GURPS targeting and skill rules make
> them significantly less than 100% effective (which the current area
> effect dampers are).

Well, as combat rounds are 20 minutes in GT, you could get quite a 
few shots off in that time.  Considering it only takes a fraction of a 
second to disable a warhead, that\'s more than 1200 nukes a 
combat round.  What that fraction is, I don\'t know.

And assuming that PD fire is at +10, I would think you had a good 
chance of taking out that many nukes.  You are practically going to 
be at Point Blank range because the dampers get too huge to break 
the 10,000 mile hex range.

Of course, there are no rules for aiming, targeting, etc.  But if 
someone were desperate enough, he could come up with some 
targeting rules similiar to energy weapons. I would treat them as 
laser turrets but with a much higher accuracy and targeting 
capability; you don\'t have to move a turret ... just deflect a beam 
(technology *we* have had since the 60s).  For range, I would make 
it the max range of the damper ... it either works or it don\'t.

So, with a handwave, I would assume that since you can 
"theoretically" target over 1200 nukes a round, and the aiming is 
much more precise than that of turret weapons, the Nuclear Damper 
is a Field Effect that encases the ship and just be done with it and 
only worry about individual warheads very rarely.

However, one sticking point ... as the range of the damper is 
*significantly* shorter than the ranges usually dealt with in a 20 
minute combat round, the number of possible intercepts are 
probably going to be substantially reduced, too.  So lets look at the 
requirements:

Any weapon can be used for point defense.  Lasers can only take 
out one missile per turn for Point Def purposes.  I propose because 
it can only shoot once per minute and once it has shot, the range the 
rest of the missiles have to travel is too short to allow another 
recharge to complete before another shot can occur.  This PointDef 
fire occurs in the last minute of the combat round.

Nuclear Dampers to not appear to require "recharging."  So they 
can "fire" continuously.  Thus, they should be able to take out at 
least 60 per combat round (1 per second for 1 minute ... the last 
minute of the combat round).  Assuming a 50/50 chance of success 
(a very conservative number IMO), they would be able to 
automatically take out 30 nuclear missiles per combat round.  
Anything more than that and they probably shouldn\'t be in the fight to 
start with!  Note that this assumes all missiles arrive within the 
Damper\'s area of effect in the same minute.

I hoped everyone was able to follow this twisting line of logic.  I 
believe this falls under Deductive Reasoning ... If Cow A is Black 
then that black animal must be a cow :)


