    'body' => 'On 11/04/99 at 11:44 PM,  Mark Watson <markw@antares.demon.co.uk> said:

>>"Could I have a napkin, please" in a restaraunt, for example. :-)

>... would get you a (table) napkin. A diaper in the UK is a nappy.
>The derivation of nappy is from napkin but nappy is always (in my
>experience, and I have 2 kids) used. 

When I was eight, my parents, grandparents and I were at some office
or other on a Saturday afternoon.  We had just finished eating
lunch, fried chicken, and my mother had been complaining about
having grease on her hands and no napkin to clean them.  I was
bored, getting restless, and had to use the rest room.  I sneaked
out.

A little exploring through the mostly empty building and I found the
Men\'s room, but it was locked and I was getting desperate...I tried
the Ladies.  It wasn\'t locked, I\'d been told to *never* go into the
Ladies room, but I was *really* getting desperate, so with great
trepidation I went in.

After taking care of urgent business, I took the opportunity to look
around.  It was much nicer than a Men\'s room.  There was even a
couch, though why anyone would want to sit around a restroom was
beyond me.  IAC, and much to my surprise, there was a vending
machine offering "Sanitary Napkins" for a dime.  It made sense.  Men
would just use the paper towels, but women were neat and selling
napkins in a ladies room seemed appropriate.

I had a dime.  It seemed like a lot for a napkin, I paid that much
for a comic book, and there was a new Sgt Rock out I wanted, but I
was going to be in trouble for sneaking out and figured this might
get me off the hook...so I inserted my dime.

Out popped a package, large for a napkin I thought, but maybe it was
a large cloth napkin and that\'s why it cost a dime. It came in a
paper wrapper, and that made sense too.  After all, sanitary means
clean.

I proudly returned to the office and presented my Mother with my
present saying, "Here, Mom!  You said you needed one of these."

A great uproar ensued!  I was sent out to wait in the car with
absolutely no idea why all the men were laughing and the women were
redfaced and embarrassed.

I don\'t suppose anyone would care to explain it to me?

Anonymous

