Sorry to burst your bubble there, but the military history of the Civil
War is predominantly of interest to military historians. As iomportant as
the actions of Grant, Sherman, Lee, Jackson et. al. were, they were of
secondary importance to the overall picture.

The _political_ history of the Civil War is _why_ we have a military
history of the Civil War and is of far more relevance, particularly in
these days of the resurgence of \'states rights\'...

Sherman, for example, is far better remembered for his \'march to the sea\'
in social and political terms than in military ones. While his campaign
did hasten the wars end, to this day, over a hundred and thirty years
later, he is reviled in parts of this country as a genocidal monster,
hardly the picture we get in our history books as children. Whihc is more
important in it\'s impact on human society?

The second problem is your assumption that assignments in academic
departments have any relationship to what the professors specialty or
training is...That professor probably had little choice over her subject
matter...

Finally, aside from some constant whiners like George Will, who won\'t be
satisfied until college educations are limited to upper-class white males,
about upper-class white males like himself again, the \'PC\' fad has been
waning on most campuses for some time.

> 
> I HATE the whole social history movement. While I think it\'s very important 
> to study the "little man/woman" to get the whole picture of history, I reject 
> the notion that one shouldn\'t study the movers and shakers (i.e., the rulers, 
> leaders, etc.). This is just 1960s backlash against the "establishment". The 
> problem with social history, is that until democracy, the little man/woman 
> didn\'t DO a whole hell of a lot. It\'s more interesting to study the leaders.

The problem with studying the \'movers and shakers\' is that we tend to
mostly have records written either by them, or by people with axes to
grind against them, and either is unlikely to be very reflective of
reality. However, historical accounts of those unimportant little people
are more likely to be factual, precisely because they didn\'t count, and no
one risked prison or worse writing some version of the truth.

From the impact on the lives on the little people we get a better idea of
what the M&S\'es were _really_ doing...and arguably studying the history of
99.999% of humankind could be considered more important that studying that
0.001% who are listed as important in the records they wrote themselves...

ObTrav. I suspect that the study of history in the 3I will be considerably
different, due to institutions such as the AAB, and the generally high
tech level of the Imperium and it\'s predecessors, leading to much better
record preservation.

For instance, imagine what the data warehouse of a megacorp like Sharushid
contains within it... the purchasing patterns and intimate detail on the
lives of trillions and trillions of customers reaching back millenia...

> Ob Trav: Imagine studying the 3I by studying how the lives of groat farmers 
> are effected by the civil wars, and NOT studying the barracks emperors.

Seen from that perspective, the Civil War was some interesting news that
happened on the trivid, or to your neighbor Eneri down the road, whose
nephew was in the Navy and lost during a battle.

Canonically, about _all_ the the Civil War affected was whose butt was in
the the Iridium Throne, and whose fleets were in battle. To the people
involved it was a Big Thing, but to the greater mass of the Imperium, it
wasn\'t. 

That it was predominantly political maneuvering is made clear by the fact
that the outlying polities, such as the Vargr, Solomani and Zhodani didn\'t
take advantage of the \'unrest\' in the Imperium, because there really
wasn\'t all that much unrest...the Imperial bureaucracy continmued to
function just fine, as did the majority of the Navy...MOST fleets stayed
on station most of the time, loyal to the Emperor or Empress, whoever he
or she was that week.

It did not have the wodespread shortages, deprivations and destruction
that accompanied the Rebellion. The Hard Times hit everyone, then.

That so much print, argument and importance is attached to the Barracks
Emperors is a sign that the study in the 3I is skewed towards the M&S\'es
almost exclusively, the Dead White Males of the Imperium.

