    'body' => 'From: Sethkimmel@aol.com <Sethkimmel@aol.com>


>I HATE the whole social history movement. While I think it\'s very important
>to study the "little man/woman" to get the whole picture of history, I
reject
>the notion that one shouldn\'t study the movers and shakers (i.e., the
rulers,
>leaders, etc.). This is just 1960s backlash against the "establishment".
The
>problem with social history, is that until democracy, the little man/woman
>didn\'t DO a whole hell of a lot. It\'s more interesting to study the
leaders.


It\'s hardly a 1960s backlash against the establishment. The very concept of
social history has roots that reach back to folks like Marx. Although I
personally think that Marx simplified things too much, his idea that history
could be viewed from the bottom up as opposed to the top down was undeniably
revolutionary. The tradition grew and continued from the 19th century on. It
gained steam later with interesting permutations that developed with the
growth and / or birth of such disciplines as folklore, sociology,
anthropology, linguistics and the other social sciences.

Academic movements, like artistic movements, literary movements and
political movements, usually don\'t appear overnight. It\'s not like everybody
in the late 60s just said, "Hey let\'s be anti-establishment and muck around
with history!" It\'s been a slow and steady progression.

>Ob Trav: Imagine studying the 3I by studying how the lives of groat farmers
>are effected by the civil wars, and NOT studying the barracks emperors.


I can easily imagine it, especially in the light that canonically the social
sciences have progressed to the astonishing complexity of "psycho-history."
Do you think that they progressed to that point by studying the tiny group
of Mules and shakers... um... pardon me, movers and shakers who cast long
shadows on history? Of course not.

The truth of the matter is that studying the groat farmers gives a much
clearer picture of history. It provides context which cannot be attained by
seeing who happened to have claim to the Iridium Throne on a given day
during the period of the Barracks Emperors.
