    'body' => 'From: Bruce Johnson <johnson@Pharmacy.Arizona.EDU>


>ObTrav. I suspect that the study of history in the 3I will be considerably
>different, due to institutions such as the AAB, and the generally high
>tech level of the Imperium and it\'s predecessors, leading to much better
>record preservation.


High technology does not always bring with it better record preservation.
One of the problems that people are starting to focus on is the lack of
permanence of computer records. I don\'t mean that they degrade, I mean that
they just simply disappear. I would one day like to write a popular history
of the BBS world, and I\'ve discovered in doing so that... well... large
chunks of that history are just gone. No archeologist is ever going to dig
this stuff up. For the most part, roughly twenty years of the history of
computer telecommunications happen to be lost. Forever.

The problem isn\'t the method of recording, the problem is that people just
don\'t realize that they\'re sitting on tomorrow\'s history. Then again...


>For instance, imagine what the data warehouse of a megacorp like Sharushid
>contains within it... the purchasing patterns and intimate detail on the
>lives of trillions and trillions of customers reaching back millenia...


...the Vilani may be a little bit different in that respect. ;)

They might *always* realize that they\'re sitting on top of history at all
times, and go to great lengths to preserve it. ;)
