Much of the data that is not actively distorted by vested interests will be
incomplete or inaccurate when viewed in retrospect, simply because the
people making the record _lived_ in their world, and made assumptions and
left out data that future researchers can\'t reconstruct. That\'s the reason
for the branch of anthropology called "Historical Archaeology", which seeks
to confirm or deny the available historical records with archaeological
evidence. HA often focuses on disenfranchised minorities, because they
leave so few written records.

ObTrav: Because of the length of the historical record, most of the
archaeology in the Imperium would fall into the category of HA rather than
the pre-historic archaeology with which we are more familiar. If nothing
else, it would provide some archaeological expeditions with a rationale and
goal *other* than the done-to-death Ancients (cf. the Beltstrike module).
