    'index' => 'ed522',
    'month' => '11',
    'topic' => ' How do fuel tanks work?',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> As the fuel is used in a ships fuel tank, what goes in its place?
>
> If air is used then it would have to be generated, or air pressure would fall
> dramatically. 
>
> Vacuum would cause the remaining fuel to boil.

You pump out liquid, and some of the remaining fuel vaporizes to
fill the space. 

That\'s how it works in current LH2 tanks, and there\'s no reason for
ones in the future to be any different.

Well, actually, there are some setups that pressurize the tank with
helium gas. But that\'s because most current vehicles have tanks that
are so lightweight that they\'ll collapse without positive pressure.
That\'s not the case with tanks in Traveller ships.

