    'ts-index' => '1999-11-08.ed532',
    'body' => 'Ian Ferguson wrote:
>>>>>>>>
	I am unfamiliar with the Vargr Charisma and Zhodani
	mageocracy systems, but I have always figured that a rich
	character with megacredits can still have low SoS (picture
	Al Capone).
>>>>>>>>
The Vargr character generation system has the far more volatile 
Charisma taking the place (for the most part) of Social Standing,
at least in Vargr culture...though an Imperial Vargr would almost
certainly have an Imperial social standing as well.

"Mageocracy" = rulership by people with magical powers. Not the
most accurate term, but social standing in the Zhodani consulate
is strongly linked to posession of psionic powers, and the strength
of those powers.

For a counter-example of Al Capone, look at John Kennedy senior.
The basis of his family fortune was his career as a smuggler during
the American prohibition era, but he was later (after he "retired" from
his stint in the "Other" career) able to turn his wealth into a high social
standing. Had Al Capone retired from his career in the "Other" profession,
and relocated out of the jurisdiction of the American justice system,
he could probably have done the same. Considering the social
circles some gangsters moved in - Hollywood, Las Vegas, etc. - there
are many examples of gangsters who would be rated with quite high
(if very vulnerable) social standings, even while at the height of their
careers.

Walt Smith
