  {
    'body' => 'Christopher Thrash writes:
>*Note: I am not a biologist, nor do I play one on TV. The
>information contained herein derived from working as a
>computer tech at the Patuxent Wildlife Research Center, with
>access to the library and entirely too much time on my hands.*

	I am a biologist, but I have not played one on TV.

>There is a specific subfield of evolutionary biology called
>/island biogeography/.
<snipped>
>There are two basic observations: 
>(1) That the number of species on an island rises as its area
>increases.
<snipped>
>(2) That extinct species are replenished more quickly the
>closer the island is to a source habitat
<snipped>

	Good summary of island biogeography.

>A secondary observation is that there is a minimum area
>threshold for speciation; areas smaller than this will not
>support the independent development of new species. If
>isolated, existing species that become extinct will not be
>replaced and the overall biodiversity will reduce to
>the level that the area can support on its own. "Fragmentation
>of tropical forests will leave only habitat islands below the
>minimum level for autochthonous speciation. (Division in situ
>into subspecies along clines)."

	I am not familiar with the term "autochthonous," but from
	the quote provided I take it to mean the division of one
	species into two where there is no physical barrier to
	separate the prospective species.  This certainly makes
	sense: very small populations would find such speciation
	unlikely (it is contraversial as to whether such speciation
	takes place even in large areas).  However, a small area can
	actually help speciation along in the sense of a population
	evolving into a new species.

>There may also be a relationship between the size of the island
>and the mass of the largest animal that can evolve there. (I
>remember reading a paper on this, but I can\'t find a reference
>for it.)

	There is certainly a limit to the size of organisms that
	can live there, and you cannot evolve if you cannot live.
	I can repost those biomass estimates to give you an idea
	of how large the different levels of the food chain are
	likely to be, but (as someone posted) 100 kg plants to 10
	kg herbivores to 1 kg carnivores is a good rule-of-thunb.

>ObTrav:
>* In the case of the generation ship, unless it is *extremely*
>large, species are more likely to die out than be replaced
>through speciation, and the overall complexity of the biosphere
>will decline.

	This is probably true.  If you really want a complex
	ecosystem, an argument could be made that the complexity
	of the vessel (halls, different levels, etc.) make it
	effectively bigger than it is.  Also, if some parts of
	the vessel are cut off from others, different species
	might evolve in each (perhaps the separation was 
	temporary, just long enough to establish reproductively
	isolated populations).

>* These results imply that (within limits) planets with larger
>land masses should support more species and therefore more
>complex land ecosystems.

	I\'m not sure that the rules of island biogeography can be
	extended in this fashion.  Without going into a long-winded
	explanation, the complexity of the ecosystem around San
	Francisco has very little to do with how big eastern North
	America is.

>* There may be some utility in looking at all inhabited planets
>as "islands", and the Imperium or other interstellar state as an
>"archipelago". Sophonts are a transport mechanism, maintaining
>the diversity of small habitats by introducing new species or re-
>introducing old ones that threaten to die out.

	I would certainly expect that lots of species would invade
	new worlds, some might be well-known pests (like Terran
	rats).

>One feature of a Long Night would then be a massive die-off of
>small populations on isolated worlds, as they reach a new, lower
>equilibrium diversity. This would not happen overnight, of course.

	Terran history has seen numbers of species fluctuate rather
	widely, and the same would be expected of any biosphere.
	That being said, I wouldn\'t expect a noticable decline in
	the number of species (other than a few transient individuals
	around the starport) in any biosphere after the cessation of
	interstellar contact.  Worlds with restricted ecosystems (life
	only found in deep canyons, artificial domes, within a few km
	of the poles, etc.) might be an exception, but speciation/
	extinction rates tend to be VERY slow by human standards.

Peez
