    'ts-index' => '1999-11-08.ed561',
    'body' => '(I\'m sure this comes up at least twice a year, so sorry if I\'m bringing back 
an undead thread)

I tend to design support vehicles and starships for the sake of 
completeness. However, I run into a problem with Traveller; the primary role 
(or at least a major role) of an ARV (Armored Recovery Vehicle) is to take a 
damaged vehicle from where it was knocked out to where it can be effectively 
repaired. This usually isn\'t much of a problem with wheeled or tracked 
vehicles; as long as wheels or tracks or intact, you just tow it back.

This really doesn\'t work for grav vehicles, though, unless you want to drag 
them around on their underbodies. As I see it, there are three (well, four) 
possible recovery situations for a grav vehicle:

(1) contragravity units undamaged: If the vehicle still has power, it can 
activate the units and be towed normally by the ARV. If the disabled vehicle 
no longer has power, a power cable can be run from the ARV to a standard 
power socket on the disabled vehicle in order to power the contragravity 
units. The vehicle is then towed as above.

(2) contragravity units damage: This gets a little complicated. Even with 
power, the disabled vehicle is no longer capable of "lifting" itself. The 
best solution I see it that every AFV (Armored Fighting Vehicle) comes with 
external attachment points for emergency grav pods; these grav pods are just 
contragravity units with either a large rechargable battery (CG units tend 
to have pretty low power requirements) or a power socket for power cables 
coming from the ARV. The ARV would carry several emergency grav pods 
(probably enough to lift the heaviest vehicle the ARV was supposed to tow). 
For realism, the CG "lift" should be distributed around the disabled vehicle 
as evenly as possible. After the emergency grav pods are attached and 
activated, the AFV is towed as normal.

(3) AFV virtually destroyed: The vehicle has been disabled to the point to 
where it cannot be towed (there is a real risk that it may break apart in 
transit). If possible, a grav transport (basically a large grav flatbead 
truck) is brought in and the disabled vehicle is placed on the back (using 
CG pods and/or cranes). If the situation is too dangerous, the AFV strips 
what equipment it can, then uses demolition charges to prevent whatever is 
left from the AFV to fall into enemy hands.

(4) AFV self-mobile: The AFV can move on its own, but is damaged to the 
point where it is unlikely to return to base on its own. An ARV is sent to 
provide minor repairs (if possible) or towing (if neccessary).

A generous and sadistic GM,

Brandon Cope

