    'topic' => ' Coke for Kiri (OT)',
    'body' => 'On Mon, 8 Nov 1999 12:01:10 -0500 (EST), "Kiri Aradia Morgan"
<tiamat@tsoft.com> wrote:

>Thanks to everyone (Jeff was just one) who mailed me about this.

>I have just one question.  I can\'t read Hebrew.  How can I recognize what
>this looks like?

If you can recognize the fact that something is written in
Hebrew, that will be enough - the Coke cans don\'t have anything
in Hebrew on them UNLESS it\'s the Kosher for Passover (Kosher
l\'Pesach) stuff.

However, let me try to describe what the Hebrew looks like:

(N.B. Hebrew is read right-to-left.  The "first" letter of a word
is the one at the right end.)

The word "kosher" has three letters.  The first letter looks sort
of like a backward C, the second letter looks sort of like a W -
or maybe a Russian SH, and the third looks like a backwards
lower-case "r".

The word "Pesach" also has three letters - the first looks sort
of like a backward lower-case "e", the second looks like an "o"
with a little bit of a serif at the upper left, and the last
letter looks kind of like a vertically-elongated backward
lower-case "r".

However, the phrase is "kosher l\'pesach", which means I haven\'t
accounted for the "l\'".  That\'s attached to the beginning of the
second word, and it looks like a "7" with a tail rising from the
left end of the horizontal bar.  The tail may or may not be
folded back along the top bar, but either way, it will be
distinct.

I\'d try to do some bad ascii, but it\'d be worse than useless.

Pesach/Passover is usually around Easter, so look at the Coke
starting about a month before then.
- --
Jeff Zeitlin
jzeitlin@cyburban.com
