The list has been talking about academic styles, particularly in the
social sciences, of late.
    One could envisage two basic approaches to the problem of \'cognitive
science\' - the intersection of psychology, psionics and
neurophysiology.
    i. \'Lumping\' - under some (?flawed) unifying theory. Canon posits
that the physical basis of psionics remains unclear [?at less than
Ancient tech levels?], so psionicology may remain on a semi-mystical
footing, especially in the Consulate (instead of being forbidden
knowledge, like in the Imperium).
    ii. \'Splitting\' - data is gathered in each separate discipline. From
time to time, some genius arises who can link apparently disparate
findings.
    I would suspect that the situation is a dynamic one, where the
pendulum oscillates between these extremes with time.

and :-

