> need to know much at all about the rain forest, and didn\'t care - as
> long as he could cut down or pave over anything in his way. Simple
> wins over complex by making it simple.

Again, we *know* that the warpage gets pretty extreme anytime there\'s a
conflict between inner desires and outer behavior. Until and unless you
"fix" the *source* of the problem (as opposed to slapping more
behavioral restrictions on top) you are in effect tieing down the
safety valve on a steam engine, and then slapping patches on each joint
as it starts to leak. Eventually it blows up in your face.

Heck, look at our world. We\'ve got "mere" social and economic pressures
keeping people "in line". And yet we still have people "go postal".
Just *think* what a person with that much anger and hatred could do by
harnessing the resulting "drive" towards finding loopholes in the
commands. 

"Fulfill Your Assigned Tasks Quickly And Efficiently." is just *asking*
for a "rules lawyer" mindset to work on it. 

> Once a simple, reliable technique is developed for keeping the proles
> in line, will the Zhodani Tvarcheedle spend their resources working on
> a more complex technique that\'s nicer to the proles\' brains, or will they
> instead work on making the simple (though brutal) technique more
> effective and more efficient?

Anything that requires "mass conditioning" *can\'t* be simple or
efficient. The mere fact that you have to do it to *everyone* makes it
inefficient. And given the facts above, it\'ll lots of monitoring and
adjustment. 

