    'topic' => 're: Zhodani and Psionics',
    'body' => 'Robert O\'Connor wrote:
>>>>>>>>>>
Heck, no ; Skinnerian operant conditioning is predicated on a \'black
box\' model of the brain. Most RW cognitive-behavioural therapies have
their origins in operant conditioning.
(My apologies to any psychologists or psychiatrists on the list who
were taught at schools with alternate views).
>>>>>>>>>>
Combine a practical, no-nonsense approach to science with such
theories...and the Zhodani seem nothing of not practical.

"When we zot a prole\'s brain like *this*, he stops behaving like *that*.
We will therefore zot like *this* all proles that behave like *that*."

Granted, the Zho\'s have been at this a long time. The zot in question
may be very fine tuned, very sophisticated, and very effective - and yet
show no necessry understanding of the multiple processes being affected.

I put forth the possibility of Heisenberg effects in psionic therapy 
techniques - that by the act of investigating, you change what is
investigated. A proficient Zho may be able to root around deep inside
a brain, but the mental processes she will be looking at will not
necessarily be the same processes that would be going on if she
were not poking around in there.

Then there may be adepts with lighter "touches" or who have developed
less invasive techniques - kind of like the rain forest biologist who studies
while suspended from a far-off crane, never stepping on what he\'s 
investigating. If these techniques take longer to learn, are harder to do,
and have less reliable results, they may only be practiced by scientists
who have some strange ideas about Proles as some kind of equals to
Citizens. Of course, some Nobles need mental help as well...

To whit: just as taming or changing a rain forest does not necessarily
show an understanding of it, taming or changing a human mind - especially
if something simple like "peacable prole" was the end result desired - 
does not necessarily show knowledge of said mind, nor even interest
in workings of said mind.

I\'m considering the example from the original Zho aliens supplement,
where all the changes to the prole in question involved acceptance and
passivity. Those seem much less complex responses than any kind
of dynamic personality aspects that would make a person dangerous,
disruptive, or even interesting. Take the complex, make it simple and
easy to manage.

Walt Smith
