    'body' => 'GypsyComet wrote:
>>>>>>>>
 Er. The Proles get no vote at all. Just as with the Imperium, the common 
man gets some control, sometimes, over his immediate form of government, 
but the governance of the Consulate as a whole is determined top-to-bottom 
by the Nobility.
>>>>>>>>
The Proles get a "vote" by outnumbering the Nobles by several orders
of magnitude. They are induced by various means to "vote" not to 
overthrow the government, the mechanism of this vote is that they
do not overthrow the government.

All governments operate by consent of the governed. This consent may
be compelled by force, fear, or fraud, or gained through trust and good
stewardship, but the consent is still required. In the Zhodani society,
consent is in some ways impelled, by turning dissenters into supporters
whether the dissenter wants to or not.

Ever read John Christopher\'s "Tripods" series? Aliens come to Earth,
take over, and keep people in line by putting these mesh "caps" on
people, that keep their brains from thinking bad thoughts. The Zho\'s
make me think of that.

GypsyComet again:
>>>>>>>>>>
 Human psyche being what it is, the Tavrchedl\' will prefer adjustment 
techniques that will stand up under pressure, whether you view the 
Zhodani as benevolent or malevolent. If you have to re-adjust the same 
poor b----rd every few months because his job is stressful enough to 
shred the "life is simple" conditioning you stamped on his brain in three 
minutes, then you are very probably going to work on the twenty minute 
"good for a decade" technique just to keep the workload down. 
>>>>>>>>>>>>
Except that jobs with that kind of stress levels probably aren\'t performed
by simple proles. The high-stress jobs are done by the hosts of 
Intendants, out there trying to prove themselves in Zho society, or by
the Nobles. These people have entirely different worldviews than the
simple ones allowed to the proles. and will have very different coping
mechanisms.

Gypsy again:
>>>>>>>>>>>>
As suggested by the original Zhodani Module, this will often involve 
installing techniques and thought channels that help the person "deal"
more readily.
>>>>>>>>>>>>
"More readily" as in "in the way the Zho oligarchy wants him to deal
with it". Of course, that\'s what our societies intend with social 
conditioning, the benevolent Zho idea is that the Zho\'s are supposed
to have the information needed to be better at it.

The channels in the example all involved acceptance, passivity - 
simple responses, pretty much based on "THAT IS NOT A PROBLEM
TO YOU. IGNORE IT. BE HAPPY."

Walt Smith
