    'body' => 'Bruce Johnson wrote:
>>>>>>>>>
Have any of you _read_ the various Zhodani supplements?
>>>>>>>>>
I\'ve read the Aliens Supplement on them, and the bits mentioned in
the Library Data Supplement N-Z, and the mentions in MegaTraveller.
Beyond that, I\'m interpolating for the sheer entertainment value of it.

Bruce again:
>>>>>>>>>>>
What would be done with the poor b____d is that he\'d be moved into a job
more suited to his talents/limits. They\'re not bending peopel to fit the
job, but the jobs to fit the people.
>>>>>>>>>>>
That is in direct opposition to the one example (from the Zhodani aliens
supplement) of how the Tvarchedl "helps" a dissatisfied prole. He isn\'t
re-evaluated and moved to another job, his current role is accepted as
the right one and he is adjusted to be happier in it.

Bruce again:
>>>>>>>>>>>
There are people who are naturally more or less able to deal with stress;
they will be steered into the jobs that generate the stress. I can\'t think
of a job that someone, somewhere doesn\'t find enjoyable. 
>>>>>>>>>>>
I agree that the Zho should be better at putting people in jobs suited
to them. Now what happens when the needs of society (that is, the 
Nobles) doesn\'t require job types in the same proportions that people are
suited for? Do the Nobles change the list of needed jobs, or change
the people that are needed to do the job?

Bruce again:
>>>>>>>>>>
The Zhodani mind control, other than described in Impy agitprop, isn\'t
oriented so much to coerce behavior, as to find the best fit between prole
and life. Think of it as extremely effective, cradle-to-grave
psychotherapy, without all the California-style psychobabble bs.
>>>>>>>>>>
I think the truth is somewhere between "It\'s a round peg, we just need
to find a round hole" and "It\'s a peg, we can hit it hard enough to force
it into whatever hole we need to put it in". The last is a bit harder on the
peg, of course.

I\'ve always read the Tvarchedl\'s job as fixing people, instead of fixing 
people\'s lives. Of course, they are described as firefighters - they\'re
not handling the people who other arms of Zhodani gov\'t/society *did*
place properly in life, they\'re handling the ones that either needed
special help or are in some ways unhelpable.

Bruce again:
>>>>>>>>>>
Where is it stated or implied that proles have a limited world view? They
are limited in the positions they can attain, but by the time they\'re
adults, they _know_ it\'s because of their inherent limitations, not that
they\'re being \'denied\' a chance. They _like_ what they\'re doing and how
they live.
>>>>>>>>>>
Their limitations aren\'t inherent, their limitations are *imposed*. They
like what they\'re doing because the oligarchy wants them to like it,
and is capable of *making* them like it. Their goals are limited and
channeled by their masters, thus I see their worldview as limited.

I\'m not saying their society doesn\'t work, or is inherently evil. I don\'t
think I\'d want to live in it, and I\'d be leery of visiting it. I guess that
makes me a good Imperial citizen. :-)

Walt Smith
