    'body' => 'Hope you don\'t mind, but I\'ve corrected the spelling in the subject line.

Going for broke with an answer then. Evolutionary rates of change don\'t
depend on time as such (we have been around unchanged for about 50,000
years - around 2,500 generations). What it depends on is the rate of change
of nuclotide structure and both the selection pressure and the evolutionary
pressure on the organisms concerned. Together with the generation rate of
the organism, that will give you a rate of change due to evolutionary
selection. If you are interested in the maths, its fairly simple and I\'m
sure you can get it from most biology books. If you just want an example,
one follows.

Assume the ship is from Earth to Alpha Centuri and travels at an average of
0.1c including acceleration and deceleration at either end of the trip (so
takes 40 years to make the journey). Forty years is less than two full
generations for humans so people will still be people when they get there -
they may be socially strange, but they will be biologically fine, even if
there are many mutations in the children. Remember too that most mutations
die in the womb, so there are more likely to be only a few fully human
children and perhaps one or two mutations than anything else. On the other
hand, the hydroponics tank has been growing vegetables for forty generations
(one per year) assuming they grow from harvested seed rather than seed
brought from Earth. If the mutation rate is 10% (and that is massive) then
in the second generation one plant in ten will be a freak. If the selection
pressure (how many of the "normal" plants die) is also a massive 10%, then
the number of freaks is near enough one in nine. Even with the 90% failure
rate for mutations (and that is a low number) then we have one successful
freak for every ninety plants.

By the third year, maybe 19% of the plants would be mutations - but they may
not be successful. The evolutionary pressure (the number of possible ways to
make food and breed successfully) will decide how many of these are going to
breed next time. If the pressure is a massive 25% (which means there had to
be a serious disaster on the ship) then we will have just short of 5% of the
plants in the third year as freaks. At the end of the trip, there will be
new breeds of vegetables on board - provided the humans don\'t interfere (fat
chance).

Now the interesting bit. Those forty years amount to 350,000 generations for
the bacteria on board - more for the viruses brought by "accident" in the
crew and plants. Given that the changing environment around the ship gives
more opportunities to the bugs to breed, selection pressure will be low. On
the other hand, having lots of places and creatures to breed in means that
evolutionary pressure will be large. With the increased mutation rate, there
is plenty of time to develop new species (rather than new breeds, like the
plants).

So, after forty years, the ship lands and sows the original 100 species of
plants plus around 40 new breeds that have developed on the ship.
Unfortunately, the Saline Nutrient bacterium that developed in the
hydroponics system appears to have taken well in the shallow seas of the new
planets as does the Duct Virus that developed on the large colonies of soil
bacteria, similar to the skin bacterium Staph Aureus, in the life support
plant. People are still suffering from the Ship Flu that swept through
passenger cargo section three a few years ago. There are no midget people,
winged men, talking flowers or any of the other things I suspect you want.
To get those, we need to move the people into the same position as the
bacteria and, based on known human speciation, we need a journey of
approximately 30,000 years to see much change.

