Apparently the "Republican Issue" isn\'t quite over yet... it is still open
for debate and election issues in the future with members of near *all* the
political parties split on the subject.  Interestingly enough, our Queen has
nothing against us spreading our wings and leaving the Monarchy.

This may not sound the very best on my behalf, but I couldn\'t see a reason
to become a republic and don\'t care one way or the other.  As I understand
it, the referendum was lost because the template was for a "President" that
was elected by a few Aussie citizens (the politicians currently in power)
and not by a majority vote of the people.  But my reason for a no vote?  So
far, this has cost the Australian people over $2.5 million already!  Upon a
successful Republican vote it is estimated that the actual changeover costs
would be a further $7 million plus!!

Now call me foolish if you like, but I live in a city (town actually, but
hey) that the local hospital is so inadequately underfunded that there is
not a week that it is not mentioned in the local/state media somewhere, and
all it needs to become safe and workable again is a mere $0.5 million.  Then
there are things like schools (I am a father of 4) that would do well with a
small slice of this money too, not to mention roads, social security,
pensions, medical groups, research, etc.

Australia\'s head of state is the Queen of England.  Australia is self
governing however.  We do not pay taxes to the Royal Family or the U.K., we
decide to war or not war on behalf of the Queen (or the Americans for that
matter), she or her cabinet CANNOT compel Australia do this, nor can it make
Australia do ANYTHING Australia does not wish to do.  We get no aide from
the U.K., nor will we if we become a Republic.  Is there a special reason
for becoming a Republic other than cutting the "apron strings" which are
cosmetic anyway and do not do anything special in reality?

But more importantly to me... is there a way of becoming a Republic without
cost to the citizens/public?  Is this the sort of question that should be
asked of a [majority of] people that has already done so (their country
already become a Republic) of it\'s own accord, but for very different
reasons (taxes as opposed to prestige)?

ObTrav:  Will the Imperium take by force any system that wishes to leave
it\'s fold?  Are the systems that as independent, would still hold close ties
to the Empire and not be subject to force of compliancy?  Is there anything
canon about such worlds/systems?

