> iron age.  (Using the stuff found around the ship and worshiping the auto-repair
> system maybe.)

Part of that will depend on the original stock from which the race would
develop.  Using primates as an example, it would take much longer for
prosimians, such as lemurs, to develop into a sentient species than for
apes, such as gibbons or orangutans.

Since there are, AFAIK, no current reptiles that are more intelligent
than lemurs, I would expect at least 50 million years of evolution to be
required to develop a sentient reptilian race from current Terran
stock.  OTOH, given that some dinosaurs are said to have been as
intelligent as some apes, a sentient species could evolve from some of
the smarter dinosaurs in just a few million years.

Of course, given higher mutation rates than those found on Earth
(reasonably plausible on a generation ship), plus greater evolutionary
pressures (again, plausible on a relatively small, tight habitat such as
a generation ship), you could see a sentient species arise from a
relatively smart dinosauroid in maybe one million years or less.

My recommendation, if you want these reptilian sophonts to be of
original Terran stock, is to have them transplanted onto the ship by a
race that predates the Ancients by 60 million years or so, who would be
as much of a mystery to the Ancients (based on recovered fragments of
Ancient records) as the Ancients are to us.

If, OTOH, the original stock is unimportant, find an out-of-the-way
world that could support large lifeforms except for an atmospheric
taint, create a species that almost fits your needs (but is _not quite_
sentient), and have the ship be built by a now-dead race from that world
(that killed itself [and nearly everything else]) off with a virulent
bioweapon (the taint in question).  Your new race would evolve from a
clever beast that had some utility for the shipbuilder\'s race (beast of
burden, menial laborer, or what have you).  This allows you to introduce
not only a new sophont race, but also any alternative tech that you want
your players to find.

Obviously, the derelict ship in question would have to be large enough,
or automated enough, to support a pre-technological race in sufficient
numbers to allow the new race to develop.  As a wild guess, I would
think that you would need to support a population of two or three
million Saurians, since (having evolved on the ship) they would not have
easy access to the technological knowledge databases of the ship\'s
builders (who died out on the ship due to whatever handwave you choose).

Of course, you could also have your reptilian sophonts _be_ the
previously-thought-extinct race from the previously-mentioned now-dead
world.  In that case, even a few thousand years might suffice for them
to lose most of their technological knowledge.  As you said, they might
worship the auto-repair systems, that allow the ship to sustain them
without their own repair efforts.  If the ship is large enough, they can
even fragment into different tribes (based, perhaps, on the systems
found in the portions of the ship they occupy), with trade and/or
warfare between different tribes.  FWIW, this is my recommendation for
your new species.  They may no longer know that they are on a spaceship,
or that there was a world on which they evolved.  In fact, since all
other lifeforms on the ship would be from their native planet, they may
believe that they, and all other life aboard the ship, evolved on the
ship.

For some hints on how a reptilian sophont species might behave, check
out Harry Turtledove\'s "Worldwar" tetralogy....

