    'body' => 'From: cos 90 <cos90@powersurfr.com>


>All this talk about corporations and the various races in
>and around the 3I get me to wondering: what kind of cultural
>expressionism (ie, "the arts") will we find from the various
>races? What do Vilani paintings look like? (Do they even paint
>paintings?) What kind of music do Zhodani listen to? Are the
>arts in the Solomani Confederacy the state-supporting propaganda
>one found in the Eastern Bloc pre-1990 or in Nazi Germany?


Ha! Good question! It\'s a damn shame that there is no simple answer. Styles
can change quickly (even in pre-industrial societies). I mean, I could
rattle off the styles for quite some time that appeared from the Renaissance
to the modern day, and there would still be dozens, if not scores, that I\'d
be leaving out... and that would just be in the West!

Answering a question like "What do Vilani paintings look like?" is like
answering the question "What do Terran paintings look like?" There are few
similarities between cubism, pointilism, and neo-classicism, for example.
The same goes for other forms of art as well... sculpture, architecture,
fashion design, industrial design (compare the Atari 2600 to the Nintendo
64, for example, or a stereo made circa 1973 to one made in 1984 to one made
today), poetry, literature, film, theater...

My head is spinning.

Okay.

I did a piece for the Traveller culture list concerning one style of Vilani
painting, which I can try to dig up, and I\'ve got a few various tidbits of
cultural flavor on my webpage at http://www.pil.net/~semo , there\'s quite a
bit on the state of the Vilani music scene in the early 1100s.

There was a RICE paper article that detailed Aslan "Trokh Ofera" <sp>, Aslan
"talk opera". All in all a nifty idea. There was also a JTAS that detailed
K\'Kree scent-sculptures as part of an adventure. I\'m sure that there are
many more that I\'m forgetting.

>The only example IMTU that\'s come up is Vargr Opera, as one of
>the characters is a Vargr. We\'ve determined that Vargr opera
>is reminiscent of Klingon Opera from Star Trek, but with a lot
>more howling. ("Sparky", the Vargr engineer, has been told to
>stop playing it over the ship\'s loudspeakers -- or else.)
>
>Any other examples?


Okay, one off the top of my head:

Darmine Experiential Animation: A style once popular in the Darmine
Corporate during the long night, which has been acquiring some degree of
popularity in Daibei recently (circa 1105). An experiential animator will
connect to a device that keeps track of his pulse, body temperature,
movements, etc. and will use a special "keyboard" that allows him to express
concepts quickly that words cannot express (all manner of sensations). He
will then take / use / imbibe a mind-altering substance of some sort. A
special computer and software will transform the data it receives into
animation.

It\'s not terribly fleshed out. I\'d like to give it a little more in the way
of history, and I would like to give it one or more movements as well. It\'s
based on Leary and Alpert\'s "Experiential Typewriter."

This brings me to my next point: I\'m on Bruce Sterling\'s "Dead Media"
mailing list. The posts are very infrequent, *but* the collected notes are
an excellent resource for would be world builder types. I have the collected
notes from at least a year ago, if you poke around you should be able to
find a meatier file. There are plenty of interesting things in there that
you can graft into your Traveller universe.
