 Well, not in the past month. I have not internalized the G:T
book because I found things I plain hate, but I have done a
great deal of thinking about the Zhodani since becoming
the HIWG Sector Analyst (retired) for two Zhodani sectors
and helping on two others in the six+ years since.

>
>What would be done with the poor b____d is that he\'d be moved into a job
>more suited to his talents/limits. They\'re not bending peopel to fit the
>job, but the jobs to fit the people.

 This sort of activity has long been part of my take on the Tavrchedl\', 
actually, but I was specifically responding to the Brain Stamp theory.
 Before he left the hobby, an old friend and fellow Zhodani enthusiast and I 
posited the existence of a branch of the Tavrchedl\' that redirected the 
perpetually square-peg proles they found into fruitful work _somewhere_, 
often beyond the Consulate entirely. The Zhodani, through the efforts of the 
Tavrchedl\' and others, are very good at career placement when they have the 
manpower to do so. There are limits, however. A particular world economy may 
not have the wiggle room to shift everyone to jobs where they would be 
happiest, so adjusting the person instead is going to be a common occurance.

 To answer the obvious question, I am a "benevolent" Zhodani proponent. Such 
is required to have a functional society over six thousand years. The 
"malevelant" brain-sucking, Prole-enslaving Zhodani model is a good one for 
raw Space Opera enemies (who won\'t last more than a generation or two) 
because it is ideally suited to the "war-machine disguised as a functional 
society" type of state. If someone wants to use the Zhodani for that in their 
game that\'s fine, but don\'t try to convince me that it\'s true in the OTU.

