    'ts-index' => '1999-11-10.ed696',
    'date' => 'Wed, 10 Nov 1999 10:13:17  0500',
    'body' => 'Mark Preston writes:
<snipped>
>Evolutionary rates of change don\'t depend on time as such (we
>have been around unchanged for about 50,000 years - around 2,500
generations). What it depends on is the rate of change of nuclotide
>structure and both the selection pressure and the evolutionary
>pressure on the organisms concerned. Together with the generation
>rate of the organism, that will give you a rate of change due to
>evolutionary selection.

	That\'s not a bad description, but just to clarify: organic
	evolution can be defined as a change in gene frequency over
	time. It\'s "rate" may be defined in a number of ways, but
	the most useful here would be the change in the average value
	of a given trait (such as the length of the legs) in a
	given time span (say 100 years). This rate will depend on the
	strength of natural selection (how strong is the relationship
	between the trait and the organism\'s ability to reproduce?)
	,the genetic variance of the trait (how much variation is
	there in that trait that is caused by genes?), and the
	generation time (how many generations have passed in the 100
	years?).

<snipped>
>Forty years is less than two full generations for humans so people
>will still be people when they get there - they may be socially
>strange, but they will be biologically fine, even if there are
>many mutations in the children. Remember too that most mutations
>die in the womb, so there are more likely to be only a few fully
>human children and perhaps one or two mutations than anything else.

	A note about mutations: on average, each human on Terra has
	about two new mutations. That is, it has been estimated that
	each of us (on average) has two detectable genes that are
	different than any that our parents had. Even without
	considering this source of genetic variation, virtually every
	trait that has been studied has had at least some genetic
	variation, that is when artificial selection has been imposed
	evolution has occured.

>On the other hand, the hydroponics tank has been growing
>vegetables for forty generations (one per year) assuming they
>grow from harvested seed rather than seed brought from Earth.

	One generation per year sounds pretty low, depending on
	the plant. If I wanted carrots out of my hydroponics,
	I would choose fast-growing varieties and manipulate
	conditions so that there were far shorter generations
	(perhaps as low as a month with constant light, ideal
	temperatures, etc.).

>If the mutation rate is 10% (and that is massive) then in the
>second generation one plant in ten will be a freak. If the
>selection pressure (how many of the "normal" plants die) is also
>a massive 10%, then the number of freaks is near enough one in
>nine. Even with the 90% failure rate for mutations (and that is a
>low number) then we have one successful freak for every ninety
>plants.

	Of course, the ship may have unusually high radiation
	or chemical mutagen levels for one reason or another, but
	evolution is not thought to proceed by large mutations that
	produce "freaks." The generally accepted view is that small
	variations in traits are favoured incrimentally. Note that
	this mechanism has been observed in the lab to produce
	rates of evolution far higher than those observed in the
	fossil record.

>By the third year, maybe 19% of the plants would be mutations -
>but they may not be successful. The evolutionary pressure (the
>number of possible ways to make food and breed successfully) will
>decide how many of these are going to breed next time.

	If we are dealing with a major mutation, the important
	factor will be whether it is any better than it\'s buddies
	at reproducing. Major mutations are considered unlikely to
	have such an advantage, but perhaps one could be invoked
	to make one of the new species that the GM wants.

>If the pressure is a massive 25% (which means there had to be a
>serious disaster on the ship) then we will have just short of 5%
>of the plants in the third year as freaks. At the end of the trip,
>there will be new breeds of vegetables on board - provided the
>humans don\'t interfere (fat chance).

	Perhaps Darwin\'s most important observation was that many
	more organisms are produced than can possibly survive. If you
	mean by a "pressure" of 25% that 25% of the plants die, then
	I would suggest that mortality is unusually low. Typically,
	the vast majority of offspring that plants produce never live
	to maturity. You are quite correct, however, that the level
	of mortality is important: high mortality is a good
	opportunity for selection to act. As for the humans
	interfering, I don\'t think that there were any left alive
	on the ship.

>Now the interesting bit. Those forty years amount to 350,000
>generations for the bacteria on board - more for the viruses
>brought by "accident" in the crew and plants. Given that the
>changing environment around the ship gives more opportunities to
>the bugs to breed, selection pressure will be low. On the other
>hand, having lots of places and creatures to breed in means that
evolutionary pressure will be large. With the increased mutation
>rate, there is plenty of time to develop new species (rather than
>new breeds, like the plants).
<snipped>

	The distinction between species and breeds is difficult to
	make in many organisms, particularly bacteria. Nevertheless,
	it is true that bacteria would have plenty of opportunity to
	evolve.

Peez
