    'topic' => ' Cultures (WAS Evolution...) Longish',
    'body' => 'Black ICE writes:
>Shimmergloom wrote:
>>Well, the setting is non canon, so the 30,000 years is no
>>problem.  But I try to avoid over using the Ancients so they
>>don\'t get boring to the players.  I mainly wanted to know ho
>>long it might take for evolution to produce a new sophant
>>species on the ship so I could judge how long to have the ship
>>floating in space.  The species I have in mind are a tribe of
>>reptiles that are roughly late iron age.  (Using the stuff found
>>around the ship and worshiping the auto-repair system maybe.)

	I hate to stick in the Ancients all over the place, but
	30,000 years is a long time to provide heat, light, etc.
	on a non-Ancient ship. As for time to evolve intelligence,
	it has been between 3 and 5 million years since we shared
	a (presumably non-sophont) common ancestor with chimps. Of
	course, we have been sophonts for a long time, maybe
	millions of years.

>Part of that will depend on the original stock from which the
>race would develop.  Using primates as an example, it would take
>much longer for prosimians, such as lemurs, to develop into a
>sentient species than for apes, such as gibbons or orangutans.
<snipped>

	Certainly evolution works with what you\'ve got to start with.
	If there was a relatively intelligent reptile on board to
	start with, it would help things along (say a pet with dog-
	like or even better Int).

<some good ideas snipped>
>Obviously, the derelict ship in question would have to be large
>enough, or automated enough, to support a pre-technological race
>in sufficient numbers to allow the new race to develop.  As a wild
>guess, I would think that you would need to support a population
>of two or three million Saurians, since (having evolved on the ship)
>they would not have easy access to the technological knowledge
>databases of the ship\'s builders (who died out on the ship due to
>whatever handwave you choose).

	I\'m not sure I follow here. With minimal handwaving, I would
	think that you could get away with a few thousand sophonts
	(or even less, if you really had to). I can imagine rather
	small creatures with short generations and a lot of resistance
	to inbreeding. If the mutation rate was high enough, the small
	population would help keep a high rate of evolution (though
	a new species of sophonts in a few thousand years would still
	require the waving of a manipulative limb).

<snipped>
>They may no longer know that they are on a spaceship, or that
>there was a world on which they evolved.  In fact, since all other
>lifeforms on the ship would be from their native planet, they may
>believe that they, and all other life aboard the ship, evolved on
>the ship.
<snipped>

	Anyone remember the cheesy sci-fi about the humans on the Arc?

