    'date' => 'Wed, 10 Nov 1999 12:54:38 PST',
    'body' => '>From: Robert Conley <estar@toolcity.net>
>
>Why do we need a separate vechile. Why can\'t we have a control module, and
>a series of standard grav lift modules of which are self powered.
>that you attach to the disabled vechile. The whole thing is controlled by
>wireless communication. You can use standard g cargo carriers to transport
>the modules and the recovery crew out to the disabled vechile site.

Current recovery vehicles are also designed to do repairs in the field 
(changing engines, gun barrels, etc.). That is, an ARV is supposed to fix a 
vehicle in the field if it can, tow it back to a repair base if it can\'t. A 
vehicle designed solely to lift a disabled vehicle (and not repair it) is 
not very cost effective, unless you have only a few issued per army and use 
normal ARVs for the bulk of recovery/repair work.

A generous and sadistic GM,

Brandon Cope

