    'body' => '>From: Sethkimmel@aol.com

>I HATE the whole social history movement. While I 
>think it\'s very important to study the "little 
>man/woman" to get the whole picture of history, 
>I reject the notion that one shouldn\'t study the 
>movers and shakers (i.e., the rulers, leaders, etc.).


Seth, I think that you and I are largely in agreement,
at least as stated in the second sentence.  I
disagree, however, that 

>The problem with social history, is that until
> democracy, the little man/woman didn\'t DO a whole
> hell of a lot. It\'s more interesting to study 
> the leaders.

In fact, what ordinary people were doing, were wanting
to do, were lacking, etc., is the necessary background
to understanding the leaders themselves at any given
point in time.  To take an example from way back in
time, Moses may have convinced Pharoah to free the
slaves, but the slaves themselves were of substantial,
if not critical, importance to the Egyptian economy --
which was at least one reason for Pharoah to harden
his heart against letting the people go. 

- --Glenn


