    'from' => 'Glenn Goffin gmgoffin@yahoo.com',
    'body' => '>From: "Terry Carlino" <carlino@home.com>

>What about different sets of laws for citizens and 
>non-citizens. In the U.S. (barring certain special 
>rules applied under immigration laws) anyone within
>the country is subject to the same laws ... 
[deletion]
>This is not necessarily a requirement. The Romans had

>one set of laws for citizens and another for non-
>citizens. Is this the case in the Imperium? Do
>some laws only apply to the nobility, in both a 
>negative and a positive sense?

Well, the Imperium is of course a crazy hodge-podge of
local laws, so anything can happen on member states. 
Imperial law in my Traveller universe has two major
divisions, general laws and the laws applicable only
to Imperial nobles.  Everybody -- commoners, nobles,
and corporations -- is subject to the general laws. 
The laws applicable only to nobles include special tax
reporting, regulation of styles of address, sumptuary
laws, etc.  

So in my Traveller universe, if the Duke and a
commoner conspired to steal from the Emperor, they
would both be guilty of lese-majeste and conspiracy to
commit theft.  The prosecutor would likely also charge
them with treason, but I\'m not sure that charge would
stick; it would depend on what they were stealing, and
for what purpose.  (The Imperial Sceptre:  treason for
sure; a hand-made jewel-encrusted gold dining table
commissioned by the Emperor from artisans on Menorb: 
probably not treason.)  

- --Glenn

