    'body' => '>>         Anyone remember the cheesy sci-fi about the humans on the Arc?
>
>Earthship Ark.  Had an actor that was later Chekov (SP?) didn\'t it?

The series you\'re referring to is called The Starlost, a Canadian-produced
series from around 1973. It was awful. (Most Canadian-produced TV was awful
back then...).  The series was about three young people aboard a great big 
huge starship, Earthship Ark, which was sent into space in response to some 
kind of disaster back on Earth (I\'m not sure we ever find out just what kind 
of disaster it was.) The ship consisted of several dozen "biospheres" all
connected to a central "core" shaft that was probably at least 100 miles 
long...

Anyway, several hundred years later, the inhabitants of one of the biospheres,
a low-tech agrarian community, have for some reason forgotten that they are
on board a spaceship. Three young people from the biosphere manage to find 
the exit into the rest of the ship and go exploring, and discover that they 
are in fact aboard a great big huge spaceship -- and that the spaceship is
no longer under anyone\'s control and is on a collision course with a nearby
star. The series had our intrepid trio going from one biosphere to the next
looking for someone who knew how to regain control of the ship and avert the
collision.

(Most of this is from memory, as it\'s been a couple of decades since I\'ve
seen it...)

A few bits of trivia about the series:
- - It was created by Harlan Ellison, who when he saw how bad the result was
asked for his name to be removed from the credits; the credits list the
series creator as "Cordwainer Bird", an Ellison pseudonym.
- - The star of the series was Keir Dullea, star of 2001 A Space Odyssey.
- - Co-star Robin Ward\'s voice can be heard narrating the second Twilight
Zone series, seen here and there in syndication. (This TZ series is the
one produced in the late 1980s.)
- - Walter Koenig appeared in two episodes as Oro, an alien who finds the
Ark and for some reason decides not to help. Had the series continued
into a second season, Oro would likely have appeared in a few more episodes.
Since this was 1973, this was after his work on the original Star Trek
series.

This was a *bad* series, boys and girls. I keep hoping that Space, Canada\'s
cable SF channel, will pick it up...


     Glenn St-Germain  Edmonton, Alberta, Canada 
