    'month' => '11',
    'body' => '(I am not going to continue a non-Traveller discussion here. I just 
won\'t let people think that such comments are welcomed by all - I 
want them Off-list). Now, On Topic...

> >Does anyone have any firm anti-violence groups active in their 
> >Traveller universe? What d they do? How does the Imperium 
> >see them?
> >Terry 

In my 3I (which I do not use much since I moved the area of play 
Beyond The Extents), Delphi sector was heavily colonized by terrans 
of asian origin. This gave a special twist to the later high 
corporate influence in Margaret\'s Stronghold during the Rebellion.

During an old FTF adventure, I introduced a pacifist movement 
following (partly) in spirit Yukio Mishima\'s ideas, vaguely linked 
to buddist religion. An Army without more weapons that those used for 
ritual suicide, willing to die but not to kill, with the firm belief 
that nobody has the right to take one life, except the own. They were 
called "Life Fighters" or "Mishimans."

They were sort of a peaceful resistance against the 
growing corporate power. Their ritual, spectacular suicides as 
protest for specific corporate acts (like causing planetary wars to 
control mineral resources) received a disproportionate media coverage 
and caused negative demand reactions among the consumers, eventually 
forcing the corporations to pay attention to the movement.

Some of their leaders made it into Margaret\'s counsel, which gave her 
some politically acceptable excuses for her retreat policy (which was 
actually caused by her focus in economics and ignorance of any 
military art).

They broke with Margaret after the Geoneecide, at the beginning of 
Hard Times, when Margaret\'s followers started hunting down Geonee.

Carlos Alos-Ferrer
