> The Starlost, an extremely low-budget Canadian sci-fi TV series which 
> came out in 1973, after Star Trek. Walter Koenig was in several 
> episodes.
>
> I can understand why you thought it came out before Star Trek; the 
> effects were so primitive it looks like something made by a 
> high-school drama class.
>
> This program was the result of some hard work by eastern Canadian 
> sci-fi fans, who got Harlan Ellison to write the pilot and Douglas 
> Trumbull to produce it. Unfortunately, the budget could not meet 
> Ellison\'s vision for the series and he disavowed it. He even demanded 
> they change his name in the credits to "Cordwainer Bird".

A standard Ellison response when his scripts get *really* screwed over.
He "gives them the Bird". Many SF writers who work with TV and movie
scripts have a registered psuedonym for such cases. I believe that
David Gerrold\'s is "Noah Ward" (No Award:-).

> I remember reading an essay from someone involved with the series. 
> The budget constraints and clueless management were so extreme it was 
> funny. Ellison was in a huge argument with a "professional" 
> (non-sci-fi) writer who thought a "backup computer" was something 
> that made the spaceship fly in reverse.

There were other howlers. Things like saying the domes were only three
miles across. Harlan pointed out that if they were only three miles
across, then the people looking for Our Hero in the pilot episode
merely have to link hands and walk from one side to the other to locate
him. They told him the special effects people can\'t make it look more
than 3 miles across. So he tells them, fine, let them do their best but
you can still *say* it\'s 30 miles across! They went with 3.

Also, the original idea was for the kids to be trying to find the
Bridge. Which could take a long time in a ship that size. 

Instead, the producers had them find the bridge in the *pilot*,
discover it wasn\'t working and then having search for the emergency
bridge. 

Beside the fact that there\'s no good reason to have them find the
bridge so soon, there\'s the "minor" detail that if *anyplace* on the
ship would have directions to the backup bridge, it\'d be the primary
bridge! 

There was a book published "Phoenix without Ashes" that has the
original script plus Harlan\'s account of the trials and tribulations of
trying to get it filmed. It\'s worth reading. 

But in essence, most of the problems came down to the usual. Media
people just not understanding that SF is *not* fantasy. That things
have to have an internal logic *and follow that logic!*

