    'index' => 'ed779',
    'month' => '11',
    'body' => 'Robert Eaglestone writes:
<snipped>
>Suppose you want to give your players the creeps?  Send
>shivers up their spine?  Worry the PCs to no end?
>
>How do you set it up?

	Slowly.  I find that creepiness is best built up by
	small incriments, with the realization that something
	is VERY wrong only slowly coming to the PCs.

>What factors do you have to think about?

	Avoid open combat of any sort.  PCs always feel better
	after they\'ve blown away some bad guys, but if they have
	drawn weapons several times without firing a shot they
	may begin to get antsy.

<snipped>
>Government cover-ups; megacorps crossing the line into
>dark experiments; medicines that create horrors; rumors
>and uncertainty about the Ancients and the Solomani
>Hypothesis; the Imperial Department of War... how does
>one fit things like these together into a coherent scenario
>that starts innocuously and turns into a monster of a situation?

	I would start with something totally bizarre and gross
	(don\'t underestimate the power of making your PCs go 
	"Eewww!"), and then built layers of scheming, deceit,
	and bad intent.  The upper layer may be merely a cover-up
	of some money-making scheme, which the PCs may get involved
	with (one way or another).  Getting in deeper, they may
	realize that the scheme is connected with a slavery ring,
	which is selling the occasional sophont to a laboratory,
	which is really a front for a "satanic" cult, which are
	being duped by nasties with Ancient\'s technology, who are
	actually evil mind-sucking spiders from another domension
	plotting to turn all living things into cattle!  Aha! Ha! Ha!

	Ahem.  Yes, well, and don\'t forget parasites.  PCs hate
	parasites.

Peez
