dizzying assortment of art forms including 2D, 3D and maybe
higher-dimensional art in the form of isographic holograms and so on.  But
that answer is not very helpful, so let me come up with a few funky
things that could be thrown into the TU:

	Terraforming as Art:  This would be the high TL equivalent of
those giant sculptures and modern art projects where they modify
landscapes.  Sponsored by gigacredit art endowments, these art projects
modify coastlines with giant dams and/or canals, adjust the color of local
plant life by introducing genetically engineered viruses and so on.  Ice
caps are melted into fun new shapes with plasma torches, fast-growing
algea lend color to oceans, and so on.  Mostly done on low-population
worlds.  Smaller scale projects modify only a continent or sea, but the
result is usually visible from orbit.

	Genetics as Art:  Highly illegal in the 3I, but practiced in less
anti-biotech areas is the practice of creating new and interesting
creatures as art.  One could make a genuine chimera or dragon or...other
things...<:-o A side possibility here is recreating "real life" versions
of famous artworks, including genuine burning giraffes, melting clocks or
whatever (That last is stolen from a story by Greg Egan :-) 

	Gravitics as Art:  Getting into less controversial territory,
gravitics should have a major impact on art and architecture with
"impossible" buildings (a la Escher), ominously suspended masses and
oscillating fleets of sculpture elements. Canonically, Darrian flame
sculpture is supposed to make use of gravitics (although personally I
consider that to be a nouveau-school fad :-). 
	
Just some ideas...

Charles C.	
