> >Suppose you want to give your players the creeps?  Send
> >shivers up their spine?  Worry the PCs to no end?
> >
> >How do you set it up?
> 
	[Steve replied]  Always, always, always do stuff that makes the
players start to look askance at each other, as well.
	There are a number of things you can do IRL that heighten this,
without the players really realizing what\'s the real thing.
	(Note - in the instances where I\'ve managed to pull it off,
invariably these are ONE SESSION gaming affairs - if you give the players a
chance to chat amongst themselves, you end up losing a lot of the atmosphere
you\'ve worked hard to engender...)

	1) seperate the group - put small groups or better individuals on
their own in the adventure, and therefore keep them in seperate rooms, and
just move frequently, dm\'ing each person alone.   keep it simple and fast or
you\'ll have boredom more than fear.
	2) plant clues that make the characters suspicious of one another -
in the game, of course; but also in real life - leave a little note saying
"The contact gives you John\'s service record and a bunch of photographs"
somwhere where John\'s player will find it.  That led to more backbiting and
suspicion than I could have ever created as a DM.
	3) never understimate the power of your player\'s imaginations.  Have
stuff happen if it\'s cool - don\'t bother to even TRY explaining it.  They\'ll
invariably come up with a plausible explanation that fits the facts.  Then
throw a curve at them that wrecks their assumptions.  :)
