  {
    'topic' => ' How to do a gritty, X-Files-like scenario?',
    'index' => 'ed803',
    'month' => '11',
    'body' => '>Suppose you want to give your players the creeps? [...]
>How do you set it up?  What factors do you have to think
>about?

Uncertainty and powerlessness. These are the two variables from which
horror springs.

Start normally. Try not to let your players know you are going to run a
horror scenario. Instead, run one of the other normal Traveller campaigns
for the first couple of sessions. Have the PCs develop their skills and
make friends with NPCs, so that they develop a sense that they know how the
universe works.

Then, when things begin to get strange, put them in situations where their
skills and friends are simply inadequate to fully deal with the situation.
You probably don\'t want the PCs to be *totally* helpless; rather, you want
them to be thwarted in resolving the situation to *their* satisfaction.

You should also isolate them, so that they have nowhere to turn for help.
This does not need to be simple physical isolation (although that works).
It can also be social isolation -- no one is willing to believe them, much
less help them.

Here are the four maxims to keep in mind when setting up an atmosphere of
horror. These are what you want your players to eventually realize:

1. Things are not as they seem.
2. These things are beyond your control.
3. Worse, you don\'t even know half of it.
4. And nobody believes you when you mention what you *do* know.

Oops, have to get back to work!

Ciao,

Joseph R. Dietrich
