    'topic' => 'Scriptwriting (was:  Cultures)',
    'body' => 'Dear Folks -

Leonard said:
>But in essence, most of the problems came down to the usual. Media
>people just not understanding that SF is *not* fantasy. That things
>have to have an internal logic *and follow that logic!*

Not just SF. Very few shows that contain "super-heroes" have good scripts,
either. "The Flash" (forex) had good SPFX and a fantastic costume, but the
writers all seemed to have their brains removed before putting pen to paper.
They just don\'t seem to realise that the main suspension of disbelief is to do
with the character themselves and their powers. Beyond that, everything else
should work "normally" - otherwise it looks *too* silly.

Plot is the most important element after character.(##)

The correct places to put special effects are as part of the background
environment and as the gloss added later, to remind the viewer that this is a
different world. The "gosh-wow effect" cannot sustain a story.

This was forgotten in things like "Star Trek: The Movie" and TV series such as
"The Flash", "Superboy", "Lois and Clark" (mostly) - there are many others.

The ones that worked were things like "Wrath of Khan", the "Star Trek: TNG"
series (mostly) and (interestingly) "The Greatest American Hero".

(##)...applies to the creation of good roleplaying scenarios, too...
