>Your protestor might be seen as a martyr, but most sane people realize that
>running in front of a squad involved in a firefight is a dumb thing, and
>will react accordingly.

Maybe, maybe not.

Remember Ghandi\'s protest against the Salt Tax in India?  Protesters
marched up to be beaten by the British police.

I think a key point here is giving the firefight time to stop. If you dash
in front of a weapon in full autofire, you probably get shot even if the
soldier tries to miss you. But if your group slowly marches between the
fighters, giving them plenty of time to stop shooting, so that it is
obvious that any casualties to the protesters are the result of deliberate
shots (or really negligent troops)...

It\'s risky, admittedly, but it does demonstrate great personal commitment
to stopping the violence.

Whether it would work or not depends a great deal on the philosophical
nature of that world\'s socity.
