    'index' => 'ed817',
    'body' => 'Robert Eaglestone wrote:
> Suppose you want to give your players the creeps?  Send
> shivers up their spine?  Worry the PCs to no end?

Just suppose, huh? Just a hypothetical question? You wouldn\'t do such a
thing? Ever? :-)

Speaking as a GM/referee of horror games (my primary genre)... I do this
kind of stuff a lot :-)

> How do you set it up?  What factors do you have to think
> about?  Likely it is some version of the Enigma, with some
> of The Push in it, right?  But vague categories don\'t help me
> very much.  I\'m asking for inspiration.

First of all, consider the room you play in. Use it to your advantage.
In other words, if the light suddenly goes out in the scenario, do the
same in the room. It helps if you can get close to the light switch
without the players realizing what you are about to do. See below.

Walk about the room when talking to the players. Talk in a low, soft
voice. Always hint at some conspiracy for mostly everything that happens
("The bus driver looks at you for perhaps a second to long"). Pay
attention to details. Many of the details you describe during the
session will have no impact. One or two will be important. If you
describe several things detailed, the players won\'t see the label HINT
pasted to the important stuff.

> Government cover-ups; megacorps crossing the line into
> dark experiments; medicines that create horrors; rumors
> and uncertainty about the Ancients and the Solomani
> Hypothesis; the Imperial Department of War... how does
> one fit things like these together into a coherent scenario
> that starts innocuously and turns into a monster of a situation?

Now for the actual story stuff. I just got a really nice idea. ;-)

The PCs are hired by a large corporation to take some "medical supplies
in sealed containers" to a research station somewhere Far Away (TM).
They get paid tons of credits, but are ordered to keep the fact that
they are working for the company secret.

When the ship gets to the destination, they find out that the container
handling equipment at the base is broken. The container will have to be
split inside the cargo hold, and the smaller cases inside will have to
be unloaded separately. If the ship has it\'s own cargo handling
equipment, the container has to be split in the hangar anyway.

Inside the container are several boxes about 2.5x1.0x0.5 meters. They
have some electronics attached to them, and look suspiciously like low
berths. They just might contain human bodies... (think Aliens:
Ressurrection)

By now, the PCs are probably wondering what\'s happening. As the last
cases are being transported out of the hangar using an old four-wheeler
of some kind, the PCs recieve their payment from an officer. Suddenly,
one of the cases crashes to the ground. The plastic breaks, and a
something shows through. A human hand. The officer rushes the PCs into
their ship, adds about 25% or so to their payment, gives them a warning
look, and leaves. They are more or less ordered to leave the station as
soon as possible.

After this, a number of things could happen. If the PCs go to some kind
of bigger media, they won\'t be believed. If they go to smaller, more
honest media, or perhaps seek rumors in bars or somesuch, they will hear
rumors of horrible experiments...

In any case, no matter if they talk about the affair or not, the officer
that paid the PCs will regret (after orders/threats from his superiors)
that he let them go. Agents of the corporation will begin to look for
the PCs. Depending on how public they have made themselves, they will be
more or less easy to find...

So, as the PCs try to uncover the Truth behind this conspiracy,
stretching over perhaps more than a subsector, agents of the corporation
constantly are at their tails. Almost no one believes them, and the ones
that do are either bought off or disappear without a trace. What to do?

Take that idea and go from there. It might be what you were looking for.
I think I am going to use it myself :-)

/Jens \'Spacejens\' Rydholm
