    'body' => 'At 12:32 PM 11/11/1999 EST, you wrote:
>In honor of Veterans/Remembrance Day (and a way to bring this flame back to 
>Traveller), I have compiled a list of Veterans organizations in the third 
>Imperium:

<snip very good list>

In Ground Forces, I am writing about the various Regimental Associations,
which I see as the equivalent of the American Legion or Veterans of Foreign
Wars.

Current or former members of a particular Regiment may join the associated
Regimental Association.  Sometimes little more than a dusty hall for
veterans to meet in and swap stories, the Associations can be a valuable
source of information about the past exploits of the unit.

Some Associations, particular those of the larger or more famous Regiments,
can wield enormous power.  The back-channel deals and contacts made at
monthly meetings can either expedite or severely hinder projects, based on
the desire of those in the Association.

Associations also function as charitable organizations.  The groups raise
funds to assist local communities by building playgrounds, establishing
scholarships, and other good works.  In this aspect, the Association
provides good public relations for the actual Regiment, which may be light
years from it\'s home territory.  Association members also act as
historians, compiling extensive records of the regiment and it\'s members.

Membership in a Regimental Association costs Cr. 200/year, on the average.
Fees for some of the more prestigious associations can be much higher.
Dues may be waved for members for reason of disability or at the agreement
of the board.  Recipients of the Starburst for Extreme Heroism tend to have
honorary membership bestowed upon them.

The most famous of the Regimental Associations is the Veterans of The
Matriarch\'s Own Cavalry, on Mora.  The Association was granted a large
atoll in the southern hemisphere, which is used as a private resort by the
Regiment\'s five battalions.

In game terms, membership can be seen as either Contacts (B234) or a
5-point Claim to Hospitality for wealthier groups.  In neither case will
the Association appreciate being constantly badgered for information, or
putting up with extra guests who were not members of the Regiment.
