I would doubt it very much. It should be remembered that our own cultures
focus on a day of rememberance is a direct product of the most traumatic
war in history (note the days choosen). Before the 1st WW there were
no specific national days of rememberance. And the 3rd Imperium has
never suffered anything even remotely as traumatic as the 1st WW. Just
to drive home the point a few numbers about the 1st WW might be in order.

Total number of men mobilised - 65,000,000 (12% of population)
Number of men killed - 8,550,000 (13% of mobilised)
Number of men wounded - 21,220,000 (33% of mobilised)
Number of men POW or Missing - 7,750,000 (12% of mobilised)

Now those figures only go part way to describing the traumatic effects of
the 1st WW; but to translate them across the Imperium you would need
to have tens of billions killed in a single war. Perhaps the Rebellion might
cut it, but that would be the only war that would even come close.



