First off, you have to convince the players that you are willing to kill
them.
If neccessary, that means doing so, preferrably in extremely graphic and
detailed goriness.

Get past the "oh shit, I\'ve been shot, where\'s the autodoc ?" stage, make
them _feel_ the wounds.

Hit them with something familiar, like the set up for "Aliens", encourage
them to think you\'ve recycled the plot, and then have something happen that
is clearly impossible ( given their current knowledge ). Preferably
something nasty that will make them want to mount a 24hr guard, and not
trust their automatics. The first killing from "Forbidden Planet" comes to
mind.

Read "Silence of the Lambs".  Would you like to be a cop in a building
knowing that Lector is loose and hunting ?

Read "The Vang : the Military Form" (or "The Battlemaster")

Read "The Legacy of Heorot"

Isolate the players. (a ship in jump, no way to get out until jump ends. On
an asteroid station waiting for the next ship. In a habitat where "outside"
is deadly to humans...)

Read "The Jesus Incident". Nerve Runners, \'nuff said.

Kill their technilogical advantage ( The power station goes critical, it has
to be shut down. There\'s a virus in the computer must be shut down, won\'t
have control for the two hours it takes to reboot the ships systems. The
enemy is invisible to their sensors....)

Make them paranoid. ( Leave hints that it\'s one of the players that\'s
responsible for the badness, especiallly if it isn\'t.  Make it seem the
enemy can "walk through walls". Enemy is "super-genius", it will outthink
anything you do....)

Make it obvious the Enemy is playing with them. ( Do the scene where the
Grendel comes across the hero strapped down in the medical tent, or from
Alien 3 where the alien leaves Ripley alone (because she is a queen.....)

Damage your characters. They are wounded, no likelihood of healing, no
autodocs, no antibiotics, lots of fungi around.....

Read "The Jester at Scar"

Talk about diseases that eat the flesh off your thigh in thirty seconds

Watch "Millenium"

Then, light the room properly.

Create NPC\'s that have strange habits and speech patterns, and don\'t  seem
"all there"

"Renfield" from "Dracula" is a good example.

Have all your NPC\'s act scared of something, but none of them wil talk to
the players about it.
Have them die in gory ways while saying something cryptic and foreboding

"It\'s too late, _they_ are loose !" _croak_



Have an otherwise staunch military type hang himself rather than face what\'s
"out there"
(Stephen King story, "The Fog "? "



































