    'topic' => ' How to do a gritty, X-Files-like scenario?',
    'body' => 'At 07:52 AM 11/11/99 -0600, you wrote:
>Howdy folks, time for a question.
>
>Suppose you want to give your players the creeps?  Send
>shivers up their spine?  Worry the PCs to no end?
>
>How do you set it up?  What factors do you have to think
>about?  Likely it is some version of the Enigma, with some
>of The Push in it, right?  But vague categories don\'t help me
>very much.  I\'m asking for inspiration.
>
>Government cover-ups; megacorps crossing the line into
>dark experiments; medicines that create horrors; rumors
>and uncertainty about the Ancients and the Solomani
>Hypothesis; the Imperial Department of War... how does
>one fit things like these together into a coherent scenario
>that starts innocuously and turns into a monster of a situation?
>
>Thanks!
>
>Rob
>

        Hi, Rob!

        IMHO, the trick is BE PATIENT.  As a Ref, that is.  There is a real
tendency to want to get the players hip-to-neck-deep as quick as possible.
It doesn\'t work, because the players don\'t have to think.

        I ran a concept game like this in Cyberpunk sometime ago...  I used
the "Countdown" concept...  As in "10, 9, 8..."  Each digit represents the
number of adventures/ scenarios between those which have something to do
with the Grand Conspiracy.  Now, I tend to run two-or-three session
adventures;  adjust timings to taste.  In Traveller, for my first FTF TNEC
game, I ran _Shadows_ as part of the Conspiracy.  The Scout took some
samples of the flora that was growing in that horrendous atmosphere.  Took
\'em back to the local Scout Base for analysis.  The took one look at them,
their logbooks and siezed the logs, recorder data, samples, everything.
When the Scout protested, they reactivated her, ORDERED the turn-over of the
material, paid her a month and then deactivated her...  

        She was steamed, but nothing like that happened for the next 30
gaming sessions, so she forgot about it.  Until they got hired to to
security work at an archeological dig that got over-run by UN Colonial
Marines.  And then they all forgot about that after nothing more came of it
over the next 25-ish sessions....  We played 4 to 5 times a month, so it was
about three years of play before the group split up due to some very
unfortunate Real Life happenings...  By that time they were getting the idea
that something was Real Wrong and the UN was Up To Something, but had no
idea what.  I figure one more "incident" and the group would have actively
started trying to figure out what was going on.

        Using the 10-9-8... approach, the pace of the involuntary
involvement of the players subltly begins to accelerate.  Note that any
scenarios resulting from the players investigating don\'t count towards the
count, as it were.... these are key plot points that reveal and/ or expose
pieces and players in the Grand Conspiracy to the PCs.  Anything else they
get into voluntarily just cements into thier heads that they are on the
right/ wrong track.

        It has worked fairly well for me.  If you try it, please let me know
what success you had with it.

        --Michel
