    'body' => 'From: Kiri Aradia Morgan <tiamat@tsoft.com>


>Not being a pacifist myself (ha! right!) I can only say that it seems
>really strange to me.  I would think that pacifists aren\'t supposed to
>kill, and that that would include themselves.  This kind of supports my
>theory that the sort of pacifist who will allow anything to be done to
>them or their loved ones rather than fight has a secret death wish.


Maybe, maybe not. A death wish might not really be all that secret. After
all, it might not be frowned upon the way it has come to be in most parts of
the modern world. After all, Vietnamese Buddhists have a long history of
suicide when they have difficulty rectifying their religious beliefs with
the secular governments of Vietnam. This is an honorable thing to do in that
culture.

The Buddhist traditions in Vietnam were pacifists, in a very real sense.
They had worked, in various ways, to end the war between North and South
Vietnam. With the public self-immolation of Nhat Chi Mai such a death also
became a form of protest that was able to galvanize the population. One of
the most memorable images from the photographic history of the Vietnam War
is that of Quang Duc, who could no longer reconcile his religious beliefs
with the South Vietnamese Diem regime. It set a precedent that a person
could do more in dying, publically and within set traditions, than that
person could do in life. Quang Duc\'s self-immolation wasn\'t the last, there
have been a number since then. Nguyen Van Kinh\'s suicide in 1998 was the
most recent, and it, too served to sway the opinion of the people and served
to bring about a change in the government.

On the other hand, I don\'t think that the way we know pacifism in modernity
is the only way that the concept could evolve. Pacifist movements in the
real world are based around an ideal of pacifism. It is entirely possible
that a utilitarian form of pacifism could develop. After all, the death
penalty - as successful or unsuccessful as it may be in different places -
is an attempt to reduce the amount of killing in a society through killing.
It is "peace through war" in microcosm.
