	Back to your original post, In the CT/MT sense there is only one "Grav"
module (as opposed to Contragrav and thrusters). Loosing that means no
more flying, and usually crashing. In this circumstance either the Grav
module can be repaired and the vehicle flies itself out or it too badly
damaged and need to be lifted. 
	In combat, the third possibility is a crew kill, where the vehicle is
largely undamaged but the crew has been killed. Recovery requires only
replacing the crew. 
	Your second option, attaching the Grav pods to a partly or fully
disabled grav vehicle seems like it won\'t work. If I were to design a
grav vehicle, particularly a combat vehicle, the Grav modules are the
weak point (like the tracks on a tank) and I would make sure they were
well protected. Anything capable of damaging the Grav module would
probably also have done significant damage to the remainder of the
vehicle. While you could build the vehicle with thrust attachment
points, usually you would either use the (replaced) grav modules or have
a wrap around lift vehicle. 
	This may easily degenerate into the "Landing unstreamlined ships" flame
war again, which I don\'t want. 

