  {
    'topic' => 'RE: How to do a gritty, X-Files-like scenario?',
    'index' => 'ed904',
    'month' => '11',
    'body' => 'Robert Eaglestone wrote:
> Suppose you want to give your players the creeps?  Send
> shivers up their spine?  Worry the PCs to no end?

Spacejens wrote:
> First of all, consider the room you play in. Use it to your
> advantage. In other words, if the light suddenly goes out in
> the scenario, do the same in the room. It helps if you can get
> close to the light switch without the players realizing what
> you are about to do. See below.

Lighting can be effective but don\'t neglect  other  environmental
factors of your playing area  (such  as  temperature  or  ambient
sound).  I once ran a horror adventure as part  of  a  non-horror
campaign that worked well:  It was based on  "Treasure  Ships  of
The Abyss" from Challenge magazine.  The players were the crew of
an IN Gazelle close escort during the 5FW and  during  a  misjump
they \'encountered\' a Type-M subsidised liner that was trapped  in
jumpspace.  A  linkway  existed  between  the  Gazelle\'s  forward
avionics bay and the Type-M\'s engine room.

Of course one PC goes across to the other  ship  to  explore  and
becomes trapped when the linkway is lost.  Now the main  room  we
were playing in was warm and well lit, but at this stage I  asked
the adventureous player to wait in the spare bedroom  (which  was
less well lit and  a  few  degrees  *cooler*  than  comfortable).
Also, I use sound FX tapes for ambient sounds  ...  a  continuous
loop of starship engine hum plays quietly and reassuringly in the
main room, while the spare  bedroom  is  deathly  quiet.  I  then
continued for 30 minuets with the main group before  joining  the
lone player.  The PC explored the ghost ship  ...  cue  \'temporal
echos\' of the long dead crew and passengers, and  other  \'spooky\'
stuff.  Once the player had become \'used\' to this I switched  the
tables on him by having a small funneral procession interact with
him and pursue him menacingly about  the  ship!  (Total  duration
about an hour.)

Eventually the linkway was restored and the PC rejoined the  main
party ... and the player reentered the main game room:  his  face
ashen!  Since then, whereever funnerals are mentioned in-game the
player goes pale (and I mean player, not PC).  Most gratifying!

That\'s the other point: there\'s safty in numbers ...  so  if  you
want to creep somone out  isolate  them  from  the  rest  of  the
players first and do it one-on-one.

With the X-files, apart from the conspiracy stuff,  most  of  the
shows recycle old material.  The show\'s success here  is  due  to
high production values: to run a creepy gaming  session  remember
style and atmosphere ... but also moderation (I\'ve not been  able
to reproduce the above effect because my players are wise to this
now).

Regards PLST
