    'body' => 'From: David Healey <David.Healey@dcb.defence.gov.au>


>On that note, at what point do the PC\'s (and, indeed, the public at
>large) consider themselves Imperial citizens as opposed to their
>cultural/racial heritage ?  That is, in this country, it takes something
>like an average of five to six generations, apparently, before an
>immigrant family considers itself to be \'Australian\'.  I\'m wondering
>how long it takes before cultural/racial loyalties are no longer
>considered relevant or pertinent by the populace ?


This is something that I\'ve been thinking about at great length in creating
the background for my "Petty States" Traveller Universe variant. Indeed,
it\'s been something of a stumbling block for me. The official Traveller
Universe is kind of odd in this respect, though. Implicitly, the progression
goes like this: "nationalism / globalism / interstellar statism". This is
never stated directly, it\'s just the impression that I get.

My own take on the official Traveller Universe is that the global,
circum-stellar, subsector, sector and domain identifications are far
stronger for the average Imperial citizen than identification with the
Imperium is. I think that there will be a group of people who consider
themselves to be "Imperial Citizens" first and foremost, but there is no
doubt in my mind that they would be in the extreme minority.

It also depends on how you view the Imperium. If you view it as actually
being feudal (as presented in canon), then it\'s safe to assume that the
*largest* community that Imperial citizens will identify with is most likely
the domain that they live in, or were born in. In my opinion, it\'s much more
likely that most people will identify themselves with their world, or a
larger community with an established history and culture. That\'s what the
social structure looks like under feudalism, indeed that\'s what feudalism
requires.

On the other hand, if the Imperium is distinctly "post-Enlightenment" in
general structure (also as portrayed in canon), then it becomes a bit more
difficult. If I were to play in the Official Traveller Universe, I would
imagine the Imperium akin to France during the reign of Napoleon, stuck
somewhere between the local identification that prevailed in feudal and
aristocratic society and the national identification that would come to
prevail eventually.

Keep in mind that a concept such as "nationalism"[1] - or in the case of the
Imperium, maybe it could be called hypernationalism - is not a "given". It
is something that has to evolve, or that has to be deliberately created.
There was a time, for example, that the concept of a united France, a united
Germany or a United Kingdom (and so on) in the sense that they exist today,
were utterly unthinkable. Even in the United States (which was *born*, in
theory, as unified) identification on the national level was slow in coming.

[1] Please note that I\'m using the term loosely here. When I say
"nationalism" I also mean the concept that is now known as "racialism", in
which identity is drawn heavily from a shared history, culture and tradition
but distinctions are drawn based on gross morphology: hair color and
texture, skin color, variations in body and facial structure. The growth of
racialism and nationalism are linked to the point that it would take
entirely too long to disentangle the two from each other, and it would be
utterly useless.
