    'ts-index' => '1999-11-13.ed948',
    'body' => 'Speaking of ringworlds...

As I understand it, ringworlds that circle a star would be unstable
and wouldn\'t last.  Is that right?

How about a ringworld that doesn\'t circle a star?  Or more
accurately, a huge ring space station.

Let\'s say we have a huge ring station (or mini-ringworld) that is
500,000 km in diameter and 20,000 km high rotating perpendicular to
it\'s orbit around a star.  The inner and outer rims of the tube
making up the interior of the ring are 100 km apart.  Inside this
tube you would have room for mountains, seas, and continents.
Several worlds worth as (3.1x10^10 km) is close to 60 earths.

Inside the tube habitable conditions could be maintained.  The
atmosphere would be retained inside the tube by the walls and
circulated by heat.  Light and heat could be transmitted from the
side wall (facing the sun) to the "roof" and reflected down.  Move
the mirrors with solar powered moters, and you can simulate sun (and
moon if you want) travelling across the sky. giving your days,
seasons and years.  Radiators on the dark side keep the system in
heat equilibrum.  

The dynamics of continent building is obviously a problem if the
system is meant to be self-maintaining.  I know it\'s verboten in
Traveller, but I envision nano-technology taking care of that.  How
I don\'t know. <g> 

IAC, something like this would be entirely "beyond known levels of
technology", but might be more doable (and survivable) for
"mysterious pre-cursor" races than true ringworlds.

Am I totally off the beam with this idea?

Eris

