    'body' => '> Let\'s say we have a huge ring station (or mini-ringworld) that is
> 500,000 km in diameter and 20,000 km high rotating perpendicular to
> it\'s orbit around a star.  The inner and outer rims of the tube
> making up the interior of the ring are 100 km apart.  Inside this
> tube you would have room for mountains, seas, and continents.
> Several worlds worth as (3.1x10^10 km) is close to 60 earths.

I\'m not quite sure what you mean by "perpendicular", but this could be a
problem.  I /think/ you mean that the spin axis of the ringworld should
pass through the star.  This would be consistant with the lighting
technique that you discuss later.

This will be a problem as the ringworld moves in its orbit around the
star.  Left to its own devices, the ringworld spin axis will be fixed in
inertial space (* see note at end).  If at one moment in time it points
through the star, then 90 degrees later in the orbit the ringworld will
be edge on to the star.

To allow the ringworld spin axis to track the star in its orbit would
require huge flows of angular momentum.  We play similar tricks with
low-earth orbit satellites in sun-synchronous orbits, using the Earth\'s
J2 gravity gradient harmonic.  As stated here, the only bodies are the
ringworld and the star.  I can\'t see right now how to take angular
momentum from the star, but I may just be being dense.  Certainly, one
could have a ringworld that encircled a planet that continually tracked
the star.  It wouldn\'t be stable, but the control forces required would
be small.

If we are postulating technologies that can build ringworlds, we can
also look at what might be required to have a ringworld track the star
in such a way.  Thrusters (mass-expelling or magical Traveller versions)
would be one obvious way.  Assuming the ringworld is rotating
counter-clockwise as viewed from the star, and the orbit progresses
counter-clockwise as seen from some arbitrary "above", you would need a
thruster at the "top" of the ringworld pushing in towards the star and
another at the "bottom" pushing out.  The top and bottom change as the
ringworld rotates, of course.  Thus, you would need an array of
thrusters around the rim.  At any given time, two would be firing.  That
could make for a nice visual effect.

Another approach would be to store a large quantity of angular momentum
somewhere on the ringworld.  By selectively absorbing and releasing
momentum on different axes as the orbit progresses, the spin axis of the
ringworld could be forced to track the star.  Storing ringworld sized
angular momentum in small objects (ie smaller than a ringworld) would
require very rapidly spinning flywheels with some sort of motor to speed
them up or slow them down, and possibly to change their spin axis. 
Modern spacecraft use reaction wheels, momentum wheels, and control
moment gyros to serve the same function.

The angular momentum storage need not be all in one place.  Perhapse
some sort of a "slaver sunflower" type plant with a gyro in the trunk
that is found all over the ring?  _The Raft_ (author momentarily
forgotten) has some cute trees with significant angular momentum
storage.  Adventure seed: an offworld plague/parisite is destroying the
trees.  Can the brave PCs stop it before the nutations destroy the
ringworld?

If you do want to put a ringworld in orbit around a star, the simplest
way would be to spin it so that it is always seen edge on to the star. 
Perhaps that is what you suggested in the first place and this is all a
bit misunderstanding.  The problem then is getting light in.  You can
make the outside wall transparent, so that the starlight shines in.  As
the ring spins, different areas see light so you have a sort of
day/night cycle.  Unfortunately, if you\'re using the spin for artificial
gravity then the light comes up from the floor!  You can\'t lay down soil
for plants to grow in or it gets dark again.

* Obscure note on spacecraft dynamics:
Okay, so the spin axis would not remain fixed in inertial space for all
time.  Gravity gradient torques over the course of the orbit would
induce nutation.  Oceans on the ringworld would absorb the nutation
energy.  Eventually the ringworld spin axis would have rotated 90
degrees to the later case that I described, with the spin axis parallel
to the orbit axis.  This situation is described as a Thomson
Equilibrium, as described in:
Thomson, W. T.: "Spin Stabilization of Attitude Against Gravity Torque,"
J. Astronaut. Sci., 9, 31-3 (1962).
I have not actually read that article -- I took the reference from
_Spacecraft Attitude Dynamics_ by P. C. Hughes (1986) which is a good
introduction to the subject.

Doug
