 >> [snip]
 >>  >During an old FTF adventure, I introduced a pacifist movement
 >>  >following (partly) in spirit Yukio Mishima\'s ideas, vaguely linked
 >>  >to buddist religion.
 >> Mishima linked with a pacifist movement?
 >As I said, *partly* based on him, *in spirit.* <grin>

     Small part, angry spirit. :-)

 >>  That thought should cause seismic activity in Japan!

 >>  The man had his own private army & thought that
 >>the Emperor should take back the reins of government and rearm the
 >>nation.
 >The aim of the Private army was to die for, not to kill for, the
 >emperor. That was the basic spirit I was referring to, not their
 >political objectives.

The aim of the private army was to bring glory to the Emperor.  They do 
that best by killing his enemies.  Another way to bring glory to the 
Emperor is to die well in his service.  The second way is not nearly as 
good.  Take the story of the 47 Ronin for example, they brought honor to 
their Lord by killing his enemy.  Their collective suicide just follow 
through.  They had the commitment to take their own lives in atonement for 
the crime of killing their Lord\'s enemy.

 >> His own suicide was an act he had been rehearsing his entire adult
 >> life.
 >>  Perhaps as an atonement for failing the physical to become a Devine
 >> Wind pilot during the Great Pacific War.
 >You or me got something wrong with the japanese mindset. AFAIK, being
 >able to plot his suicide for such a long time is a *far* more
 >important achievement than passing a physical test. In fact,
 >Insurance companies bet that you can\'t plot it for more tha one or
 >two years.

   The physical was a test to qualify to fly a plane, just *once*, for the 
glory and honor of the Emperor and his nation.  He felt that he failed the 
test due to his own nervousness.  i.e. he worried himself sick, and that 
was the cause of his personal failure at the hour of his nation\'s and his 
Emperor\'s greatest need.

 >>  >An Army without more weapons that those used for
 >>  >ritual suicide, willing to die but not to kill, with the firm belief
 >>  >that nobody has the right to take one life, except the own. They were
 >>  >called "Life Fighters" or "Mishimans."
 >> Remember that Mishima used his sword on several unarmed soldiers prior to
 >> his suicide. He certainly was willing to fight & kill others.  His own
 >> suicide was an act of grand theatre.
 >The above is IMTU, and, as I said, *partly* based on Mishima. YMMV.
 >As for a suicide being theatre, I won\'t comment on this. I am sure
 >you realized what you said right after sending it. He *died.*

No, I meant exactly what I typed.  Yukio Mishima was considered one of 
*the* greatest authors of post-war Japan.  He was also a playwright and 
screenplay author.  He stared in many of his theatre and movie 
productions.  In a fair number of them, his character took his own 
life.  This is one way he practiced the act that he probably knew long in 
advance that would end his own life.

As it has been pointed out before on this list, often in Japanese culture, 
a ritual suicide is a statement.  Be it personal, political or 
social.  It\'s done to drive home a point.  Mishima wanted a return to a 
militaristic Japan with the Emperor as the actual, controlling head of 
state.  He was willing to commit himself body and soul to that.  The only 
peace he wanted was a Pax Nippon.

Besides, He was deathly afraid of not leaving behind a good looking 
corpse.  :-)

 >> Given all that, I think the concept is certainly interesting, and the name
 >> could be the result of cultural drift and historical revisionism.

     Thousands of years in the future, pacifists could be calling 
themselves "Mishimans" with a straight face, but a serious professor of 
Earth history would find it damn odd.

May I suggest the really excellent book: <A HREF="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0374524645/eclipsewebwarren">Th 
e Life & Death of Yukio Mishima"</A> by Henry Scott Stokes
A lot of Mishima\'s work is still in print, very interesting reading.  One 
of stories, "The Sailor Who Fell From Grace with the Sea" was turned into a 
movie with Kris Kristofferson.


