    'body' => 'On Fri, 12 Nov 1999 09:27:18 -0800
Richard Hough <corvus@telus.net wrote:

>>I don\'t think canon addresses the issue, but I\'ve
>>always assumed that once you\'ve joined the Imperium,
>>you can\'t leave -- and once the Imperium decides it
>>wants you, all you can do is cut the best deal you
>>can.
>
>How about states can join or leave the Imperium by majority vote of
>citizens of the polity in question? That is, by a majority of the
>citizens of the separate state to join, and by a majority of the
>citizens of the *entire Imperium* to leave.

<sarcasm mode>
"Majority vote? Wadaya thing we\'re runnin here? The Imperium aint no democracy!"
</sarcasm mode>

Citizens of the Imperium have little to no say in the affairs of the Imperium.
They don\'t get a vote.

The Emperor is the only citizen that can decide which worlds are or are not
allowed into the Imperium. Once a member, he is the only citizen that can
decide to let them leave the Imperium. His decisions are backed up by the full
weight
of the Imperial Navy, Army and Marine forces. Citizens who have a problem with
the
Emperor\'s decisions can see any of the above agencies to register a complaint.

:-)

Any world that wants to leave the Imperium would have to send someone
to formally petition the Emperor for their release from the Imperium.
They would almost certainly have to involve the sector Duke/Archduke
for their case to be heard at all.
This would be a long, drawn out process and involve lots of intrigue,
back-stabbing and deceit as different groups pro and anti try to ensure
the success/failure of the discussions.

Sounds like a -great- plot thread. Maybe even a campaign.
Graeme Batho
