    'body' => 'We\'ve been talking about tourist attractions in the Spinward Marches,
and the subject of racing has come up.  I have a few ideas and questions
to pose.  

1) Being in a race
I just spent the day in a sailboat race in San Francisco Bay.  Because
the boats in the race were of different classes, the racers won\'t know
who placed where until the committee compares times and handicaps and
posts the rankings on a web page.  Races in the Far Future can have
similar issues.

2) Engineering a race
Manoeuvre drives under at least High Guard and Book 2 have 1, 2, 3, 4,
5, or 6 Gs of acceleration.  A race under, for example, Mayday or Book 2
rules will end in a tie if the vessels are both of the same G-rating. 
That\'s not very interesting to play.  How do you handle races, if at
all?  I have never done a race, but I\'ve thought about it a little.  

One approach is to break each drive rating into fractions of a G, and
allow fractional increases or decreases in acceleration capability
depending on availability of power for the M-drive (taking systems
off-line), design issues, maintenance, damage, and maybe engineering
skill (but I canna break the laws of physics more than once per episode,
Captain!).  

Another approach is to make the race revolve around handling various
obstacles, like the gravity of a world.  A race involving landing and
registering arrival could also be gamed out with efficiency of takeoff
and landing becoming a major issue.

Races involving jumping are more difficult, as the time in jump has a
randomization element, making it more a game of chance than a sport.

- --Glenn
