    'body' => 'From: Glenn M. Goffin <gmgoffin@pacbell.net>


>That\'s a good question.  I think most Imperial citizens think of
>themselves as Vilani first, which is not too different from being
>Imperial.

I disagree more than I can express by way of email. There are segments of
the Imperium who view themselves as culturally distinct, the Darmine, the
Ilelish, the Antereans, those along the Solomani Rim, etc. I think that
those who consider themselves to be *Vilani* first and foremost would be
relatively small.

>Most local cultures are based on the Ziru Sirka,

I don\'t know about this. The sheer amount of government types which can be
found in a given subsector or sector is pretty astonishing. Granted,
government types do not a culture make, but the government code is a strong
indicator as to where a planets\' inhabitants are culturally.

>which
>dominated the same region of space for nearly 10,000 years and which
>actively Vilanified every world it conquered.


The question is, of course, what Vilanification consists of and in what way
they did whatever it was they did. I remember reading that the those who
were able to adapt to the Vilani way of life (or culture) did better under
the Ziru Sirka than those who weren\'t. In this respect, it can be understood
that the Vilani actively sought to assimilate cultures. However, there\'s
also the factor of what the Terrans / Solomani did when they blew through
the Ziru Sirka. After all, the speed with which they conquered the First
Imperium doesn\'t really support the idea that all of these worlds identified
themselves as strongly as you suggest with Vilani.

Then there\'s the Long Night, when the majority of worlds in Imperial space
had to learn to adjust to being worlds again. Toss in a pocket empire here,
assimilation by a new interstellar polity, and you\'ve got a simmering brew
of worlds that have very little in common with each other.

I\'m not arguing that the imprint of Vilani culture wouldn\'t be felt across
the Imperium, but I don\'t believe that it would be in the form of direct
identification. Cultural (and "national") identifications are anything but
permanent.
