    'date' => 'Mon, 15 Nov 1999 16:24:01 +1100',
    'body' => 'Terry Carlino wrote :-
> What\'s the state of gravetic technology in Traveller? I\'ve heard mention
> that ship lasers use gravic lenses to give them their massive range. I seem
> to recall one of the versions using repulser technology for point defense.

Laser grav focussing dates to the TNE era and was a device to keep the
size of laser focal arrays down. The technology didn\'t appear to spill
over into any other area, which I have always thought a little strange.

CT (High Guard) and MT used repulsors as a defensive modality. The
versions available at average Imperial TLs are quite inefficient
compared to those that arise when you can build tractor and manipulator
(effector) beams.

and :-
> I could buy high gravity filed technology (as used in ship
> laser weapons) being a very short range application. This would explain the
> 6G limit on inertial compensators, and prevent the ST "tractor beam" for use
> from ship to ship.

Yep. For example, there\'s the gravisonic modulator that enables low
berthing without cryogenic fluids.
	Applications of this device could range from \'lighters\' to \'ovens\' to
\'furnaces\', \'refigerators\', etc..

Using modified grav lensing technology, mechanical pumps, winches, etc.
_are_ obsolete.

Vehicles, like buildings, would have gravitic reinforcement. The 6G
limit on inertial compensators strikes me as a rather arbitrary one.
	Another way of setting up inertial compensators would be to use them as
crash protectors - the tremendous decelerations during a collision are
shunted into a storage bank (the vehicle\'s frame and hull?), and a crew
pod ejected to safety.
	If nothing else, this would mean crashing vehicles of advanced tech
levels would probably explode on impact as the storage banks overloaded.
This may be useful for a more cinematic campaign <g>.

None of the above is canon, but none of these things are talked about in
canon either IIRC.


Robert O\'Connor
Medico, Gamer
