    'body' => '>From: "Glenn M. Goffin" <gmgoffin@pacbell.net>
>Subject: some thoughts about racing
...
>2) Engineering a race
>Manoeuvre drives under at least High Guard and Book 2 have 1, 2, 3, 4,
>5, or 6 Gs of acceleration.  A race under, for example, Mayday or Book 2
>rules will end in a tie if the vessels are both of the same G-rating. 
>That\'s not very interesting to play.  How do you handle races, if at
>all?  I have never done a race, but I\'ve thought about it a little. 

  You _could_ make ship design genuinely interesting (and important!)
by using rules that involve maximum & sustained (total) thrust (just
don\'t get into changing fuel/mass ratios?) - basically a similar approach
to that taken by Mayday for small craft & missiles.

>Another approach is to make the race revolve around handling various
>obstacles, like the gravity of a world.  A race involving landing and
>registering arrival could also be gamed out with efficiency of takeoff
>and landing becoming a major issue.

  A number of attempts to organize Triplanetary races have been made on
other lists, but unsuccessfully thus far. Sadly, the Triplanetary map
does not lend itself to the variable ship design very well, even though
the mechanics are essentially those of Mayday.

        Steven Hudson
