    'body' => 'Date: Mon, 15 Nov 1999 09:42:14 +1000
From: "Alan Bradley" <alanb@elf.brisnet.org.au>
Subject: Re: States in the Imperium

> From: "David Healey" 
> That is, in this country, it takes something like an average of five to
> six generations, apparently, before an immigrant family considers itself
> to be \'Australian\'.  I\'m wondering how long it takes before
> cultural/racial loyalties are no longer considered relevant or pertinent
> by the populace ?

I can\'t see how this can be correct.  There aren\'t very many fifth or sixth
generation \'Australians\', unless you\'re talking about indigenous people. 
Most present day Australians are people who migrated here this century, or
their descendants.

Ah, OK.  Maybe what I should have said was this : My family have been in this country (in dribs and drabs) for the last 150 years or so, possibly longer depending on who you believe.  I consider myself a native of this wide brown land, and an \'Australian\', which means whatever you take it to mean.  I wondered what \'nationality\' most citizens within the 3I would consider themselves to be.  Vilani ?  Solomani ?  Sylean ?  Or is the issue of \'race\' completely irrelevant as most people cionsider themselves \'Imperial\'.

A curiousity:  apparently about half of the \'Australian\' troops that fought
in the First World War had been born in Britain.  I\'m pretty sure that this
is a higher proportion of British-born people than existed in the general
Australian population at the time.  It may have some relationship with the
defeat of the two referenda about conscription, too.

Yes and no, in that order.  Proportions of UK-born men in the army at the time roughly mirrored society.  Many of them joined up in the hope that they would see home again, or to get away from the drudgery and hard toil that they found themselves facing on a daily basis in the bush.  You\'re far less likely to be bitten by a venemous reptile in Europe than you are in Australia.  That may also have been something of a drawcard.

An anecdote:  a distant relative of mine, Paddy Brosnan (gee, I wonder
where his family came from:  Bulgaria?) threw an egg at the Prime Minister
during the anti-conscription campaign.  The local (Queensland) cops refused
to arrest him, saying it was a federal matter, and not their problem.  The
result was the formation of the Australian Federal Police.  The PM (Billy
Hughes) tried to use this incident to discredit the anti-conscriptionists,
but still lost - twice.

That explains the \'Don\'t throw Eggs at the PM Act, 1915\' then ......

The AFP were formed in 1979.  As a direct result of the Hilton Bombing.

Dave
