and
>>a series of standard grav lift modules of which are self powered.
>>that you attach to the disabled vehicle. The whole thing is controlled by
>
> Is it just me, or isn\'t the issue of attaching these pods going to be
>non-trivial, and potentially pretty damned exciting with all the power
>cables running to the control module/crew cabin?

Use a robot. I haven\'t gotten around to design it yet (to GT:Robot), but
here\'s a verbal description. The robot consists of a central body made up of
a contragrav unit and a power supply, and several contragrav pods joined to
the main body by control and power cables. A com telemetry unit lets the
operator control the robot from a recovery vehicle, an armored grav vehicle,
perhaps a modified APC.

To recover the downed tank the robot flies to the tank and attaches using a
grav plate. (This allows it to attach even to non-ferrous/non-magnetic tank
armor.) The contragrav pods deploy to envelop the tank in their contragrav
fields, attaching with grav plates to the tank at predetermined points based
upon the tank model. The contragrav field is activated, the tank rises, and
small reactionless thruster plates nudge the tank close enough to the
recovery vehicle so that it can be towed. A larger reactionless thruster pod
would allow the tank to be simply remoted to an evac location.

If the tank\'s contragrav is working, just send over a power supply robot to
hook into an external power and control point and drive the tank out.


