    'index' => 'ee024',
    'topic' => ' Ringworlds',
    'body' => 'I designed a Trav campaign once that centered around a relatively "modest" 
ringworld circling a white dwarf.  The reduced diameter brings the
structural strength requirements for the material way down.  I handwaved
that bonded superdense was good enough (no Scrith required! :-).

The ring spun for .5 g and was divided into segments which mimicked
different homeworlds.  One section was "earth normal", with grav plates 
adding the extra g, while another was designed to immitate a small
rockball world, with grav plates reducing the basic g.  The thing was set
up as a kind of Ancient\'s Menagerie, with the homeworlds of many sophont
species included.  Oh, I almost forgot the mention that there was a kind
of magic polarized filter field that let through a mix of wavelengths
appropriate to each environment.  

If you want a ring-shaped station orbitting a sun, probably the best thing
to do would be to have it orbit in the ecliptic with its axis of rotation
tilted a little off the perpendicular.  This is basically the same as
earth\'s set-up, but inside out.  The "upper" portion of the ring would get
sunlight at one point in the orbit while the "lower" portion would get it
at the opposite side. 

Just some thoughts...
Charles C.
