    'subj' => 'Re: How to do a gritty, X-Files-like scenario?',
    'from' => 'Leonard Erickson',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>>Howdy folks, time for a question.
>>
>>Suppose you want to give your players the creeps?  Send
>>shivers up their spine?  Worry the PCs to no end?
>>
>>How do you set it up?  What factors do you have to think
>>about?  Likely it is some version of the Enigma, with some
>>of The Push in it, right?  But vague categories don\'t help me
>>very much.  I\'m asking for inspiration.
>>
>>Government cover-ups; megacorps crossing the line into
>>dark experiments; medicines that create horrors; rumors
>>and uncertainty about the Ancients and the Solomani
>>Hypothesis; the Imperial Department of War... how does
>>one fit things like these together into a coherent scenario
>>that starts innocuously and turns into a monster of a situation?
>
> A great resource for this sort of thing is GURPS Illuminati, which
> is generic enough to be useable in any role-playing environment, no
> matter what rule set one is using. I successfully did a superhero
> campaign -- set in the same universe as a handful of other campaigns
> we did -- using Illuminati. The PCs wound up being pawns in a huge
> conspiracy, a conspiracy with many layers so that when the players
> solved one mystery, all it did was generate more questions.
>
> This could easily be done in an interstellar setting. You don\'t even
> need to figure out all the details ahead of time -- just enough for
> the PCs to become involved in, and maybe a little more. The important
> thing is to keep them guessing, and get them to the point that they
> begin to suspect that everything they know is wrong.
>
> One great fake-out I pulled on them: the Evil Corporation that they
> were fighting against, in whose HQ they had been several times, was
> an outfit called OmniTech. When the heroes finally decided to face off
> against OmniTech once and for all, they went to the OmniTech building
> and found... a completely different building, the offices of a toy
> company. Suspicious, they went to a nearby phone booth and checked the
> directory. No listing for OmniTech, but a listing, at that address, for
> the Toy Company.
>
> It got to the point that the PCs didn\'t know who to trust or where
> to turn... and by having the Enemy plant a few fake clues, I had some
> of the PCs begin to suspect that one of the others was secretly working
> for the Enemy.
>
> As I said, you can easily do this in a space game...

True. It\'s all to easy to have them told. "You must be thinking of some
*other* planet. We\'ve always had the toy company there..."

For the "ultimate" in paranoia, have them go to a system they\'ve been
to several (or better yet *many*) times before. And have the system be
different. Different star, different orbit and UPP for the mainworld.
To really rub it in, keep the name. And have all their library records
etc match the *new* system.

For extra points, make the "missing" system their home base. With the
"new" system having no records of them...

