    'topic' => ' How to do a gritty, X-Files-like scenario?',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

>>Suppose you want to give your players the creeps? [...]
>>How do you set it up?  What factors do you have to think
>>about?
>
> Uncertainty and powerlessness. These are the two variables from which
> horror springs.
>
> Start normally. Try not to let your players know you are going to run a
> horror scenario. Instead, run one of the other normal Traveller campaigns
> for the first couple of sessions. Have the PCs develop their skills and
> make friends with NPCs, so that they develop a sense that they know how the
> universe works.
>
> Then, when things begin to get strange, put them in situations where their
> skills and friends are simply inadequate to fully deal with the situation.
> You probably don\'t want the PCs to be *totally* helpless; rather, you want
> them to be thwarted in resolving the situation to *their* satisfaction.
>
> You should also isolate them, so that they have nowhere to turn for help.
> This does not need to be simple physical isolation (although that works).
> It can also be social isolation -- no one is willing to believe them, much
> less help them.
>
> Here are the four maxims to keep in mind when setting up an atmosphere of
> horror. These are what you want your players to eventually realize:
>
> 1. Things are not as they seem.
> 2. These things are beyond your control.
> 3. Worse, you don\'t even know half of it.
> 4. And nobody believes you when you mention what you *do* know.

You just reminded me of one of the *creepiest* stories. It\'s one of A.
Bertram Chandler\'s "Commodore Grimes" stories. I *think* it\'s "Into the
Alternate Universe". Anyway, to put it in Traveller terms, a ship
misjumps into our universe from another very similar universe. The big
difference is that a few centuries back, a ship had a badly damaged
engine and drive. All sorts of stray radiation from the power plant and
god only knows *what* leaking in thru the damaged jump bubble. It
misjumped. Worse, it was one of the misjumps where the jump lasts a
*lot* longer than a week. 

Not only is life support getting bad (even with hydroponics and tuissue
culture tanks), but the rats they ship had picked up a few jumps back
and not gotten a chance to exterminate are *changing*....

In the "normal" universe, the rats make an attack shortly after the
ship emerges from jump and the ship burns up on re-entry on an
earthlike world.

In the alternate, the ship manages to set down ok. And the mutated,
*intelligent* rats win the fight and enslave the crew. They establish a
colony on the unihabited planet. Eventually they either repair the
ship, or another ship happens by. 

By the time of the story, the Rats control dozens of worlds in the out
of the way cluster. Enough that Humans are more interested in keeping
them from spreading than in trying to exterminate them or liberate
their human slaves. 

There\'s some trading, and a lot more raiding across the borders. And
since this is a frontier area, there are still worlds for both sides to
expand onto. 

So, our hero learns about this when he\'s attacked by a ship that turns
out to be a Rat ship that has misjumped. He wins. Barely. And then he\'s
got to deal with human sized, intelligent rats. Ones that not only keep
human slaves, but consider them as a backup food supply (one of the
uglier things they discover when they search the captured ship is that
the tissue culture tanks are growing *human* flesh...)

One possibility would be that it turns out conditions in a particular
system make jumps between the universes easy. 

Another stolen from the original is that they figure out how to jump
the ship back to it\'s universe of origin, and how to make a jump back
in time to prevent the infested ship from landing. 

Or maybe the Rat ship is from their universe\'s future, and they have to
try stopping the infested ship...

Just dealing with these "ratoids" ought to be unsettling enough. The
possibility of them being neighbors (ie the players are the first
contact between "rat" civilization and human), or as the future (the
rat ship is from the future and the players need to see if they can
prevent the rat civilization) ought to be good for lotsa of creepiness.

Stuff like rats eating people, and the way they discpline slaves by
biting chunks out of them ought to *really* get to the players.

Oh yeah, if you go with the "rats are a possible future" scenario,
consider that the PCs may have to shoot down that cripplerd ship. If
they get observed doing so, they\'ll have a lot of explaining to do. A
kind GM will let the evidence from the future stay. A nasty GM will
have all of it vanish. 

