    'index' => 'ee051',
    'month' => '11',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> Hit them with something familiar, like the set up for "Aliens", encourage
> them to think you\'ve recycled the plot, and then have something happen that
> is clearly impossible ( given their current knowledge ). Preferably
> something nasty that will make them want to mount a 24hr guard, and not
> trust their automatics. The first killing from "Forbidden Planet" comes to
> mind.

Another *extremely* nasty is to hit the players with something familar,
but where the "natural" response is *wrong*. Say a conspiracy where
they finally uncover enough proof to show that *something* was going on
in secret. They release it to the media, the conspirators disappear.
But one of them corners a PC alone, and *proves* to him/her that the
conspiracy was going to do something good and *wonderful*. And that
since it\'s been exposed, it\'ll be a long time before the conspirators
can again get the conditions right for XXX.

Maybe XXX is a *cheap* cure for diseases that can\'t just be placed on
the market because it\'d hurt the profits of too many megacorps. Maybe
it\'s something good for the citizen, but that the Imperium doesn\'t
like. 

In any case, the punchline is that the characters, by being their
normal, suspicious selves have just made the biggest screwup of their
lives. One they can\'t *begin* to fix. And they\'ll have to live with
being praised for what\'s really a disaster. 

Note. This is best saved for *players* who play their characters *way*
too paranoid and suspicious. Think of it as a "last resort" to get them
to realize that they need to allow for *good* hidden motives sometime.

> Make them paranoid. ( Leave hints that it\'s one of the players that\'s
> responsible for the badness, especiallly if it isn\'t.  Make it seem the
> enemy can "walk through walls". Enemy is "super-genius", it will outthink
> anything you do....)

Psionics. The enemy can read your mind. He *knows* what you are going
to do. 

Or just read John W. Campbell\'s "Who Goes There?" It\'s the basis for
both versions of "The Thing", and while Carpenter stuck closer to the
story, it\'s possible for you as a ref to do even better. 

