    'from' => 'Robert Prior robert_prior@sympatico.ca',
    'body' => '>>Rather like some of the New Age Wiccans around here, who ignore an awful
>>lot of history.  Or many of my fellow Anglicans, who resolutely learn
>>nothing about early church history so that their "faith" is unshaken.
>
>Amen to that.  I\'ve met some mighty narrow minds on both sides of the
>tracks.  But I\'d have to say from personal experience that most of the
>churches these days do little or no good anymore.  I tried one here in New
>Hampshire and it was pretty lame.

Depends on what you mean by "do".  Helping the poor and what-not is now a
secular responsibility.

I know that up here in Hogtown the group that looks after more homeless
than any other is an agency of the Anglican Church, yet even most
churchmembers don\'t know that and credit either the Salvation Army or the
government Social Services. So publicity is also a factor.

As to the serious religious stuff, finding a congregation that is serious
about religion, as opposed to being serious about having a nice church with
new hymn-books, is tough. For one thing to seriously grow in religious
faith people have to be free to question it, which doesn\'t happen inside
most churches, and also have to be willing to put serious skull sweat into
learning what their religion actually means, which requires commitment.
(In Credo terms, most Angicans can\'t tell an "Article of Faith" from a
"Customary Practice", and I suspect the same is true of most religions.)

I\'m seriously considering going to seminary part-time, not to become a
priest but just to find an environment where people don\'t get offended when
you ask questions. (Like "When Jesus cast the demon into the pigs, why was
it OK for him to thus destroy some farmer\'s herd of pigs? What had the
farmer done to deserve that?")

ObTrav: Read 101 Religions.
