> Robert Eaglestone wrote:
>> Suppose you want to give your players the creeps?  Send
>> shivers up their spine?  Worry the PCs to no end?

I just remembered a technique that I sort of stumbled onto. If your
players are into reading SF or even just watching SF movies/tv,
recommend things to them. Or even loan them some tapes or books. 

Then later, have something come up that is similar to or even outright
stolen from one of the works you recommened or loaned to them. 

I once scared the pants off a player in a D&D game. I knew he\'d just
finished Brunner\'s "Traveller in Black" collection not that long ago.
The main character in those stories is a sort of Power or Demigod or
*something* (never made entirely clear). But he wanders around the
world and when people make certain sorts of wishes/statements he grants
them. For example a prominent citizen\'s niece is being executed for
having falsely charged him with attempted rape, and he comments "I wish
you knew how much this pains me". And by nightfall everyone in town
knows that he really *did* try to rape her, and bribed witnesses and
bought the judge so she\'d be executed and cease being a problem. 

The Traveller in Black always grants the wishes with the phrase "As you
wish, so be it." 

So, while someone was messing with something that they thought might be
a magic item. and made a "wish" type comment, I "intoned" the PHRASE.
"As you wish, so be it.". And the player who\'d read the book recently
(and several others that I hadn\'t known had read it) just about had
heart failure. :-)

