    'ts-index' => '1999-11-15.ee063',
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> I was having similar thoughts myself. In a couple of weeks time,
> we\'re taking our kids to Disneyland (tm) for a holiday, and I
> was wondering; what do citizens of the 3I do for a holiday?
> Do they go to theme parks? Is there a Disney - World - orbiting
> some star in the 3I? What has the entertainment industry become?
>
> Here on Terra we have huge tracts of land devoted to tourism.
> Even some countries use tourism as their major source of income.
> But if you look through the Marches sourcebook there is no indication
> that tourism is an important industry anywhere, and there isn\'t even
> any mention of things that would be points of interest to a tourist.
> So where are all the sight-seeing opportunities & pleasure planets
> (like Star Trek\'s Risa)? Where do the luxury liners and safari ships go?
>
> It strikes me that there is very little that would attract tourists
> to the Marches.  There\'s the museum at Regina, but that is solitary
> entertainment and it\'s appeal could hardly be described as being
> "fun".  Apart from that, there is nothing that I would consider a
> "draw" for tourists.

Alas, you are projecting a rather recent cultural phenomenon into a
situation where it just plain *doesn\'t work*. 

Tourism, of the sort you are thinking of is a creation of the railroad,
the steamship, and most especially the *airplane*. 

You didn\'t get huge numbers of "average joe" tourists until
transportation was cheap AND IT WAS POSSIBLE TO MAKE THE TRIP IN NO
MORE THAN TWO WEEKS!

That last is the killer in Traveller. That means that you *can\'t* go
even *one* jump away for your vacation, because even with 2 weeks
vacation, it\'d use up your entire vacation just getting there and back!

The only offworld tourists will be rich, retired, or at the very least,
folks with enough seniority to get 4 week vacations. And even the
latter aren\'t going to go more than a jump away. 

For the vast majority, an offworld trip is a "once in a lifetime" deal.
That puts the attractions in a whole different class. The stuff that
currently attracts tourists isn\'t going to do it. 

Glorified amusement parks, like Disney World, are going to be *local*.
Besides, given the *vast* cultural differences between worlds,
attracting folks from offworld isn\'t all that likely anyway.

