Hmm... I remember my dad having email as early as 1979, probably earlier.
Then again, he was getting it through the mainframe at work, even though it
did pass mail to/from DOD HQ. I know that by 1981, there were extensive
mail-nets running; by 84 (when I got into modeming) FidoNet, WWIV-Net,
UUCP-net, and DARPA-Net were all going strong... I know that at least one
local board (BBS) had a DARPA-Net -> WWIV-Net interchange going. One way,
as I recall.

Then, about 2 years ago, I worked for the local office of the National
Archives. The RRS (Records Retention Schedule) for E-mail specified the
storage means allowed: printed out onto paper and filed like snail-mail.
All incoming and outgoing e-mails to/from government offices in the
executive branch (other than personal e-mails, which ARE allowed) were
required to be treated in this manner.
Databases, documents, and such are required to be in print-form as well...
space, tab, or comma delimited text files, on mag-tape, are allowed as
interim storage...

Ob Trav:
IMTU, hardcopies are still the "Default" long term storage method. Usually
nanofiche (2-3 mm per page, laser etched, on non-flexible bi-layer
(Dark/light) media, approx 0.1mm thick. Typically 10x20mm sheets...). IMTU,
typical uses include 5 or even 6 layer media (You can get color that way,
assuming reflective rather than transparency based reading methods). Naval
orders are typically sent on Fiche, via courier, on the "Correct" media for
the issue date, with several verification methods built onto the fiche
(Like built-in nanowire layers for verifying sender secured codes, specific
spectrum requirements for each layer, etc, ad nauseum) with digital copies
also sent. Generally, these will be encoded using twin-key or triple-key
encryption schemes.

The problem with digital media, lack of lifespan not withstanding, is that
any re-writeable media is editable, and any non-rewriteable media is
generally single session, or non-terminated partition-mapped, but still
limited in number of writes. Additionally, electronic media require
compatable data encryption/decryption (Hell, ASCII is techinically a
"Published Key" encryption...) to return to readable formats. Far better to
have a physical method that is in clear-text (IE, not encrypted from the
original linguistic content), even if it requires extensive magnification.
Actually, Microfiche is an exceptionally easy to use archival storage
method. And, if etched rather than photo-imaged, can be both very compact
and extremely stable. I envision some megacorps (Sharushiid, Makidhadrun,
Nasiraaka, LSP, Schunamann & Sons) having fiche archives going back
multiple centuries... probably only barely indexed, and kept for various
reasons.

Envision the fun of a Genealogical search on a non-indexed stack of fiches
for some nobleman trying to prove his heritage in order to claim some heir
status to the fortunes of some deceased (and non-noble) relative... Pouring
through THOUSANDS of fiches, tracking relatives by Dependant Decalrations
of the governing vilani megacorps...

