    'ts-index' => '1999-11-15.ee076',
    'body' => 'From: Leonard Erickson <shadow@>


>Alas, you are projecting a rather recent cultural phenomenon into a
>situation where it just plain *doesn\'t work*.


I\'m not sure that I can agree with you here. While it is a rather recent
phenomenon, I think that there may be other factors involved as well. I
agree with you in spirit, though. It\'s not likely that there\'ll be a
Makhidkarunworld on Regina that will be a draw for folks from Glisten, for
example. That\'s not to say that there aren\'t other alternatives.

>Tourism, of the sort you are thinking of is a creation of the railroad,
>the steamship, and most especially the *airplane*.

>
>You didn\'t get huge numbers of "average joe" tourists until
>transportation was cheap AND IT WAS POSSIBLE TO MAKE THE TRIP IN NO
>MORE THAN TWO WEEKS!


That\'s assuming that a two week vacation is some sort of universal that will
be part of the status quo in the Traveller universe, despite the fact that
vacations for the working class - of *any* sort - are also relatively young.
Hell... come to think of it, the working class is pretty young as well.

Before vacations were a given for Joe Average, it was much more common for
promoters to bring the attractions to his hometown. Incidentally, the
travelling carnival concept is *perfect* for Traveller. Canonically, jumps
are relatively expensive for individuals, but *ships* are cheap enough that
promoters could create travelling carnivals and road shows of all sorts.

Stylistically, the idea also fits perfectly with the adventuring dynamic of
Traveller.

>That last is the killer in Traveller. That means that you *can\'t* go
>even *one* jump away for your vacation, because even with 2 weeks
>vacation, it\'d use up your entire vacation just getting there and back!

>
>The only offworld tourists will be rich, retired, or at the very least,
>folks with enough seniority to get 4 week vacations. And even the
>latter aren\'t going to go more than a jump away.


Again, this requires that a two week vacation is some sort of universal. I
don\'t know that there\'s any really strong evidence for it.

>For the vast majority, an offworld trip is a "once in a lifetime" deal.
>That puts the attractions in a whole different class. The stuff that
>currently attracts tourists isn\'t going to do it.

>
>Glorified amusement parks, like Disney World, are going to be *local*.


Not necessarily the case, at least in my humble opinion. Places like Disney
World and Disneyland are frequently sub-standard with regards to variety and
quality of rides. In the U.S., places like the Six Flags amusement parks
literally smack the crap out of the Disney parks with respect to rides.

It\'s not the *rides* that are the draw, they just happen to be (as GURPS
fans might say) a "special effect". What\'s the real draw is the marketing
machinery that portrays the Disney parks as a once in a lifetime experience
that can be enjoyed by anybody.

>Besides, given the *vast* cultural differences between worlds,
>attracting folks from offworld isn\'t all that likely anyway.


I disagree, anything is possible with the right spin. Places like the Disney
parks are the draw that they are because of their universal lowest common
denominator appeal. Due to this appeal, the travel industry can lower prices
and / or package trips to the Disney parks... the lesser expense and / or
greater convenience strengthens the appeal, and so on. With the vast power
of the megacorporations in the Traveller universe, I would find it difficult
to believe that such facilities wouldn\'t exist, dotted across the subsectors
and sectors. They *would* draw off world tourism, and probably alot of it,
but it would still be "local" in a sense.

I do think that it\'s quite possible to flatten the cultural distinctions
concerning entertainment. The lowest common denominator appeal of the
American entertainment industry is proof of that.

Another interesting idea would be "Subsector (or Sector, or Domain) Fairs",
or Olympic style sporting events that are "fixed" in a specific location,
but only for a short time. The Subsector Fair is particularly applicable,
stylistically. The real World\'s Fair concept will be forever linked with
"the World of Tomorrow" style Golden Age sci-fi. Both ideas make excellent
adventure hooks... wow... my mind is swimming with the possibilities.

Both the Fair and the Olympic models are methods by which the travel time
problem that Leonard mentioned were overcome in the real world. They serve
to foster a sense of unity, they are an excellent advertising opportunity,
and they\'re just damn interesting.
