    'ts-index' => '1999-11-15.ee078',
    'body' => '>I just remembered a technique that I sort of stumbled onto. If your
>players are into reading SF or even just watching SF movies/tv,
>recommend things to them. Or even loan them some tapes or books. 
<...>
>So, while someone was messing with something that they thought might be
>a magic item. and made a "wish" type comment, I "intoned" the PHRASE.
>"As you wish, so be it.". And the player who\'d read the book recently
>(and several others that I hadn\'t known had read it) just about had
>heart failure. :-)

That\'s evil.... :-D

Sometimes, all one needs to induce paranoia in the players is a previous
rep for that sort of thing. The last game I ran before my current GURPS
Traveller was the paranoid Supers campaign I had run last year, with 
the same group of players.

This past weekend, I had the group NPC break her ankle to get her
separated from the others, for no particular reason. The group leader told
her to call him when she was released from the hospital. A broken ankle
on a high-population, hi-tech world shouldn\'t take long at all. But with
all the other activities going on, I had forgotten completely about her,
until several hours had passed in game time. So when I had her call the
others, to explain what took so long I came up with an excuse that the
hospital had been overwhelmed with patients after a mag-lev train accident.

Earlier in the scenario, the PCs had taken a mag-lev across the city, and
had also encountered a couple of members of a (rival) intelligence unit. So
when they heard about the train wreck, their response was to connect to 
the local newsnet to get as much info about the accident, then try to
correlate the time and place of the wreck with their own movements to see
if there was a connection. All this from an off-the-cuff comment I made
on the spur of the moment to cover my own mistake.

A way to use this in a game: have things happen in the background of 
wherever the players are, to make them suspect that maybe someone *is*
out to get them. They take train from point A to point B on planet X;
later that day, there\'s a big train wreck on planet X. The PCs visit a
space station; after they leave, the station\'s reactor core goes critical
and blows up, taking half the station with it.... Keep doing this, and
it will have an effect on the players...


