    'body' => 'Dear Folks -

As Leonard reminded us:
>Alas, "Greatest American Hero" made an *unforgivable* mistake in the
>first episode of the second season. One that caused me and just about
>everyone I know to quit watching it.
[snip]
>Then at the start of the second season, the aliens give him another
>copy of the instructions WHICH HE PROMPTLY LOSES! That was it. He was
>too incompetent to live.

I know, I know, that was a bad idea. It would have been a better idea to allow
him to have the book for one or two episodes, find out one or two nifty new
powers, save the world, and *then* lose the book.

Losing the book allows the character to be more interesting - with the old 70\'s
all-powerful Superman, his hardest choice was "who to hit first?" More
underpowered characters actually have to *think*.

The point was made later as an understatement, when the hero meets the
*original* human who was given the suit. It is the old "absolute power corrupts
absolutely". If he had full access to the suits powers and abilities, he could
well have lost sight of what they should be used for (character explanation) -
and could have overcome problems too easily to make for an interesting storyline
(story/game balance explanation).

ObTrav: dunno, maybe the nobility losing sight of the concept of "noblesse
oblige"? Or "ordinary" characters having to work out how to defeat a foe (or
solve a problem) that seems far beyond their meagre resources?  ;-)
