> watch at these points.

For that matter, you can have things like the "Armstrong Classic" from
Philip St. John\'s "Rocket Jockey"[1]. The race was in the Sol system
(pre-FTL). The initial leg (a "qualifying run") was from Terra to Luna.
The ships that qualified had to land on Mercury, Venus(?) Mars,
Ganymede, Io, Callisto, Europa and Titan(?) and then return to Earth
(or was it Luna). One of the tricks was that they could land on the
other worlds in *any* order. They also had limited fuel supplies. They
were allowed to have fuel dumps of up to some amount at the port on
each world. Winner was the lowest total time.

One of the nice touches of this setup is that since the relative
positions of the planets change from year to year, the race is never
the same. Also, if your ship has a bit more thrust or can get more
delta-V out of a full load of fuel, you can hit planets in an order
that takes less time than it would for the other ships. Heck, in the
case of the Jovian moons, a difference of *hours* will greatly affect
the positions!

This can be run in the Sol system, as in the story, with or without
stops at major asteroids and outer planets. Or you can run it in
another system. 

I recommend keeping it to the inner system simply because it gets
impossible to keep track of things on a scale map without custom
computer software otherwise. 

[1]Philip St. John is one of Lester del Rey\'s pen names. This
particular book is somewhat famous because even though it was written
in the 50s, del Rey got a bit of future history right. The race  is the
Armstrong Classic. It\'s named after the first man to land on the moon! 
Talk about weird co-incidences!

