    'body' => 'On Mon, 15 Nov 1999 18:13:07 PST
shadow@ (Leonard Erickson) writes


>> It strikes me that there is very little that would attract tourists
>> to the Marches.  There\'s the museum at Regina, but that is solitary
>> entertainment and it\'s appeal could hardly be described as being
>> "fun".  Apart from that, there is nothing that I would consider a
>> "draw" for tourists.
>
>Alas, you are projecting a rather recent cultural phenomenon into a
>situation where it just plain *doesn\'t work*.
>
>Tourism, of the sort you are thinking of is a creation of the railroad,
>the steamship, and most especially the *airplane*.

<cheap shot>
 I\'ll be more careful what I\'m thinking of now I know you\'re Zhodani.
</cheap shot>

I was only using my present day vacation to lead in to the topic and
did not mean to imply that there were any parallels between that and
tourism in Traveller. I too think that tourism works very differently
in the Imperium. But just because it doesn\'t work the same way doesn\'t
mean that it can\'t work at all.

>You didn\'t get huge numbers of "average joe" tourists until
>transportation was cheap AND IT WAS POSSIBLE TO MAKE THE TRIP IN NO
>MORE THAN TWO WEEKS!

I agree with you that 2 week vacations won\'t work that way in Traveller.
That doesn\'t mean that tourism *doesn\'t work*. Just that the same kind of
vacation we\'re familiar with here will not lead to space tourism in the
Traveller Universe.

However, tourism DOES happen. It\'s what luxury liners are built for.
It\'s what safari ships are built for. It\'s what at least one of the
megacorporations specialise in. It\'s in canon. There are published
scenarios that have tourists and entertainers aboard cruise ships.
The luxury liners aren\'t just there for business travellers or those
who are migrating. They take tourists around the Imperium.

Heck, when you think about it, aren\'t all Travellers tourists?

>That last is the killer in Traveller. That means that you *can\'t* go
>even *one* jump away for your vacation, because even with 2 weeks
>vacation, it\'d use up your entire vacation just getting there and back!

Only if your vacation is for 2 weeks. In my country 4 week vacations are
the norm (we have it good). That would give sophonts time for 2 weeks stay
at their destination as well as 2 weeks in jump. It makes it possible.
But only if there is something worth the time and expense one jump away.

Space travel, while affordable to the masses, is still expensive. To my
mind most sophonts would not holiday outsystem unless there was
a real \'draw\' to attract them. It certainly would not be a yearly event.
Most "average joe" would find something closer to home to look at instead.

>The only offworld tourists will be rich, retired, or at the very least,
>folks with enough seniority to get 4 week vacations. And even the
>latter aren\'t going to go more than a jump away.

That\'s the kind of folks I see as \'tourists of the Imperium\' too. Don\'t
forget the nobles. And with the volume of sophonts in the Imperium even
a minute percentage of tourists is a huge amount. Even if they only
travelled once in their lives.

>For the vast majority, an offworld trip is a "once in a lifetime" deal.
>That puts the attractions in a whole different class. The stuff that
>currently attracts tourists isn\'t going to do it.

Bingo! My point exactly. So, since we know it does happen, what are
they going to look at in all those luxury liners, yachts & safari ships?
What do people go to see that they can\'t get locally?

A thought. Perhaps it\'s not so much the destination - but the trip.
The sightseeing might not be as important as the experience of getting
there. You can\'t experience jumpspace except in jump. You can\'t just
look up at the stars, you can BE there. That feeling might be what
draws people to travel.

Any more ideas?

Graeme Batho
