    'body' => '>A thought. Perhaps it\'s not so much the destination - but the trip.
>The sightseeing might not be as important as the experience of getting
>there. You can\'t experience jumpspace except in jump. You can\'t just
>look up at the stars, you can BE there. That feeling might be what
>draws people to travel.
>
>Any more ideas?

How about this: Most world which permit easy "temporary egress" to their
locals will probably have a significant minority who have left world for
vacation, at least once.

Looking at the tables in (Ooo, ich, I\'m quoting from GT) GT-Far Trader,
most TL 7+ will be able to save up for an off-world vacation, should they
so choose. For most of the middle class, it would be like Disney; once or
twice in a lifetime. Assuming 3 weeks vacation per year (IME, typical for
persons at a single employer for more than 5 years, but see below), that
would allow  J-1 once per year for the upper middle classes (1.5-2 x base
per captia GWP) each way, and minimal spending; save up for a few years,
and use two years accumulated leave, and you can get one week, and two
jumps, assuming 3 day layovers. If they are careful, you can get by with
under KCr6 for a week on a world J1 away.

Hmm another look (this time in GT itself) finds Soc-0, middle class, to
have maintenance of Cr500/month. Incomes range from PRxCr75 to PRxCr100 per
month for average jobs. Most require PR\'s of 10+, most typically would be
12\'s...at PR\'s of 10, at the Cr75 per point of PR, that\'s Cr250 per month
above cost of living. With J1 mid passage being Cr8000, that\'s 32 months
savings; or just about 2.5 years.

Combining these two approaches (GT incomes and outgoes, GT-FT prices),
travel aboard a liner will run you Cr1800 per parsec, assuming you pay 10
weeks early, or Cr3600+hotel to the neighboring (J1) world, so for a week\'s
hotel, let\'s chalk up another KCr1. That\'s Cr4600, at say Cr125 per month
(That\'s 50% savings rate, about maximum for surplus income IME), or 37
months (just under 3 years). About as long as people save up to go to Los
Disneys....

Under other rulesets, the math is a little more grim. IF WE ASSUME KCr10K
per annum as the base salry per person, then we wind up with Joe Average
being able to afford Low Passage occasionally, perhaps every two years, and
the very wealthy can afford Mid passage often, or High passage
occasionally. Most middle class will probably save up for a
once-in-a-lifetime mid passage trip off world. Perhaps the middle class
might send a son or daughter off world via low passage for college. If we
assume that MT\'s payment rates are LOWER than typical world payments for
skilled labor, but we use them as the baseline for skilled labor, we get
some KCr13 per year, and also assuming skilled labor tends to be Soc4,
that\'s KCR13 as well. So, later in career (Skill level 2) there is a 10%
bonus; that gives us KCR 14.3 income, or a mid passage in some 7 years or
so. Typically, junior executives and other middle class types tend to make
nearly double the skilled labor rates currently, and that\'s not likely to
change; so we\'ll assume soc 7, KCr 26 income annually, and an outgo of
KCr22.75, or about KCr3 per year. This gives us enough surplus to afford
low passage almost annually, or that once in a life-time trip every 6
years, assuming no other vices. Still, at KCr3, if you\'ve got the three
weeks, good life insurance, and a desire to travel, you get a week one jump
away (Prollly 1-2 parsecs...)

CT\'s math is not able to be worked out easily; that\'s a flame war I wish to
avoid. TNE\'s is almost as bad, due to lack of materials, but looks to be
about KCr25 per annum for soc 7 (IIRC... the data is derived from world
tamer\'s), for income; we\'ll assume Cr200 per Soc for monthly expenses of
about KCr19. Travel becomes affordable. Occasionally. Most will be able to
travel low or steerage once a year. There were people who traveled steerage
as tourists during the steamer days; there would be in the space era as
well.

[1] As for leave times: Typically, I\'m seeing entry level stuff in alaska
with 1 week leave after 1st year, 2 weeks each after 2nd through 5th, and 3
weeks per each additional. With an accrual limit of the not more than two
or three years\' worth. As a federal employee, I accrued 1/2 day per 2
weeks, or 13 work days per year, as a new hire; some long term feds accrue
a day per 2 weeks, or 26 days per year; certain persons are accruing 1.5
days per 2 weeks, or 45 days per year. The fed stats are just annual leave,
and do not include comp time (which most feds will accrue some of), sick
leave, or military leave. This is when working either 4x10hr per week or
5x8hr per week. Guys working the slop get (typically) time off equal to the
time on, or 2 weeks on, 2 weeks off. Fishpackers get 2 weeks off per 2
months worked, although it tends to be seasonal work for about 75% of them.
Most commercial seamen (fishing crews and factory vessel crews) up here are
forced by the companies to take the 2 weeks per 3 months, as a matter of
company policy.

Just for reference, Even McDonalds grants 3 weeks a year to long term
employees... and generally, makes them take it within three months of
earning it; a few employees cash it in, and a few get permission to bank
their time off for the following year. I know a guy who banked his second
year, and McD\'s made him take BOTH 2 weeks one after the other (total 4
weeks) when he earned the 3rd years leave.

