    'ts-index' => '1999-11-16.ee101',
    'body' => 'shadow@ (Leonard Erickson) wrote:

>Alas, you are projecting a rather recent cultural phenomenon into a
>situation where it just plain *doesn\'t work*. 
>
>Tourism, of the sort you are thinking of is a creation of the railroad,
>the steamship, and most especially the *airplane*. 
>
>You didn\'t get huge numbers of "average joe" tourists until
>transportation was cheap AND IT WAS POSSIBLE TO MAKE THE TRIP IN NO
>MORE THAN TWO WEEKS!

Is this an American problem?

I know several people who have either carried forward leave for
a year to allow a six week Australian or African holiday.
And several people who get six or more weeks holiday per year.

Then there are contractors (usually unmarried) who are secure enough
financially to take a couple of months break between contracts.

And not to forget the mainstay of the round the world cruise industry -
the retired middle classes (who are rich by many definitions but not
actually the Soc A+ that people tend to think of in Traveller).

Also you get the people who are between education and work who just
want to "see the galaxy before accepting the chains of conformity."

Looking towards the future, there is the concept of parental leave
being muted in this country, which might eventually allow parents
and children enough time to vist nearby worlds.

>That last is the killer in Traveller. That means that you *can\'t* go
>even *one* jump away for your vacation, because even with 2 weeks
>vacation, it\'d use up your entire vacation just getting there and back!
>
>The only offworld tourists will be rich, retired, or at the very least,
>folks with enough seniority to get 4 week vacations. And even the
>latter aren\'t going to go more than a jump away. 

Even with all I said above, I\'d agree that travelling much more than
a jump or two for a holiday is going to be pretty rare - I may know
people who have had six week trips to Australia, but I know a lot more
who haven\'t

>For the vast majority, an offworld trip is a "once in a lifetime" deal.
>That puts the attractions in a whole different class. The stuff that
>currently attracts tourists isn\'t going to do it. 

For most people, it\'s still likely to be a "once in a lifetime" thing,
from cost alone. So I agree here.

>Glorified amusement parks, like Disney World, are going to be *local*.
>Besides, given the *vast* cultural differences between worlds,
>attracting folks from offworld isn\'t all that likely anyway.


