    'topic' => ' How to do a gritty, X-Files-like scenario?',
    'body' => 'Glenn St-Germain wrote:
>>>>>>>>>
A way to use this in a game: have things happen in the background of 
wherever the players are, to make them suspect that maybe someone *is*
out to get them. They take train from point A to point B on planet X;
later that day, there\'s a big train wreck on planet X. The PCs visit a
space station; after they leave, the station\'s reactor core goes critical
and blows up, taking half the station with it.... Keep doing this, and
it will have an effect on the players...
>>>>>>>>>>
PC\'s aren\'t the only ones who correlate data. As my players learned in
my old superhero RPG, otherwise normal people can have unsettlingly
good detective work skills. The players aren\'t the only ones who are going
to notice the chain of disasters that are always one step behind the
player characters. The PC\'s might be the always-missed target, but the
first idea our NPC detective may come up with is that they are the
cause.

It\'s hard to be a moving target while sitting in jail. Those prison guards
won\'t be much protection against something that cracks space
stations.

Walt Smith
