    'month' => '11',
    'topic' => ' The Republic Question',
    'body' => '>Silly question. What are the rules (if any) governing *leaving* the
>European Union. For that materr what are the rules on *joining*?
>(*those* exist!).
>
>- --
>Leonard Erickson (aka Shadow)


If a country chose to leave, there would be nothing the EU could do about
it, even if they wanted to.  Remember the EU doesn\'t have an army, and
doesn\'t even really have a government.  Things are more likely to work the
other way round. A country could cause just use its veto to bring the EU to
a grinding halt and then they would probably be forced out (one way or
another).  Of course, for those countries in the single currency (or at
least when they issue bank notes), this would casue all sorts of problems -
imagine one country that decides it is going to print more bank notes.

As to how a country would decide to leave - that woudl be up to them.  In
the case of the UK, I can\'t image it happening without a referendum, but we
don\'t have any \'right\' to one.  Maybe other countries have a right to
referendums in their consitiutions (I think Switzerland does, but they\'re
not in the EU)  but the UK doesn\'t have a consitution.

Mark.
