> The AFP were formed in 1979.  As a direct result of the Hilton Bombing.

Oops!  I might have been thinking about some intelligence outfit or other,
or I may have just plain got it wrong.  I vaguely recall some outfit of
this kind being set up (using British and US models) around about this
time.  Of course it wasn\'t just this episode that caused it - the whole
anti-conscription thing was a threat to law and order, and the British
Empire, and God and the Protestant Churches too...

I checked on this one, but the first Intelligence body to be set up was the
Intelligence Corps, established on 6th of December 1907. Prior to this,
Australia\'s first military spy was William Throsby Bridges, who was sent to
New Caledonia to draw up plans of the French defences at Noumea. His cover
was that he was a traveller for Dalgety\'s, a pastoral and trading company.
The British had requested this mission to be conducted, however Australia
had a choice between Samoa or New Caledonia. The deciding factor in the
mission came down to a 2 pound difference in ticket prices. After the
mission was conducted, the British Government refused to pay expenses for
the mission and Bridges was left with the bill. I guess it might have been
an early form of "denying all knowledge".

There are no other records of any Australian intelligence body prior to
1907, and the 1903 incident is only known about because Bridges eventually
became the Commanding officer of Duntroon, the Royal Military College.
