    'body' => '> Date: Mon, 15 Nov 1999 18:46:02 -0800
> From: "Luther Martin" <martin@ksarul.com>
> 
> How do you manuever any distance in space safely without using a computer?

Easy.

Well, not *easy*, but certainly possible.  Using a sextant-like
instrument, an ephemeris (printed), and fixes on nearby bodies (star,
world, one or more moons, fixed stars for reference frame) you could get a
reasonably good position fix.  Do one of those every half hour or so and
you get your velocity, and over time your acceleration.  Knowing the
masses and radii of all the bodies (again, from a printed table) and the
principles of orbital dynamics, shaping a desired orbit is an exercise in
solving simultaneous diffy-Qs...no picnic, but people did it way back when
before all these here \'puters came along and spoiled the fun.

Note that doing manual orbital calculations, especially near a body, is
much harder if you are accelerating due to more than gravity -- that is,
if your \'sail\' is active/unfurled/deployed.  So to hit a narrow course
window accurately, you might want to get on course for it and then go
ballistic through it.  Conversely, though, continuing to get solar
acceleration longer makes for a faster run, so going ballistic is a bad
thing.  And there\'s our element of skill, neatly back into the picture.
And tension, too, as the front-runners head toward a grav-assisted turn
around a small moon and each waits to see if and when the others furl
sails.  Add in the fact that solar wind comes in gusts and not always
straight from the star and this is starting to look like an exciting sport
again!

