  {
    'body' => 'At 11:29 AM 11/16/99 -0500, you wrote:
>>I always judge that there are many ways to say a single name, due to
>>dialect differences and such. Also, lots local names for the same system
>>might be in use, due to different languages, cultural reasons et al.
>
>One name that illustrates this well is "Ivan".  In its natural russian, is
>pronounced "EE-vahn".  In the U.S., we say "EYE-van".
>
>Now I wonder how those pesky Vargr would say it?  Oh and what\'s Vargr for
>"milkbone"?  :)
>
>___________________________________________________________
> J-Man

        I don\'t know what is worse, the fact you asked, or the fact I sat
down with AM:3 and figured out the answer.

        Ivan actually, is two syllables.  Under the word-gen tables on pp14,
that isn\'t doable.  The closest Gvegh will let you get is *spelt* "Ivan" but
pronounced "EYE-veh-An" -- three syllables.

        Now, "milkbone" is probably translated as "human wants a fight", but
we\'ll ignore that issue =).  Now, looking at the selected Gvegh words on
pp22 and pp23 finds nothing "canon" for either "milk" or "bone".  I suppose
you could presume that it\'d be an imported foodstuff and use "zduekhnge
foeloel koers" (literally "exotic friend foods", presuming that you never
tell the speaker *what* Milkbone is used for on Terra).  However, you are
essentially left stuck with the word generation tables.
        A quick visit to said tables results in the following:
"Khozul-Uer".  For reasons of perversity and flavour (excuse the pun), I\'d
suggest it to be a non-litteral iterpretation...  "Uer" to mean "bones or of
skeletal nature" and "Khozul" to mean "litter\'s milk".

        --Michel
        (who likes the Vargr as a concept race)


