> subsonics. 

I wrote :-
> i. Disorienting agents
> - smoke, hallucinogens, light, sonics, other sensory distractors.

\'Sonics\' includes infra-, ultra-, and audible frequencies, yes?

<Subsonics>
> They are directional, nausea inducing (they disturb a variety of
> systems, including the vestibular and digestive), and can safely be used
> with CS or other flamables, as they do not induce that much heating.

There are problems with organ resonance at high enough power levels
(well below the 220dB level required to bore through concrete). IIRC
hollow organs e.g. stomach and intestine can be disrupted with
infrasound.
	You are correct in that cavitation and heating effects are not an issue
until you get to ultrasound frequencies in the megahertz range (a
\'juiced up\' diagnostic ultrasound machine could be quite dangerous, if
you could touch someone with the transducer).

> Another possibility, at least in the traveller universe:
> Psionicological field inhibitors.
The logical thing to use would be mini-Empress Wave generators -
psionically assault the crowd, or induce feelings of hopelessness, etc.
	Canon more or less prohibits the \'mechanical\' duplication of psionics
until well above Impy TLs, anyway (but gravisonic modulation and
psi-shield fields are an obvious exception to this).

> I do know that certain forms of RF have severe brain-disturbing
> tendancies...
EM induction. This is the basis of magnetic cortical stimulation which
has been used as an alternative to electroshock therapy in depression.
Works reasonably well (but not as well as \'dial a smile\').

At Traveller TLs... I think Imperial cultural mores prevent ranged
devices of this sort from being developed. Certainly possible though
given the perfomance of sensor tech.

> Another idea: Use a damper field to increase decay in the area of a group
> of rioters.
The most abundant radioactive isotope in a human is potassium-40 (which
makes up 0.0118% of your body potassium or some 0.0157g in a 70kg male).
	This contributes about 30 millirem per year to the average annual
radiation exposure of 100 millirems.
	Fizzing that off might do some damage.

Robert O\'Connor
Medico, Gamer
