  {
    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> The problem is that things move *really* fast in space. How fast is the
> Earth moving in its orbit? How fast are the other planets moving? I believe
> that manuevering in space to the extent you would need to participate in an
> interplanetary race is infeasible without computer assistance.

Earth orbits at 30-40 km/sec (too lazy to look up the exact figure). At
1 g, constant boost, you hit 40 km/sec in 1 hour, 6 minutes and 40
seconds. 

With thruster plate drives that can operate all thru the inner system,
you can simply *look up* the position of the target planet at various
points in the future, figure the distance versus your accel (don\'t
forget to allow for turnover halfway!) and aim at more or less the
point it\'ll be at when you get there.

Solar gravity and other factors will throw you off a bit, but you can
*manually* correct for the errors. 

With a 1-g or more, constant boost ship, you can almost literally
"point and go". There are better trajectories than the one you\'d get
that way. But if you aim for where you expect the planet to be, you are
close enough to an optimum orbit that it doesn\'t make a lot of
difference. 

