<snip>

> A way to use this in a game: have things happen in the background of=20
> wherever the players are, to make them suspect that maybe someone *is*
> out to get them. They take train from point A to point B on planet X;
> later that day, there\'s a big train wreck on planet X. The PCs visit a
> space station; after they leave, the station\'s reactor core goes critical
> and blows up, taking half the station with it.... Keep doing this, and
> it will have an effect on the players...

Something *I* discovered is that in a long running campaign, it pays to
let the players brief new players on the "background" and "history" of
the campaign. You\'ll find that they\'ll have invented all sorts of
details that you never gave them, and linked things you never thought
of connecting.

An example was this *elliptical* crater, partly filled with water in
the area the D&D players were campaigning in. They had visted it
*once*, in *daylight*. Yet I heard them tell new players about how the
pool glowed in the dark. Thus are myths created and legends born.

Players are *always* "unconsciously" filling in details. And by letting
them brief newbies, you find out about these "fill ins". Then you can
either adopt them, or you can not them down and wait for a chance to
use them to trip up the players by having these assumptions prove
*wrong*. 

