> to notice the chain of disasters that are always one step behind the
> player characters. The PC\'s might be the always-missed target, but the
> first idea our NPC detective may come up with is that they are the
> cause.
>
> It\'s hard to be a moving target while sitting in jail. Those prison guards
> won\'t be much protection against something that cracks space
> stations.

Then there\'s always the "Dirty Pair" scenario. Kei & Yuri are a pair of
top notch law enforcement types. There\'s just this one *little*
problem. Whenever they get involved, disasters happen. It\'s 100%
demostrable that it simply is *not* their fault. Their actions don\'t
cause the disasters, and there\'s nothing they could have done to
prevent them. Nonetheless, disasters occur. 

A *minor* example was when they were *passing thru* a space station. A
robbery went bad and one of the crooks accidentaly activated a bomb that
not merely blew a hole in the hull, it ble it right at an airtight
bulkhead, thus compromising *two* sections of the station.

This gives the "Lovely Angels" (their code name) the unofficial tag of
"the Dirty Pair" and means that *nobody* wants to work with them. 

Have someone like that following the PCs. Possibly for benign reasons
(maybe they are shadowing the characters waiting for an old enemy to
attack them). 

The players will go nuts. And just think of the fun if/when they
determine the *cause*. 

Player1: "I\'m gonna *kill* those jinxes!"
Player2: "You can\'t do that! They work for Imperial Security"
Player3: "And besides, just imagine what could go wrong if you were
         *trying* to commit violence in that \'jinx field\' of theirs!"
         <shudder>
