>
> Therefore \'Spasm\' is a cute drug, but makes very little pharmacological
> or physiological sense. Consider me one of the upset.
>
> i. Drugs have to get to their site of action. Usually this is via the
> circulation, unless the agent is delivered directly.
>         Combine this with uptake time and you have a delay of at least 30
> seconds (arm-brain circulation time, with optimised IV medications).
>         Heck, cyanide will take at least five minutes to kill you (though
> you\'re unconscious and fitting within 60 seconds, usually).

Ok, so it isn\'t "instantly". 

> ii. There is no functional difference down to a receptor level between
> various beds of skeletal (striated) muscle. If the limb muscles are
> paralysed, then the chest wall and diaphragm will go too.
>         If these muscles are \'locked\', it will become impossible to
> artificially ventilate the victim with any degree of safety.
>         (I\'ve been at resucitations like this, folks. They are *scary*).
>         If you can\'t breathe or have someone breathe for you, you will almost
> certainly die. Access to cardiopulmonary bypass (or, in Trav, low
> berths) isn\'t guaranteed. Irreparable damage may occur before the
> subject is ready to go on the pump/in the cooler (though this is less
> likely with higher TLs).

I know for a *fact* that there are surgical muscle relaxants that *do*
only effect the "voluntary" muscles. They leave the heart and lungs
alone. Mind you, I seem to recall that they do this by blocking nerve
impulses from the spine, rather than by directly affecting the muscles...

>> This makes it an *ideal* military weapon, in that it ties up a maximal
>> amount of enemy resources in caring for the victim. Yet it\'s not even
>> lethal, so you can play things down if you accidentally shoot a few
>> "innocent bystanders".
>
> The polio epidemic of the 1950\'s springs to mind. There were *wards*
> full of people on \'iron lungs\' and pedal powered ventilators all over
> the developed world.
>
> Nightmarish stuff. It would only take one riot to overload the critical
> care facilities of a good sized (pop 3 million+) city at current tech
> levels.
>         In a combat situation, a lot of people would die, either from inability
> to get to them in time, or on the basis of triage (save the \'Spasm\'
> victims or the multi trauma casualties - I assume bombs and
> bullets/beams would still be used?).
>
> I don\'t think \'Spasm\' makes a good riot control agent, for the reasons I
> have touched on above, unless you are uninterested in the survival of
> the rioters (and part of the plausibility of your narrative). 
> Perhaps the mere threat of its use would prevent riots.

Spasm *wasn\'t* a riot control agent. It was a load for a very
specialized weapon. It was *targeted*, not sprayed indiscriminately. 

You seem to have rolled the comments on spetsdods (an odd "hand
weapon") and anti-riot measures into one. They were seperate subjects.


> ii. Incapacitating agents
> - an aerosol sedative ;
> - an agent to interrupt the motor pathways in such a fashion as to cause
> transient Parkinsonian motor signs (you can\'t riot much faster than a
> slow shuffle and you can\'t change direction or stop without assistance)
> i.e. a *very selective* dopamine receptor blocker ;
> - \'soma\', from Huxley\'s \'Brave New World\' ;
> - descendants of modern agents (e.g. CS) with shorter onset and offset
> times and fewer spillover side effects.
> - immobilising foam and slipping agents (which have already been
> mentioned).

Real world items:

A derivative of one of the high blood pressure meds. It slowly lowers
your blood pressure. After a while, you get faint if you are standing.
So you sit down (or fall down) after more time, you are faint even
sitting up, so you lie down or fall down. Now, you are flat on your
back, and getting over excited will tend to make you pass out. Now the
riot police can collect you.

A derivative of that surgical muscle relaxant I mentioned. The effects
start at the base of the spine and work up. So you lose control of your
feet and ankles, then of the knees, etc, until you are effectively a
(temporary) quadraplegic. Again, at this point the police wander over
and pick you up. 

Supposedly both of these are hard to administer overdoses of, and have
limited effects (ie the blood pressure won\'t drop too low, and the
"nerve block" stops before it gets too high up the spine).

