    'index' => 'ee204',
    'body' => '>From: "Thomas Vickers" <redroach@flex.net>
>Subject: Re: some thoughts about racing
...
>Any such technical problems for traveller?  Precise jump exiting? Exiting
>closer to way points?

  If one wants to follow Triplanetary (and of course, one does :> ), then
real racers would use ion drives - low thrust, high-fuel efficiency for
those _long_ races. And then you could simulate Triplanetary one turn of
double thrust to represent a long burn over the drives safe on-line duration,
to be followed by maintenance before being allowed again.

  You could also have crew aboard to perform that maintenance to allow
multiple long burns during a single leg of a race; a crit failure on 
the relevant skill roll might mean that the drive may remain off-line
totally for one turn.

  If other crew have roles (no/minimal computers means that you want a
navigator, or all skills are penalized if performing multiple roles),
then the designer also needs to decide between having lots of crew, or
getting more reaction mass into the tanks.

  Given that a very small crew may be highly over-worked - making the
race a matter of skill, design, and the endurance of both the ship and
its complement - we can only await FS chemical amplification programs,
or the Sayat\'s ever so loosely-interpreted definition of "design/ship/
abominations-of-genetic-engineering".

        Steven Hudson
