    'index' => 'ee243',
    'body' => 'On Wed, 17 Nov 1999 16:35:37 -0500 (EST), Walter Smith
<SmithW@HARTWICK.EDU> wrote:

>Question for the law enforcement types on the list: if a cop chases a
>bad guy, and the bad guy does something very destructive in an escape
>attempt, (say, drives a truck at high speed through a crowded pedestrian 
>mall,) does the peace officer get blamed? Or does he just get blamed if
>the chase was not successful in catching the criminal?

It depends on the jurisdiction - and that doesn\'t necessarily
mean the _police_department_ jurisdiction in question.  For
example, all five boroughs/counties of New York City are serviced
by the same New York City Police Department - but if the scenario
you describe happens in the Bronx, the cop is held fully
responsible (if a black man is arrested by a white cop, and has a
heart attack in custody, it\'s a racist murder), whereas in
mid-Manhattan, the cop will get screwed for engaging in an unsafe
chase against department policy, but the scumbag he was chasing
will get nailed for the pedestrians.

I\'m sorry; do I sound bitter or cynical in the above? If so, it\'s
because I am; I\'m not a cop (civilian computer geek working for
the NYPD), but I\'ve seen good cops get screwed or worse because
of shit like this.

Disclaimer: The New York City Police Department allows me to have
my own opinions.  Since they do, and I do, I don\'t post theirs.
Besides, I pay for this account with my own money.
