    'ts-index' => '1999-11-18.ee276',
    'body' => 'My apologies for sending this to the list... I couldn\'t find the original
posts in the thread, and I\'m hoping that it finds the right people. I will
gladly take it offlist.

From: Kyle Schuant <kyle3054@yahoo.com>


>> Kyle wrote:
>> >Creepy stuff! That particular game I dislike because done as it\'s
>>  >intended, it\'s all rather dark and depressing.

To be fair to the Storyteller System games, they\'re not supposed to be
really all that depressing, and most of the darkness is purely a matter of
style. When played "right", Vampire is really about tragic heroism. Check
out the section on Humanity if you don\'t believe me. Every other game in the
Storyteller System line has something similar built in, whether it\'s part of
the plot, as it is with the struggle against dark forces for control of
reality in Mage, or part of the system, as it is with Vampire and Werewolf,
or a little of both, as it is in Wraith.

Ultimately, the tragedy in the various White Wolf games comes from the
alienation and isolation inherent in the settings. That\'s nothing new for
cultural heroes in America. In westerns, it\'s common for the lone gun
fighting hero to ride off into the sunset as a sad song plays. Police
heroes, like Dirty Harry, are alienated from their peers due to their work
ethic, as well as their community at large. Bruce Willis has made a career
playing the embittered, alienated and isolated hero.


>> >I think a dark seesion or two is great, but ultimately if I want
>> >to be a misanthropic socially isolated angst-ridden strange dude
>> >(like vampires are supposed to be according to most players), I\'d
>> >say could probably manage that in real life (not that I have, thank
>> >G-d!) And if it ain\'t done that way, it\'s just meaningless slaughter,
>> >and incomprehensible politics.


Considering the fact that most roleplayers, especially young roleplayers,
are *already* socially isolated "strange dudes", and the fact that young
people today are literally filled to the brim with anxiety, it\'s not hard to
see the appeal. Most of them *are* managing that in real life already.

Take a look at the various "character classes" in the Storyteller Systems
games, take out the various supernatural elements, and if you\'re between the
age of 16 and 25 or so - maybe even a little older - you\'ll likely see the
bare bones of one or more people you already know.

Still, it is entirely possible to play a game in the Storyteller System that
doesn\'t collapse into angsty cheese or meaningless slaughter. In my own
experience, it\'s also relatively common. *All* roleplaying games have the
capacity to collapse into either mindless cliches or meaningless slaughter.
The accusation is usually levelled at AD&D and Vampire... but, it\'s more a
matter of popularity than anything else. If Traveller were to suddenly
replace Vampire in market share tomorrow, it would be less than a week
before people would criticize Traveller for the same reason. I\'m not
highlighting the critics as much as the players.

Yeah, popular games are going to draw lots of folks, especially younger
folks, who are going to play adventures and campaigns filled with
meaningless slaughter. Some of these folks will fall away and leave the
hobby entirely due to boredom, others will get bored and become "mature"
roleplayers and stick with the hobby.

>Jeff wrote:


[I\'m not sure who the Jeff is to whom I am responding here... I couldn\'t
find the original post]

>> No argument from me - I never saw the point of the whole \'neo-
>> Goth\' movement. I don\'t know how old you are, and won\'t venture a
>> guess ([Kyle is 28], but in my case, I see it as a reaction to the
>> excessive liberalism, sweetness, and light that was preached from
>> every rooftop during the \'60s and \'70s - these are today\'s kids
>>\'rebelling\' against the parents who were the rebels during that era.

I can see where you\'re coming from, but the "excessive liberalism" is
slightly out of place. It\'s not like goths are embracing some sort of
fascistic ideology or anything. The goth / industrial movement has always
been utterly fascinated with the late 60s, usually directly via covers,
samples... but in other ways that aren\'t directly apparent. There are too
many to list here, but the late 60s and early 70s *did* have their "dark"
moments and music as well. While people were chanting "Make Love Not War"
the Stones were releasing Beggar\'s Banquet and singing "I was around when
Jesus Christ had his moment of doubt and pain". Then there was David Bowie
and the androgynous glam movement. Let\'s put it this way: it was no accident
that Peter Murphy, the singer for Bauhaus (one of the earliest lights in the
goth movement), covered Bowie -nay... emulated Bowie down to the last
detail - and named his label Beggar\'s Banquet. It\'s no accident that most
goths have their Bowie collection.

Of course, there were lots of other things going on in the 60s and early 70s
as well that contributed, in one way or another: the God is dead movement,
the occult revival, the exploitation film boom...

To say that it\'s the movement is merely a reaction is to grossly
oversimplify things.

>[Kyle: I see it more as a nihilistic kind of thing, certainly that of a
>Vampire is a life pretty much devoid of meaning, everything
>ultimately coming don to animal survival, there being no "higher
>values."]


Well, to focus on one small segment of a movement in the way that it
interacts with our own hobby is sort of like focusing on those roleplayers
who like to "freak the mundanes" at cons and saying that they are typical of
gamers.

Even so, I know more than a few goths who would balk at being labelled
nihilistic. Some are quite bouncy and obnoxiously happy. Even among those
who aren\'t bouncy, nihilism is really pretty rare. Your average goth is
hopelessly romantic, and fascinated to some degree with all things mystical,
mythical and philosophical.

You don\'t have to trust me on this one. At one point in their life, most
goths will read, enjoy, and be influenced by the DC / Vertigo comic "The
Sandman". Head down to your local comic store and pick up one of the trade
paperback collections and tell me how nihilistic you think the series is. ;)

>Jeff:
>> Also, to some extent, people are \'growing up\' too fast these days,

>> becoming \'too sophisticated\' before they\'ve been able to just have

>> fun.  That leads to the \'method acting\' style of rle-playing - not

>> automatically a bad thing, but it leads to a gaming style that feels
>> \'forced\' or artificial.

That\'s an awfully strange way of getting from point A to point B. I\'m
surprised that the "method acting" approach didn\'t come sooner, since
roleplaying games are frequently popular - with good reason -among high
school drama types. It was a direction that roleplaying games were bound to
go in eventually. I think that the origins of this style of roleplaying go
back quite a bit further, though. I\'ve been winding my way through the
Dragon Magazine archive, and I came across an old article by Gary Gygax
decrying the growing trend of gamers who were putting the playing of roles
above the "action".

Keep in mind there\'s always been a crossover of "dress up" types in
roleplaying fandom. The large SCA crossover, for example. I\'m really not
sold on the "growing up to fast" angle.

>> but the idea is to act like your character would, based on the
>> situation, as though it  were real life - not some sort of dramatic
>> presentation

Just to play devil\'s advocate here: Who says? ;)

>>(which is  what most neo-Goth theme games encourage).


To some extent, yeah, but every game system encourages *some* sort of play
that others don\'t. The D&D line, for example, tends to encourage the dungeon
crawl. Traveller tends to encourage mercenary and merchant campaigns...
Every game brings *something* that is "unique" to the table.

>Kyle wrote:
>> >I always felt that a roleplaying session should be fun. Sometimes
>> >it\'s fun to be scared, or in a dark atmosphere, or worried, or
>> >disgusted, but ultimately...


I think that you\'re taking such concepts as scare factor, a dark atmosphere,
and anxiety *much* more seriously than the average Vampire player does.

>[Kyle writes: Well, I say, those that don\'t take on
>the kids, shouldn\'t complain that there are so few in
>roleplaying today, so few at conventions!]


Yep, at least *something* I can agree with.
