    'body' => 'Chris Seamans wrote:
> To be fair to the Storyteller System games, they\'re not supposed to be
> really all that depressing, and most of the darkness is purely a
> matter of style. When played "right", Vampire is really about tragic
> heroism. Check out the section on Humanity if you don\'t believe me.
> Every other game in the Storyteller System line has something similar
> built in, whether it\'s part of the plot, as it is with the struggle
> against dark forces for control of reality in Mage, or part of the
> system, as it is with Vampire and Werewolf, or a little of both, as it
> is in Wraith.
<snip>

Vampire et al are my primary games, and I find myself disagreeing with
what has been said here on the list (although not with Chris in
particular).

Vampire can (like every RPG) be used in many different ways. I prefer to
run scenarios with intrigue, personal relations, and social conflicts.
Kind of like a soap opera, but with fangs. I find it refreshing to play
a game where the "objective" is seldom to kill your opponents, instead
discrediting them and so on.

I agree with the "tragic hero" idea somewhat, but that doesn\'t need to
hold true for every character in a game (although one or two characters
are usually played that way regardless). I would rather call Vampire a
game about morality. Which part of that concept (villain, hero) the
player characters take is up to the players/GM.

/Jens \'Spacejens\' Rydholm
