    'date' => 'Thu, 18 Nov 1999 12:10:22  0500',
    'body' => 'While there is some stuff in this post that relates to Traveller, it\'s going
extremely off topic extremely fast. Please post any replies that don\'t have
to do with my characterizations of Traveller to me personally. I will be
responding to any response personally. Sorry for taking up the bandwidth.

From: Kyle Schuant <kyle3054@yahoo.com>


>That\'s alright, Chris, it was my fault. It was a discussion that Jeff
>Zeitlin and I began a couple days ago, which we thought could go
>onto the TML. My editing skills are not too hot, hopefully it was

>readable:)


It was plenty readable. ;)

>Yes, and AD&D isn\'t supposed to be a dungeon crawl,

>either. But when you\'re writing, you have to consider

>not only what you write, but who\'s going to read it,

>and how they\'ll interpret it.


On the contrary, AD&D is supposed to work best for dungeon crawls.
Everything about the game, from the proliferation of underground beasties to
the party dynamic is aimed toward the dungeon crawl.

I also disagree that the makers of a game - or anything else for that
matter - have some sort of obligation to take possible misinterpretations
into account.

>Quite true, and for me that makes these settings a
>problem - a "party" makes little sense (except perhaps
>in Werewolf, where they\'re a "pack").

Let\'s face it, a party makes little sense in *most* roleplaying games, and a
GM, or the players, have to come up with all sorts of reasons why their
characters would be together in the first place. I remember when I first
bought MegaTraveller and saw all of the careers in the character generation
system I found it difficult to imagine building a party from such disparate
character types.

Whatever its other faults may be, AD&D does a wonderful job of this by
building character interdependence into the rules. Traveller does it by way
of background. One of the reasons that merchant and mercenary campaigns are
so popular in travel is that the background props up such games. Vampire
takes a little from column A and a little from column B. The clans play off
of each other mechanically, and they fit into certain roles within a party.
The background is also rich enough that reasons for getting parties together
grow out of this.

The dirty little secret of roleplaying games is that the real reason for a
party in any game is that a bunch of friends get together around a table and
choose to spend their time playing a game. Whether this is supported in the
game by the rules or background doesn\'t matter.

Still, to get back around to your original point, although the essence of
the game is the tragedy inherent in the isolation of the characters -
usually from mortal society, but frequently from vampiric (or supernatural
society) as well - the characters all share that same alienation. To say
that folks in such situations can\'t band together on some level, even if
it\'s simply a result of their alienation, is to deny that a group of
alienated kids would sit around a table and roleplay in the first place.

>And I\'ve seen
>that typically people do create such characters, which
>then utterly fail to co-operate. I agree that we need
>something better than "you meet in an inn and decide
>to adventure together" to keep the group together,
>some deeper reason, but I just don\'t see how it can
>happen in the World of Darkness.


Well, to be fair, the Storyteller System is rich with possibilities. There
are so many levels of supernatural conpiracy going at any given time that
it\'s not really all that difficult to come up with reasons for why the
party\'s together.

Of course, as I pointed out above, the real reason that a party forms is
that you\'ve got a bunch of friends sitting around a table in real life. I
don\'t think that a game even requires that the party has a "reason" for
being together.

>So why reinforce the troubles they already have?


Who says it reinforces anything? I don\'t like reading to much into what a
game might possibly "reinforce". After all, if we were to dissect Traveller
with the same scalpel, we might not find things that are all that pleasant.
If we simply focus on the popular mercenary-style campaigns, we find a
setting that seems to reinforce doing really nasty and distasteful things -
like punching holes in people with a gauss rifle - for the purpose of
profit.

Still, I\'m not really in agreement with the idea that games reinforce
behavior. Once you open that floodgate, you drown the entire roleplaying
industry and you admit that every media slander against roleplaying, every
negative stereotype, and groups like Mothers Against Dungeons & Dragons are
all *right*.

>better a game which encourages sociability,
>co-operation, and so on. But perhaps I\'m thiking too
>much of the "mentoring" aspects of GMing younger
>players.


I think that you are thinking too much of the "mentoring" aspects of GMing
younger players. You seem to have an interest in younger players, I advise
that you get out and try to understand what the world looks like from their
point of view. With all due respect, you seem to have some misunderstandings
about it already, and I sincerely don\'t mean that as an insult.

>You\'re right, there. But some systems, some genres,
>lend themselves more easily to that than others. Hands
>up those who\'ve given up on, or never entered a Star
>Wars game because they were overwhelmed by film quotes
>and cliches?:)

Perhaps, but across the board from RPG fandom there are all too frequent
criticisms of the way that the two top games are "played wrong", or played
in a way that to others is essentially "hollow" in some way. I do think that
if T5 came out tomorrow and that through some stroke of divine providence it
found itself as one of the top games we\'d find the same kind of collapse
into cliches and the same breakdown into mindless slaughter.

Having been on the list long enough, I\'ve seen enough  anecdotal evidence
that lots of Traveller games do break down into one (or both) of those
camps. It\'s something that the industry is extremely self-conscious of, but
which is ultimately detrimental to the hobby as a whole.

>No, it\'s a complete lack of an ideology - a nihilism,
>or the pseudo-religion of armchair
>self-psychoanalysis.


Well, no, it\'s not really either of the above. The Storyteller System may
posture itself in a certain way with some degree of "self help" talk, to
attach that same concept to a larger movement borders on absurdity. It\'s
just simply not true of the larger movement. Goth is not the complete lack
of ideology any more than the romantic movement in art, literature and
philsophy was. I can hit my record collection, or my book collection and
come up with an astonishing amount of information to support my claim. Don\'t
take my word for it, though, if you don\'t believe me, do your own research.

>Certainly I don\'t think all World of Darkness players
>are Goths. But you don\'t find many Goths playing
>Traveller, that\'s for sure.


I think you may be surprised. I know that fully half of my gaming group were
goths, and nearly all of the members of my gaming group have some sort of
direct connection with the scene.

>Maybe we just have more depressed Goths Down Under?


Probably not *different* goths, if the movement looks anything like the way
it looks in the U.S. and Britain, and I\'m betting that barring minor
differences it does. I\'m not saying that goths aren\'t depressed or that
those who aren\'t don\'t appear that way. I\'m saying that the depression or
the affect of depression doesn\'t flow from the wellspring of nihilism.

If you just think about it for a moment, you\'ll see why I\'m saying that.
What\'s there to be depressed about if you don\'t believe in anything?

In reality, there are things that pop-up time and time again in the goth
movement. Interpersonal relationships, or, to put a fine point on it, "love"
is the backbone of the goth movement. The word "love" is probably the most
often repeated in goth songs. The concept of love is at the center of much
of the literature.

There\'s also the religious paradox. Despite the fact that most goths reject
traditional religion, and many reject non-traditional religions, Christian
(and specifically Catholic) imagery, symbolism and trappings are central to
the movement. Even when religions are attacked in, say, music, it\'s usually
the perceived insincerity of religious institutions that is criticized.

The closely linked industrial movement frequently deals with politics and
economy. I\'m already way off topic here though.

>By "method acting" we mean people becoming deeply
>involved in their characters, to an almost
>pathological degree. Taking themselves WAY too
>seriously.

Perhaps, but have you considered the distinct possibility that *you\'re*
taking *them* too seriously? Or that, in point of fact, there are folks who
find that to be more fun than, say, the more traditional concept of
roleplaying as rolling dice and deciding what combat your characters are
going to get into next, or trying to figure out how much money you\'re going
to make when you unload your cargo of groat\'s milk at the next port, or how
much gold you\'re going to snatch up from the third level of the dungeon?

>I\'m not too sold on the "growing up too
>fast" idea, either, not when so many are thirty years
>old living with their parents and never held a steady
>job types. Kids today, it seems to me, are learning
>the hard stuff, drugs and violence, without learning
>the more pleasant stuff - work, relationships
>(committed).


That is, of course, if you think of "work" and "committed relationships" as
"the more pleasant stuff". When I say that, I say that with the utmost
seriousness. Adam Smith, a central figure in the development of the
capitalist ideology *didn\'t* share the same opinion of "work". Of course,
"work" today is a really loaded term, it encompasses those things that are
"jobs" (and I don\'t see why any kid should think of flipping beef patties at
McDonald\'s as pleasant), "careers" (which are rapidly being phased out in
America and other parts of the West), and "callings" (I don\'t mean that in
the religious sense either, still, they are tough to come by these days).

Committed relationships... well, of course, let\'s just say that they\'re not
what they used to be. In the Western world, we\'re living in a society where
therapists spit on love by calling it "co-dependence" and equate it with an
addiction, while schizophrenically holding onto an ideal that true love wins
out over all.

Boy, with such competing viewpoints, is it any wonder that so many Western
relationships are doomed to failure?

Still, in order to really do a fair treatment of that subject, I\'d have to
go back over the course of 200 - 250 years to find the root of the problem,
and I simply can\'t justify the use of such bandwidth. In this case, I\'ll
simply point you to "After Virtue" by MacIntyre, which deals with the
general erosion of morality and ethics in modernity[1], and "Habits of the
Heart" by Bellah et. al. which concerns itself specifically with seeing how
the problems of modernity[1] manifest themselves in American life. Both are
excellent books, and I highly recommend them.

[1] Modernity in this sense is not used to describe "today" but to describe
the Enlightenment and post-Enlightenment trends.
