    'body' => 'Robert Prior wrote:

> >Racing will be simply an exercise in computing. Given any course, whether or
> >not it includes direction changes, it will be an easy exercise in TL10+
> >computing to find an optimal course. You just start your ship on a
> >preprogrammed course and wait for it to cross the finish line. To make
> >racing interesting, you need some sort of dynamic inputs.
 
> Kinda like yacht-racing and computer-designed ships?
 
> Two suggestions:
 
> Limit computers. Sure, you _have_ the TL10+ computers, but if you run
> anything but the official nav package you are disqualified. In an
> emergency, you run the fancy "get me out of here" application which flies
> your ship (but then you\'re out of the race).
 
> Include a refueling skim. You fly to the gas giant, skim to refuel, and fly
> back. Plenty of room for piloting down in the smoke.

IMTU, as part of the Mark system\'s Centennial Celebration a sail race
is taking place. The race is from mainworld orbit to an asteroid in
the belt, around a marker there, across the belt to a second marker,
then out to a gas giant where they slingshot to a second gas giant
further out. A final slingshot and the ships sail back in to orbit
around the mainworld. The winner is the first ship that successfully
docks with the christmas tree back at the UpPort. (IOW, getting back
fast is great, but you have to decelerate and dock at the end of the
flight.)  The contestants aren\'t allowed any navigational equipment
beyond handheld astrolabes, and all maneuvering is down by setting
lines on the sails. Support and media ships are traveling along with
the contestants to rescue anyone that gets in serious trouble.

The PC\'s passed the race on it\'s outbound leg as they entered the
system a couple weeks ago. They\'ll probably pass it again on their way
out, as it will be near their route from Mark to the Segui jump point.
If *nothing* else it provides some local color. <g>

Eris
