    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> why not have a race through an asteriod belt, having to go past a set of
> beacons making up different stages. that way it will be more like a car
> rally than deep sea yachting, so  the circuit isn\'t too large and that way
> you would be able to have enough camera ships to get a good look at the
> action. The course could be arrranged so you could go the longer but safer
> route through the asteroids or the quicker but more dangerous route, and
> you could change between stages or try half the safe then swap over to the
> dangerous mid stage, and  then the final stage would be a sprint to the 
> finish

Asteroid belts aren\'t like in the movies. Except for the occasional
double or triple asteroid (asteroids orbiting each other), you\'d need a
telescope to see one asteroid from another. 

Work out the math. The main belt is centered at about 2.5 AU. Let\'s
assume all the asteroids are in the plane of the ecliptic, and within
.5 AU of the 2.5 AU mark. That gives us a flat ring from 2.0 AU to 3.0
AU. That gives an area of 15.7 AU^2 or 353 *quadrillion* km^2.

Assume there are a *million* asteroids of size worth worrying about.
That means each has (on average) 353 billion km^2 to wander around in.
Which makes their average seperation about 594,000 km.

In the real world, there are only about 10,000 asteroids of that size
(1/100th as many) which means they are *ten* times as far apart. About
6 million km.

But a race of the "you have to make contact with these asteroids, in
any order" sort could still be interesting, simply because of the way
the orbital dynamics work.

A good way to get a "feel" for this sort of thing is to try to find a
copy of the old SPI "Battlefleet Mars" game. It\'s got a map of the
inner Solar System, with the planetary orbits divided into one day
chunks. So each "day" of play, you move the planet counters one space
along their orbits. 

It\'s also got rules for figuring ship trajectories between the planets.

I\'d advise refs that plan "in system" adventures that cover multiple
planets, or have the players frequently visiting the same system, to
draw up such a map. It can make keeping track of where things are
easier. 

Some day, I\'ll write a program to do that sort of thing. If I\'m feeling
ambitious, I\'ll even try to port it to the Mac.

