    'month' => '11',
    'topic' => 'MTU Imperial Justice (was: IMoJ)',
    'body' => '>Robert said:
>>>I think there was an article, "Law in the Imperium," back in
>>>Challenge, which spoke about the Imperial Ministry Of Justice (IMOJ)
>>>and gave some statistics for the number of agents.
>[snip]
>>There was. Unfortunately, the article reads very much like a summary of
>>common law as it exists in America.
>[snip]
>>Extremely disappointing, especially when you consider all the possibilities
>>that were ignored.
>
>Would you like to elaborate? Give us some new ideas about the MoJ, since its
>canon is patchy.

OK, here goes.  As far as I know, my take on this doesn\'t contradict any
Classic Traveller canon (except the article). I totally ignore IRIS, as
that was a variant (according to the original IRIS article). Besides, I
think the whole idea of IRIS as presented was silly.

Imperial law is fairly narrow, and not particularly concerned about
individuals. Remember, the Imperium sanctions _wars_. Philosophically, I
see the Imperium as concerned with "peace, order, and good government" on
the broadest scale. Justice is not particularly an issue. If the planet
Barghest conquers the planet Fretgan in a short, sharp war the local
Imperial representative may well let it stand. If Tukera sabotages the
players\' free trader during a tradewar, the Imperium isn\'t particularly
bothered.

Imperial courts are inquisitorial, not adversarial. The judge takes an
active role, with an emphasis on discovering the truth. He may ask
questions, direct investigations, and so forth.

The judge is always a noble: although the judge is technically the Imperial
noble in who\'s fief the crime took place, he often deligates his authority
to another noble. Respected commoner jurists are ennobled for this task,
and retain their noble rank after retirement (although these titles are not
hereditary). Training in the law is _not_ required for Imperial justices;
what _is_ required is a tenacious ability to uncover the truth coupled with
an incorruptible nature.

Prosecuting and defense counsels are usually present. Their task is to
present information and to ensure that the law is followed. Unlike American
practice, a counsel is forbidden to misrepresent the fact,  In particular,
if a defense counsel knows, or has good reason to believe, that his client
is guilty then he may not plead innocence. (Mitigating circumstances, pleas
for leniency, and so forth are perfectly in order.)

Precedent is not legally binding, although it is usually used as a
guideline. The emphasis is always on the _intent_ of the law, rather than
exact wording. This results in some inequities, although it closes many
loopholes.

Appeals may always be made to the noble\'s leige lord, including up the
chain to the Emperor.  The higher noble is under no obligation to hear the
case; indeed, most appeals are denied. (The operative philosophy is
"promote good men and trust their judgement.")

Costs are born by the plaintifs, not the Imperium. This disadvantages
poorer individuals. Mitigating against this is the inquisitorial nature of
the court: the costs of any investigations ordered by the judge are born by
the judge (part of the cost of running a noble court), and as the judge is
after the truth a poor defendant _or_ prosecutor needs merely to convince
the judge that the investigation is critical to uncovering a relevant fact.

On that note, charges in an Imperial court are brought not by the Imperium
but by individuals. This means that theoretically the players could
prosecute a Tukera executive for treason. This is a rare event, as the
consequences of bringing a frivolous charge are severe, and are born by the
individual bringing the charge.  If an organization wishes to lay a charge
then a member of that organization must do so as an individual.

A noble may demand a trial by his peers, in which case a jury is assembled:
the nobles in this jury must be of equal rank, the judge must be of a
higher rank. The judge still directs the investigation, and the jury may
ask questions and request investigations (although the judge may decide
that the investigation is not warranted). The jury is chosen by the judge;
although custom dictates that the closest nobles who can attend will make
up the jury this is not always followed.



The Ministry of Justice is not, as described in the Challenge 50 article,
an interstellar FBI. (For one thing, add up the number of agents required
to have one per 100,000 people, then add in the support staff. Yikes.)

IMTU, the Ministries are a counterpoise between the nobility and the
megacorporations. The Emperor balances this triad. The Ministries are a
tool for doing what is necessary for the gopod of the Imperium, yet falls
outside the purview of the nobility and is not profitable enough for the
megacorporations. In a sense the Ministries are a bureaucratic equivalent
to the Imperial Services.

The Ministry of Justice is concerned with enforcing Imperial laws and
regulations. They deal only with matters that affect the Imperium, and only
when those matters are not being handled by another body. Thus, the
supression of piracy is a Navy duty, while an MoJ agent will be more
concerned with tracking down how the pirates are able to operate (ie. which
world is providing covert support). While MoJ agents have broad powers they
have little in the way of force. If force is required the Navy is brought
in.


Imperial laws are, as I said before, mostly concerned with preserving the
Imperium. As such they are more concerned with subsectors than individuals.
Actions count for all, motivations for nothing. (Mitigating circumstances
and mistakes are used as reasons for leniency, but there is not
_requirement_ for leniency. A man who accidentally kills a Duke may be
executed for treason, although if the judge\'s investigation shows that it
was a genuine accident then he may well not be punished at all.)


Imperial crimes are:

Treason. This, technically, includes refusing an order of the Emperor (or
an Imperial Warrant-holder), or killing a leige-sworn noble acting in His
name.  Comes in different flavours, from High to Common, depending on the
offense and circumstances.

Piracy. This is restraint-of-trade by force. Note that while tradewar is an
accepted safety valve there is no legal level, merely custom, and that a
corporate officer who declares a tradewar runs the risk of being personally
charged if it goes too far. (Which leads to lots of nice subplots ablout
dead men and tales...)

War. This is, generally, conquest at the interstellar level. In general the
Imperium allows low-intensity conflicts to continue as long as they do not
endanger those outside the combat area, and those inside are allowed to
leave. (Note that "allowed to leave" doesn\'t mean "free transportation".)
While an invasion is technically illegal, a short sharp invasion will often
be left to stand by the Imperium, if the Imperial judge views it as
increasing the long-term order of a subsector.

Devastation. This is destroying a significant planetary asset of value to
the Imperium. Rarely used.

Slavery. Actual chattel slavery is forbidden. Indentured servitude is not,
but indentures are not transferred to offspring. (Good plot hook: players
are on a world where indentured servitude is common. Someone throws them a
baby, hoping that they will take it offworld before it runs up a debt for
clothing, schooling, food... What do the players do?)

Imperial Trespass. Violating an interdiction, trespassing on an Imperial
base, and so forth.


There are also a great number of Imperial Regulations covering licensing
for starships, safety requirements for Imperial Ports, and so on. I usually
invent these as necessary, under the principle that the Imperium regulates
in the interests of promoting order and trade. Imperial Ministries don\'t
have enough staff to enforce complete complience, and usually rely on
planetary governments for most of the enforcement work. (For example, most
starship safety inspectors are actually part of a planetary government, not
an Imperial body.)

Technological restrictions are covered by Imperial regulations.



There\'s more, but this is getting long and I still have two tests to set.
Let me know if you want more.
