This is why today\'s military talks in terms of UTM coordinates instead of
place names.

There must be some unambiguous coodinate system for the 3I to describe
locations in space with precision, but I have no idea what it is. I assume
that the paths of stars as they move through a galaxy are different enough
to cause difficulties in using them for reference points. A more difficult
problem (perhaps?) is to precisely describe a location on an arbitrary
planet. UTM coordinates are tailored to the Earth. If you need accuracies
down to the centimeter or even the meter, say for accurately targeting
artillery, you need a very precise way to describe where the observer, the
target, and the gun are.

Imagine the difficulties in accurately calculating firing data on some
worlds. When I went to gunnery school years ago at Ft. Sill, we learned how
to calculate corrections for a wide range of errors: those caused by the
spinning round drifting to one side, those caused by the different wind
speeds at different elevations, and even for the Earth rotating under the
shell while it\'s in the air. You will need lots of local data to make
gunnery precise on arbitrary planets from these factors and others. I assume
that the Imperial Marines have come up with a solution, however.

Not really connected to how to pronounce system names, was it?
