> that the paths of stars as they move through a
> galaxy are different enough
> to cause difficulties in using them for reference
> points. 
Yes, stars do move, but they typically move with a
velocity of something like 300 km/sec, which is faster
than you can run, but still slow year-to-year. At that
speed, it would take a 3,250 years for a star to be a
parsec away from where it was. I always assumed this
was the reason that starships came out of jump far
from the target system, in case it have moved since
they were last there! And that this was a good side
effect of being able to jump only 1-6 parsecs at a
time, along your way somewhere you could stop, have a
look around and adjust your aim for the next jump.

A more difficult
> problem (perhaps?) is to precisely describe a
> location on an arbitrary
> planet. UTM coordinates are tailored to the Earth.
> If you need accuracies
> down to the centimeter or even the meter, say for
> accurately targeting
> artillery, you need a very precise way to describe
> where the observer, the
> target, and the gun are.
Well, when I was in the infantry, maybe our armies
Down Under aren\'t such good shots, but we used to have
spotters who\'d say, fire on this spot, and then adjust
the gunner\'s aim for them. As for co-ordinates, you
can just do what the IAU has done and choose an
abitrary crater or mountain on a world as "greenwich
meridian", and of course the equator and poles are
easy to put on the map... The only difficulty would be
on worlds with frequently changing features, such as
Europa or Io, but hopefully there\'d be not too many
battles on such worlds...
