Consider the difficulties is computing exact coordinates for a jump. Even a
little relative motion makes a big error over a few parsecs. The
navigational data required to perform accurate jumps must be both very
extensive as well as very precise.

> Well, when I was in the infantry, maybe our armies
> Down Under aren\'t such good shots, but we used to have
> spotters who\'d say, fire on this spot, and then adjust
> the gunner\'s aim for them. As for co-ordinates, you
> can just do what the IAU has done and choose an
> abitrary crater or mountain on a world as "greenwich
> meridian", and of course the equator and poles are
> easy to put on the map... The only difficulty would be
> on worlds with frequently changing features, such as
> Europa or Io, but hopefully there\'d be not too many
> battles on such worlds...

The problem with adjusting fire is that you don\'t get many first round hits.
When you are fighting a sophisticated adversary with meaningful
counter-battery capability, this really matters. That\'s why the US Army does
the "shoot and scoot." Even with TL8 technology it is possible to have
counter-battery fire on the way before the first round impacts. (Probably
only for high-angle fire.)

Do you suppose that the 3I still uses Napoleon\'s system for gunnery?

With the other worlds, I would expect that the varying degrees of deviation
from a sphere for the shape of the planet may make a nice, clean. accurate
coordinate system difficult to devise.
