    'ts-index' => '1999-11-20.ee356',
    'body' => 'A few random comments, sorry for the mess.

> Yes, and AD&D isn\'t supposed to be a dungeon crawl,
> either.

And many of the times I\'ve played it hasn\'t been.

Alhough actually, originally it _was_ supposed to be a dungeon crawl,
"wilderness adventures" didn\'t appear until the supplements.

> But when you\'re writing, you have to consider
> not only what you write, but who\'s going to read it,
> and how they\'ll interpret it.

No you don\'t. If you do that you\'ll emasculate your vision and never write
anything good.

> Quite true, and for me that makes these settings a
> problem - a "party" makes little sense (except perhaps
> in Werewolf, where they\'re a "pack"). And I\'ve seen
> that typically people do create such characters, which
> then utterly fail to co-operate.

Which is a valid choice. It also makes a good game, because as they fail to
co-operate they lose agaist the better NPC\'s, and slowly start learning that
to win they _need_ to co-operate. (Which is also the theme of many of these
"lonely, embittered hero" films as well.

BTW, Traveller is no better at generating parties than any other game, I\'ve
seen just as many "loners" in Trav games as in others. Heck, having the
Scout Service practically guarantees such types.

> I agree that we need
> something better than "you meet in an inn and decide
> to adventure together" to keep the group together,
> some deeper reason, but I just don\'t see how it can
> happen in the World of Darkness.

Pretty simple really, get good roleplayers who will design characters that
fit together.
Nothing to do with the system, or even the genre, everything to do with the
players.

...
> So why reinforce the troubles they already have?

Why assume they have troubles ?

> better a game which encourages sociability,
> co-operation, and so on. But perhaps I\'m thiking too
> much of the "mentoring" aspects of GMing younger
> players.

You\'re thinking too much of being a "responsible adult"
Play the game for fun instead.Let them have fun.
_All_ games encourage sociability and co-operation, if only to succesfully
beat your opponent into a pulp.

> You\'re right, there. But some systems, some genres,
> lend themselves more easily to that than others. Hands
> up those who\'ve given up on, or never entered a Star
> Wars game because they were overwhelmed by film quotes
> and cliches?:)

That\'s the whole _point_ of that game.
What\'s wrong with it ?

Though it\'s quite possible to play SW games that have none of that.

Try playing Rebel Special Forces. Even more Traveller than Traveller.

> No, it\'s a complete lack of an ideology - a nihilism,
> or the pseudo-religion of armchair
> self-psychoanalysis.

It is ? Most of the goths I know would laugh at such a suggestion.

> Certainly I don\'t think all World of Darkness players
> are Goths. But you don\'t find many Goths playing
> Traveller, that\'s for sure.

You don\'t find many of _any_ social group playing Traveller, and I know at
least one goth Traveller player.

Heck he\'s also the only goth that plays in the local VtM LARP, the rest of
the players , while many are certainly fringe types, don\'t usually go for
that scene. There does seem to be a higher than average  number of  women
with nipple piercings involved though...

Frankie
