    'ts-index' => '1999-11-19.ee357',
    'body' => 'William Hostman wrote :-
> Don\'t forget that I mentioned the Area. (Oh, BTW, thanx for the commentary,
> Robert). That includes the ground...
15 to 200 millirems per year from this source.
Using a damper to deliver a century\'s worth of rays will yield at best
20 rem. Acute radiation sickness requires at least 100 rem whole body
dosage.

> Another thought... what does all that potassium 40 decay into, and is it
> used in any neurotransmitters?
Argon ; this decay chain is what keeps the insides of the Earth molten
(K-40 is relatively common). The ratio of K:Ar is also determined when
dating geological specimens.

Argon is anaesthetic in very large concentrations (but you would need a
hyperbaric chamber).

Neurotransmitters are amino acid derivatives, or proteins for the most
part (the obvious exceptions being adenosine and nitric oxide). No
potassium contained therein.

Leonard Erickson wrote :-
> I know for a *fact* that there are surgical muscle relaxants that *do*
> only effect the "voluntary" muscles. They leave the heart and lungs
> alone.

I\'m not sure how you\'re defining \'"voluntary" muscles\'.
All the muscle relaxants that are in current clinical use interfere with
the propagation of nerve impulses at the neuromuscular junction of
skeletal (striated) muscle, leading to the predictable onset of \'flaccid
paralysis\'.
	The information I posted previously, stands. The diaphragm and chest
wall are composed, and perform, as described.
	Some of the older members of this class do have cardiac effects via the
autonomic nervous system (curare, pancuronium, succinyl dicholine).
	
> Mind you, I seem to recall that they do this by blocking nerve
> impulses from the spine, rather than by directly affecting the muscles...
	This was correct with a class of drugs referred to as ganglion
blockers, the only useful member of which was decamethonium, which is
only available in the dusty cupboards of established research labs.
	Curare has been available since the 1500s and was only used clinically
really from the mid 1940s ; the various derivatives have appeared over
the ensuing years. Succinyl dicholine became available in the
early 1950s. The ganglion blockers enjoyed a brief period of use in the
mid 50\'s - early 60\'s. 

> Spasm *wasn\'t* a riot control agent. It was a load for a very
> specialized weapon. It was *targeted*, not sprayed indiscriminately. 
> You seem to have rolled the comments on spetsdods (an odd "hand
> weapon") and anti-riot measures into one. They were seperate subjects.

IMHO, \'Spasm\' makes a lousy incapacitant, regardless of the \'sphere of
operations\'. The method of delivery is neither here nor there.
	My apologies ; you mentioned \'Spasm\' as ammo for spetsdods after the
quote on the riot in the \'Matador\' series by Steve Perry.

> Real world items:
> A derivative of one of the high blood pressure meds. It slowly lowers
> your blood pressure.
Sounds like an overdose of any of the antihypertensives. Delivery is a
problem in the \'riot control context\'.
	Strokes, myocardial infarction, renal failure, gut necrosis... real
potential for unwanted damage here. The vagaries of individual and
species variation have been commented on by other posters.

> A derivative of that surgical muscle relaxant I mentioned. The effects
> start at the base of the spine and work up. So you lose control of your
> feet and ankles, then of the knees, etc, until you are effectively a
> (temporary) quadraplegic. Again, at this point the police wander over
> and pick you up. 

This is done every day with local anaesthetic and narcotic delivered
into the epidural or subarachnoid space, in a highly controlled fashion.
	Again, if we overlook the problems of delivering our agent to the right
spot, we run into a few little problems as the block rises :-
	injury secondary to falling over ;
	lethal falls in blood pressure secondary to loss of peripheral vascular
resistance ;
	aberrant cardiac rhythms ;
	paralysis of the diaphragm (the last of the \'chest\' muscles to succumb,
due to its innervation) ; and
	brainstem paralysis - with a total loss of control of blood pressure,
heart rate, vascular volume, and respiratory sensing and function. This
is a state indistinguishable from \'brain death\', unless you can
demonstrate that the cerebrum is being perfused or otherwise works (e.g.
EEG/SPECT scanning).


Robert O\'Connor
Medico, Gamer
