    'topic' => 'Meta-stories',
    'body' => 'Hello folks,

After collecting lots of ideas for gritty, X-files like scenarios, I
was drawn to the mysteries which were used in Traveller to
provide a type of background environment, or overarching
enigmas or pushes... real big, hazy carrots floating in the Traveller
background to make players go "hmmm" and wonder if there\'s
any rhyme or reason to it all.

Reflection brought out several concepts, including
1) The Ancients
2) The 5th Frontier War
3) The Rebellion, sort of
4) Longbow
5) Jumpstart
6) Empress Wave
7) Black Curtain
8) "The Boy" (remember?)

These are grand mysteries that add yet another layer of depth
to the Traveller background; they fill an aching gap between the
Mystery Of The Universe itself and the Mystery Of The Day,
which is embodied in current campaign goals.

Of course, these meta-stories are played out and terminate, but
they are slow and not generally the prime focus of the players,
because they\'re literally too big to tackle (some are bigger than
others, but they all fit the mold of a mythology that colors the TU).

Last night I had ideas -- finally, finally, ideas -- about how to
use these to my advantage.  These are not perfected, but I
think they are useable.

1) The Ancients is an incredible enigma of massive proportions,
and of course by now everybody -- players and referees -- pretty
much knows their history.  Those who haven\'t played the LBB
adventures just read summaries in other books.  Good!  Now that
everyone takes the solution for granted, I suggest turning it on its
head.  Pick a key part of the evidence and history, and have players
unwittingly debunk it.  The whole edifice collapses, and now all
you knew about the Ancients is bogus.  Is it a massive plot, and if
so, by who, or is it just another red herring that the community
just bandwagoned along with, as is so common with people?

2) The political and military twists and turns of war are never
exhausted.  As we have seen recently, Loren Wiseman knows this.

3) If you\'re willing to do the groundwork, then pick an alternate
Rebellion.  Dulinor was framed; or, Lucan is not a convincing leader
(or is assassinated) and the Imperium is rapidly being gathered back
together... by Judas himself, who is busily removing all evidence of
his handiwork.  Order, law, and peace is being restored, and the
rebel scum are being crushed... all will soon be well... right??

4) Archer, a predecessor and competitor to Longbow, was going
full steam in the early 1100\'s.  Its goal: to produce feasible jump-
torpedos containing military beacons.  An expensive and effective
(and fully automatable) J-6 communications network.  Obviously
a strict military project.  Why would prototypes end up with
Barracai Technum?

Okay, that\'s what I\'ve got down so far.  Opinions and contributions?

- -Rob
