    'month' => '11',
    'body' => '>> But when you\'re writing, you have to consider
>> not only what you write, but who\'s going to read it,
>> and how they\'ll interpret it.
>
>No you don\'t. If you do that you\'ll emasculate your vision and never write
>anything good.

Sorry, but you must consider your target audience. The first thing taught
in US colleges is to consider your target audience; you don\'t write using
$5 words when trying to target the general public, and you don\'t avoid em
when they are part of the jargon for the field you\'re targeting.

Best example of successful targeting: the D&D Basic/Expert/Companion/Master
progression. The first book introduces the basic concept of play, and CGen,
and dungeon crawls. Each further box expands the game with new rules,
campaign types, weapons, background, etc.

>> Quite true, and for me that makes these settings a
>> problem - a "party" makes little sense (except perhaps
>> in Werewolf, where they\'re a "pack"). And I\'ve seen
>> that typically people do create such characters, which
>> then utterly fail to co-operate.
>
I find the best solutions to the "Party" issue are a common patron and
prior service together... or at least sitting down, drawing a timeline of
the character\'s carreers, and noting when A met B. As for cooperation,
that\'s either going to happen or not, and is player dependant, having
little to do with characters (excpt for the most dedicated ROLE-players)/
>
>> I agree that we need
>> something better than "you meet in an inn and decide
>> to adventure together" to keep the group together,
>> some deeper reason, but I just don\'t see how it can
>> happen in the World of Darkness.

It is easy enough in Traveller: a common patron. In WoD, have a mummy or
some other (not represented in the group) type of supernatural draw the
group together with a combination of threats and promises.

William F. Hostman  |  "Smith & Wesson: THe original Point and Click
interface!"
