> basis of the Empire the first time there is a major problem rather than fix
> the problem. What, the six months to a couple of years it would have taken
> for the new clone to form was too long?

Re-read the book. The evidence all points to several clones having
never even made it out of the initial "facility". And also to the idea
that a new clone *won\'t* be any closer to the original. Too much drift
over the centuries, and the built-in failsafe has failed unsafely. 

Any *new* clone, even if a good copy, will sooner or later find out the
dodge the "bad" one found for getting around the implanted bomb. And
then we\'re back to an all-powerful Emperor *without* the balance of a
conscience. 

The solution the "computer" came up with was to try to get a person who
would make a good Emperor to take over the job. Sten decided that it
wouldn\'t work any better a second time, and probably not last as long
as the first time. So he declined the offer.

