  {
    'body' => 'Well, a bit late to this thread, but...

I\'ve had a world idea that I\'ve been meaning to write up for a while. And,
coincidentally enough, looking through my maps of the marches last night, I
came up with a great spot for it in Regina subsector.

Whanga 0206 Regina E676126-7

I haven\'t done the "nice" writeup, so you\'ll all have to do with a brain dump
of the random thoughts.

The basic idea is that Whanga is, by most definitions, a garden world. (more on
the atmosphere taint in a second). It\'s lush, it\'s (mostly) green, you might
even think that it was Terra if you didn\'t know better. A world well suited for
human life - with one minor exception. No one has ever been able to get
agriculture to work on the planet\'s surface. I\'m still trying to handwave an
explanation for this, but I\'m thinking along the lines of a more "aggressive"
strain of plant life on the planet which prevents any large-scale agricultural
activity from going on for more than a season or two. Colonies have tried to
establish themselves for centuries , but constantly been killed off or pushed
out by the lack of ability to sustain themselves. (This is the basic premise
which sets up pretty much everything else, so if you don\'t like my explanation,
you can stop reading here, as it\'ll all fall apart). The atmospheric taint
doesn\'t really exist, it was just put there by an early survey team who
couldn\'t think of any better explanation for the dead colony they came across.
Research on the planet\'s biosphere continues in the Third Imperium trying to
figure out what\'s up. (Note that will make more sense later: even in 1100,
nearly 5 million tourists show up every year with filter masks in tow, thinking
the atmosphere is tained. Whanga does a good business selling re-conditioned
filter masks that they leave behind)

So, you\'ve got a garden world which can\'t be colonized, so what\'s it good for?
Well, it makes a nice retreat for the rich, assuming you can get there and pack
enough food in for the time you\'re there. So, over the centuries, nobles set up
small cottages & ranches there, bringing in everything with them when they
arrive - food, supplies, servants - and taking it out when they leave.
Eventually businesses set up shop catering to the nobles, importing food on a
regular basis, etc. many of the private noble ranches eventually turned into
commercial retreats, taking anyone (who can pay the price) in for rest,
relaxation and a level of "wilderness" that simply can\'t be duplicated on a
populated planet.

Of course, nothing that nice lasts forever. Eventually (say, around year 800,
900 or so) someone saw the opportunity to re-cast Whanga as a more "populist"
tourist destination. With the lack of a planetary government, there\'s no one to
tax and legislate any dubious activities, so the resorts turned into casinos
(and, for the more "adult" campaigns, "chicken farms"). Sitting close to
various highly-populated worlds, Whanga quickly became, well, I\'ll give away my
inspiration here - Las Vegas.

For example, Whanga is:

Jump 4 from Regina,          pop ~700,000,000
Jump 2 from Efate,         pop ~8,000,000,000
Jump 2 from Roup,          pop ~3,000,000,000
Jump 3 from Louzy/Jewell, pop ~10,000,000,000

Which is about 21,700,000,000 sophonts within a reasonable one-jump distance.
You can run a tourism business on that. Of course, it\'s no small feat,
considering that you have to haul in a ton or so worth of food for each and
every person that\'s coming to stay for several weeks. Not to mention hauling
all the, er, shit (for lack of a better word) back out. At any given time,
there are tens of millions of resort employees serving the tens of millions of
visitors on the planet\'s surface. But to operate in a beautiful, idyllic,
government-free environment - well, who could pass that up?

Of course, like Las Vegas, the Whangan resorts make money hand over fist and
since it\'s tax free, they can do some pretty aggressive expansion. Many of them
have turned into replicas of famous cities from across the Imperium. "Iridium
Palace" is a replica of the Imperial Palace on Capitol. "Manhattan" is an odd
mishmash of various Terran cities, incorporating pieces of New York, Paris,
Venice as well as famous sights like the Taj Mahal and Terra\'s most (in)famous
location, the former headquarters of the 12th Imperial Marines (left over from
the occupation days), a kilometer high windowless slab of metal containing
(instead of marines and training facilities) numerous simulator rides, several
grav ball courts and, of course, the biggest casino on the planet. There are
replicas of other famous cities as well, including ones from Vland, Antares and
one that claims to be a replica of Kyusu (sp?) the Aslan homeworld, though,
unsurprisingly, few people who have ever been to Kyusu show up to challenge the
claim.  These cities are more than just show pieces - they\'re actual real
cities that house the employees and visitors. There are very few explicit
hotels in the resorts - you feel like you\'ve just moved somewhere else for a
while.

The planet is run by a loose coalition of the planet\'s biggest resort owners,
all of whom disavow any knowledge of a planetary government, lest the Imperial
Palace begin asking for tax money. At one point in history a single small
resort owner did declare himself the planet\'s legitimate government, but oddly
enough, a million-ton grain freighter crashed into his compound shortly after
unloading at the highport. Since then, no one has attempted to make a similar
claim. Thus the government type of 2, as the planet is de facto ruled by the
various resorts.

The world has no official starport, thus the \'E\' rating. There is, however, a
privately owned highport and (of course) casino, which handles all of the
world\'s traffic, receiving cargo and passengers, which are then ferried to the
surface by the resorts\' private boats. "Boats" is a relative term, as some
cargo boats approach the 1,000 ton mark.

There is a system navy to protect the various passenger and cargo ships moving
through the system. It is funded, unofficially, by the various resorts, but is
autonomous, alleging to report to no one except it\'s own high commander.
Although small, it is amazingly well equipped, with nothing but the best of
Imperial TL 15 equipment.

Finally, there is a small official Imperial presence on the world\'s surface. A
resort owner lost a chain of islands (near the planet\'s equator in the
semi-tropical zone) to the then Duke of Regina in a card game, in 1002. The
islands are now used by the Duke\'s Own Huscarles as a "training facility" - one
of the sector\'s more plum military assignments. There is also a Naval
Intelligence school associated with the facility, again one of the better
schools in the sector. Whanga\'s population of 1 reflects the few dozen
full-time staff assigned to the base and the school - the only real "Imperial
citizens" there on a full-time basis.

Whanga is (in)famous throughout the Marches as the ultimate tourist
destination. Outside the Marches it\'s seens as a kind of monument to the
tackiness of the spinward frontier dwellers, but it never the less manages to
