    'index' => 'ee426',
    'topic' => ' modern roleplayers',
    'body' => 'This post actually contains material bringing the thread back to
Traveller. Read on...

Kyle Schuant wrote:
> The problem being that the "tragic hero" is a loner...
> how does the traditional "party" work then?

Normally when you play Vampire, there is no traditional "party" at all.
That\'s how :-)

Actually, the characters in such a game are not quite as close friends
as in a traditional game. They keep details of their backgrounds from
each other, have secrets that the others shouldn\'t know about, etc. They
have gathered together more because of convenience than anything else.
After all, there are perhaps five other vampires in a city who would
consider socializing with people like you. So how much of a choice do
you really have (except leaving town, which is very dangerous)? Even the
"tragic hero" cannot bear the loneliness of enduring eternity alone.

As long as the characters have some force holding them together, the
game will work. That force doesn\'t need to be friendship. ;-)

ObTrav: This kind of game could easily be run in Traveller as well. Have
a captain of a ship (NPC or player) hire the other player characters
independently of each other. They should all be more or less desperate
for work, but they will not fit together as a group. The constant
squabbling is really fun to GM. In addition, it gives the characters a
lot more depth, since they can act out all kinds of minor quirks.

"Did you see that package Eneri picked up last time we hit ground port?
I wonder what\'s inside of it."

"Captain, I\'ve smelled a thick, sweet odor from Eneri\'s room ever since
we entered jumpspace. I think he might have brought some kind of drugs
on board."

> Glad to hear the games [Vampire et al] work for you; I just can\'t
> imagine how, but perhaps that reveals more about me,
> than the game?

You should try playing in this fashion, regardless of game system. It\'s
a really interesting break from the "normal" group, where everyone
trusts each other completely.

Be sure not to overdo it, though. If everyone in the group has some
reason to kill at least one of the others, things will get out of hand
sooner or later.

Happy (?) travelling,
/ Jens \'Spacejens\' Rydholm
