    'from' => 'Kyle Schuant kyle3054@yahoo.com',
    'body' => '> Consider the difficulties is computing exact
> coordinates for a jump. Even a
> little relative motion makes a big error over a few
> parsecs. The
> navigational data required to perform accurate jumps
> must be both very
> extensive as well as very precise.
yes, and I imagine that\'s the reason they tell us that
doing a jump without a computer is VERY risky! But I
would the most important thing is survival, rather
than time, so as long as you stay outside the stars
gravitational well (which I understand can induce
misjumps and all sorts of disasters), you\'ll be okay.
You can "target" your jump simply by looking out the
window, taking a bead on the star, moving a few
million miles, doing the same again, and then a third
time... with a bit of trignometry and a calculator,
you can figure the distance... I get the impression it
ain\'t meant to be that exact, else why do you always
