> progression. The first book introduces the basic concept of play, and
CGen,
> and dungeon crawls. Each further box expands the game with new rules,
> campaign types, weapons, background, etc.

But it\'s also an example of some of the worst technical writing, rules
design and prose I have ever seen.

For a start, the rules expansions and changes are incompatible between
versions, and do not "flow" from one set to another in a logical way.
Secondly, figuring out how to play either game by actually reading the book
is almost impossible. Luckily for TSR, most people don\'t bother actually
using all the rules, and most kids playing it learn how to play from other
kids, not from reading the rules.

The prose is about as good as that in bad Mills & Boon novels

Just because it is _succesful_ does not mean it\'s _good_ . Microsoft is the
prime example of this phenomenon.

