>my US Army experience talking here) is that the law of land warfare exists
>and is generally followed because it makes sense to.

The cynic in me reads this and considers the source. I don\'t mean that as an
insult to you, but it\'s obvious that an armed service branch that
specializes in land warfare is going to say that the law of land warfare
exists and is generally followed because it makes sense to.

One would imagine that someone who joined a branch of the armed services
that specialized in land warfare wouldn\'t get to a point where they\'d be
able to teach policy if they believed that no "law of land warfare" exists,
and that it is generally followed out of tradition, not because it\'s
rational or sensible to do so.

I\'m not saying that I hold that belief, only that I am not surprised to hear
that the U.S. Army teaches a doctrine thats says that there is a reason for
an organization specializing in land warfare to exist, and that reason is a
rational one.

With all due respect, though, that doesn\'t really tell us alot concerning
whether or not land warfare would be seen as effective by those who hold
positions of responsibility (or more cynically, those who pay the bills) in
the Imperium.

>Violating it may get
>you short-term gains, but the long-run result is generally unfavorable.


Fair enough. What are these long term gains that would be gained as a result
of ground warfare that wouldn\'t be gained through the use of cheap but
excessive force (as in orbital bombardment) or any variation on this theme?

In this case, I\'m putting the powerful traditional romantic notion of the
infantry soldier aside. Ordinarily, I don\'t like to sweep such things under
the carpet, but in this case I feel that it is justified. This is an appeal
to tradition, and as a result it naturally follows that it  is descriptive,
not prescriptive. In other words, based on experience, such a notion
describes things as they *have* been up to this point, and does not
prescribe as they might be, nor as they will be.

In this sense, I\'m trying to head off possible misinterpretations that may
lead people to reply by saying something like, "Well, as everyone knows you
always need a doughboy down in the trenches and the mud." For the sake of
discussion, let me say that I *don\'t* know that.

How am I to be convinced that the Imperium (or other major interstellar
power) won\'t see value in dropping big, cheap rocks on major cities in order
to get their way?

>that would be straying way off topic.) You can find volume after volume of
>case studies which demonstrate this point.


Perhaps, but it still boils down to description, not prescription.

>This is the ultimate reason why it is very unlikely that such things like
>near-c rocks will be regularly used as weapons. Maybe once in a while by
>renegades, but not as a weapon of choice.

Well, why not? ;)

>Civilizations which progress far
>enough to reach advanced technology will also have come to the same
>conclusion.


I can\'t tell you how many times, in the last few months, I\'ve read
variations of this same statement concerning just about everything under the
sun. ;)
