    'ts-index' => '1999-11-20.ee450',
    'body' => '>In mail you write:
>
>> Imperial crimes are:
>>
>> Treason. This, technically, includes refusing an order of the Emperor (or
>> an Imperial Warrant-holder), or killing a leige-sworn noble acting in His
>> name.  Comes in different flavours, from High to Common, depending on the
>> offense and circumstances.
>
>And if you do the logical thing and have a homage/fealty type model
>extending all the way down the line, any noble should be able to lodge
>charges of "treason" against anyone violating their oaths to *him*.

Common treason, yes. Judged by the noble\'s leige lord. Charges of treason
are not normally laid except in times of emergency, or in cases of active
hard. (Ie. ignoring the Duke when he says "pass the peas" at dinner won\'t
get you charged with treason.)


>BTW, this brings up an important point regarding oaths of
>fealty/homage. Not only do they work both ways (that is, while the
>underling is obligated to his liege, the lieg has equal obligations to
>the underling), but there are two more factors.
>
>First, being in effect "contracts" laying out *mutual* obligations,
>they can be terminated by *either* party by claiming non-performance
>(ie the underling can charge his liege with failing to look after the
>underlings welfare in the manner specified and that terminates the
>"contract" just as fast as the liege claiming the underling was
>derelict in the underling\'s duties). This makes "treason" acting
>against your liege *without* severing the tie first.

Said severing consisting of a ceremony. Nothing major, but enough that
saying "I quit, now b****r off." isn\'t enough.


>Second, there\'s the very important matter of whether or not
>fealty/homage is transitive. That is, if I\'m sworn to Baron X, and he\'s
>sworn to Count Y, am I obligated to Count Y? If yes, the relationship
>is transitive. If no, it isn\'t. The two possibilities result in *very*
>different sorts of "politics", but both are arguably possible given
>what is known of the Imperium.

Partially, IMTU.  If you are sworn to Baron X, then you are obligated to
Count Y, but Baron X must pass along the orders unless he has told you to
obey Count Y. There is nothing to stop you from obeying Count Y of your own
accord, of course, and obedience is expected (but not required).

This is why the Imperial Navy swears an oath to the Emperor, directly.


>Playing fealty/homage "right" makes for interesting legal situations.
[snip]
>
>BTW, in a "feudal" setup with oaths between liege and sworn man, even
>if it\'s gotten so complex (as it likely would) that the oaths are
>multipage contracts, you\'ll have an element that among both the
>nobility, and the people serving them under such "oaths" ones sworn
>word is a *very* valuable commodity.
>
>This presents interesting playing possibilities. Including such things
>as putting a PC in a spot where he gave his sworn word, and then found
>out that things were a *lot* more complicated than he\'d thought. Now
>he\'s got to find a way to keep his word *and* avoid getting in trouble
>with the law (or getting into some other sort of trouble).
>
>Being "honorable" can be a *real* bitch at times. :-)

That\'s why it makes for great gaming. And if you\'re playing GT, that\'s why
it\'s a disadvantage (although a _reputation_ for being honourable would be
an advantage, too).
