    'from' => 'yikes@evansville.net',
    'body' => '>>ObTrav: What kind of name is Alkhalikoi anyway?
>
>Sounds Hawaiian/Polynesian

Hawaiian, eh? I guess the old kingdom finally got justice. Yanks in Space,
indeed! ;-)

3,000 years is a long time to retain a cultural/ethnic identity
(historically, anyway, although information technology may have now changed
that). How likely is it that Strephon would have anything resembling the
appearance of a Polynesian? How likely is it that the human population in
general will retain distinctive genotypes that one can distinguish visibly?
With specific exceptions  like the Sword Worlds notwithstanding, humaniti
seems to me to have become pretty "raceless." Or is this my own
wishful-thinking filter kicking in?

Do we have a situation in the Imperium where there are 11,000 x n different
human ethnic groups, with at least one for each world and possibly hundreds?

This could be really ugly, and could go a long way to explain why something
like the Rebellion could get so nasty (I know, I know, the Rebellion was
all just a dream).

Or do we think that social sciences and technology have advanced at pace
with the hard sciences (given the way people behave in the canon
liturature, I would say not -- except, perhaps, for the Zhodani)?

Okay, I guess this is just a roundabout way of asking: how balkanized is
*your* Imperium? Not Douglas\'s specifically, but anyone\'s. How do you see
issues of culture and ethnicity reflected in YTU? Do you see it breaking
down into the big three (Vilani, Zhodani, Solomani), regional (Sylean,
Denebian, Solomani), planetary (Capitalian, Regianian, Solomani), or even
on sub-planetary basis? Or do you expect a mix of all four? If it\'s a mix,
how is it biased?

I would suppose that it would be mostly planetary or regional -- as recent
discussion has reminded us, off-world travel is not for the average citizen.

For those of you into genetic drift and the like, how differentiated do you
think humaniti will have become (Ancient and human meddling aside)?

Ciao,

Joseph R. Dietrich
