There\'s a ral world ultrasonic gizmo sold for protection against dogs.
I accidentally got the effect it uses while visiting a friend working
with an ultrasonic alarm system. I have "abnormal" hearing in that I
can hear well into the ultrasonics (I\'m told this is common among those
who had asthma as children). 

Anyway, I thought I could hear the alarm transducers. So I picked one
up and brought it *quickly* to my ear. This doppler shifted the output
to a higher frequency. I thought the top of my head was going to come off!

I\'ve been hit in the head by a fist sized rock. It felt better than
this "sound" did. 

I assume the anti-dog device works similarly. In which case I can
understand why it makes the dog stop. I\'m told that they can\'t use the
ultrasound gizmo on people because it apparently has nasty effects on a
small percentage of the population. Something about rupturing
anuerisms? 

Still, it\'d make a nice weapon for folks who weren\'t too worried if it
occasionally killed someone. But it\'d definitely be a *short* range
weapon. More suitable for muggings than crowd control.

Oh yeah, after I recovered, I *slowly* brought a transducer to my ear. The
faint whine I\'d heard *was* the transducers. 

