    'index' => 'ee466',
    'topic' => ' The naming of things',
    'body' => 'From: Joseph R. Dietrich <yikes@evansville.net>


>3,000 years is a long time to retain a cultural/ethnic identity
>(historically, anyway, although information technology may have now changed
>that).

Well, 3,000 years is a long time to retain much of anything. Even those
concepts that "survive" are going to change so much that they no longer look
like they did originally.

>How likely is it that Strephon would have anything resembling the
>appearance of a Polynesian?

It depends. It\'s possible to imagine a scenario in which the variations of
gross morphology in the major and minor human races in known space might
inspire a resurgence of racialist ideas. On the other hand, it\'s also
possible to imagine a scenario where the opposite is true.

>How likely is it that the human population in
>general will retain distinctive genotypes that one can distinguish
>visibly?


Extremely likely. After all, we\'re dealing with isolated worlds in space and
a model of interstellar travel that precludes the possibility of mass
immigration or mass exodus. Interstellar travellers might tend toward
"uniformity", but it\'s likely that those who are planetbound (the vast
majority of the citizens of the Imperium) would have significant differences
in gross morphology.

>With specific exceptions  like the Sword Worlds notwithstanding, humaniti
>seems to me to have become pretty "raceless." Or is this my own
>wishful-thinking filter kicking in?


There are certain things that Traveller avoids like the plague in canon. The
three main ones that I can think of are religion, race and ideology.

With that in mind, it *is* possible to read between the lines. Concepts such
as  major and minor human races *do* exist in the Imperium. Make of that
tidbit what you will.

It seems to me that there is *something* that distinguishes various branches
of humaniti from others. If distinctions in race were flattened to the
extent that is frequently imagined in sci-fi there would be no need to
distinguish between the two.

>Do we have a situation in the Imperium where there are 11,000 x n different
>human ethnic groups, with at least one for each world and possibly
hundreds?


In my opinion, yes, at least to some degree. Planets are isolated from each
other, and travel between them is relatively expensive. In general, I think
that you\'re going to have far fewer racial "melting pots".

Culture, on the other hand, is a horse of a different color (no pun
intended). It is much more likely that cultural distinctions could, and
probably would be flattened to some degree in the Imperium. That\'s a general
rule, but it\'s not going to apply in all cases. Take a look at the
astonishingly successful American entertainment business, and to a lesser
extent the British and Japanese entertainment businesses.

>This could be really ugly, and could go a long way to explain why something
>like the Rebellion could get so nasty (I know, I know, the Rebellion was
>all just a dream).


Perhaps, but racial distinctions don\'t automatically mean that things *have*
to get ugly. Keep in mind that the modern notion of race (at least in the
West) is quite different than that which was held in the 16th Century, and
the 16th century notion of race. In the same vein, that conception of race
would also be different from the one that Greeks or Hebrews held in
antiquity.

>Or do we think that social sciences and technology have advanced at pace
>with the hard sciences (given the way people behave in the canon
>liturature, I would say not -- except, perhaps, for the Zhodani)?


That simply cannot be the case. It\'s easy to imagine a society in which air,
sea and land travel have been superannuated by cheap and efficient
contra-gravity devices and power plants. It\'s much more difficult to imagine
a society in which the discipline of history has changed its focus.

Indeed, in real life the discipline of history has changed its focus over
the course of the last two centuries or so and there are still those who
criticize its current state as in some way invalid. To take it further,
we\'re heading for a really bumpy road in the next century as more and more
people will be applying such concepts as structuralism and
post-structuralism to the social disciplines.

We\'re *still* feeling the fallout from, say, the psychological approach to
history, and that\'s been around for a century. There are still people who
grumble about feminist historical approaches and socialist historical
approaches. Now there are enough of the above theories out there, and people
are starting to place them relative to each other in the structuralist
approach to history.

I shudder to think of what the state of social science will look like when
I\'m a doddering old professor who can remember where he left his glasses!

I\'m not being critical of the new approaches in social science. In point of
fact, I\'m really excited that I\'m entering the field at such an exciting
time. I\'m just pointing out that it\'s very difficult for many people to
accept the advances that have been in place for a century or more *today*,
and that it would be completely and utterly impossible to imagine the social
sciences several millenia from now.

>Okay, I guess this is just a roundabout way of asking: how balkanized is
>*your* Imperium?

Extremely balkanized. Balkanized to the point that it\'s impossible for a
single interstellar government to exist. ;)

>Not Douglas\'s specifically, but anyone\'s. How do you see
>issues of culture and ethnicity reflected in YTU? Do you see it breaking
>down into the big three (Vilani, Zhodani, Solomani), regional (Sylean,
>Denebian, Solomani), planetary (Capitalian, Regianian, Solomani), or even
>on sub-planetary basis? Or do you expect a mix of all four? If it\'s a mix,
>how is it biased?


I think that the lines around the "big three" are much less distinct than
most people on the list consider them. If you use the United States of
America as a model (I apologize to those of you out there who get surly at
the idea of "Yanks in Space", but I can think of few countries that have the
same sort of mixture), there is considerable difficulty in getting most
people to consider themselves "American". Culturally and sub-culturally, the
U.S. is factionalized to the point that walking from one neighborhood into
another, or even from one *nightclub* into another is like setting foot on a
different planet.

Hell, compared to the tradional canon view of the Traveller universe the
differences between two cliques in your average high-school are far more
acute than the differences between Aslan and Solomani. ;)

[As an example of the scenario, the recent off-topic discussion of the goth
movement suddenly becomes on topic! ;)]

>I would suppose that it would be mostly planetary or regional -- as recent
>discussion has reminded us, off-world travel is not for the average
citizen.


Yes. I agree. I\'m working from a model that assumes that the smallest unit
of cultural currency in known space is a planet, or more commonly, a solar
system.

>For those of you into genetic drift and the like, how differentiated do you
>think humaniti will have become (Ancient and human meddling aside)?


Dammit Joe, I\'m a social scientist, not a biologist! ;)

<I\'d be fascinated to see some ideas from those who know more of this
subject than I though>
