    'from' => 'alanb@elf.brisnet.org.au',
    'body' => '> >> Hard to organize a riot if all your megaphones stiop working.

A couple of thoughts on this:

1.  Riots are rarely organized.  They tend to occur in the absence of
organisation, and one of the best ways of turning a political demonstration
into a riot is to take out its organisational structure!  Of course, there
can be situations where "mere chaos" is the goal, but even so, I doubt the
instigators of this would really need much of a communications network.

2.  Not all megaphones are electronic.  A basic TL0 megaphone consists of a
hollow cone with open ends, made of whatever material you chose, which you
shout through.  Although it\'s directional, it\'s remarkably effective.

3.  Gimmick devices like the anti-electronics one that I seem to have lost
the reference to above only work when they are a suprise.  A bit of thin
plastic and some masking tape would adequately seal most electronic
equipment.

4.  From what I\'ve seen, well organised demonstrations (or "riots", if you
are on the side of the oppressive government) tend to have marshals for
crowd control, and a network of runners throughout the crowd for
coordination and communication.  In some cases, the bulk of the crowd will
be loosely associated in contingents, too, derived from various
organisations and geographical areas.  This kind of organisation would be
more likely in situations where violent responses are likely to be met.  If
you take out the electronics, you would simply force reliance on the good
old fashioned TL0 runners, and the Mark I sentients leading the crowd.

5.  Invent a better mousetrap, and someone will invent a better mouse.

Alan Bradley
alanb@elf.brisnet.org.au
