    'body' => 'In mail you write:

> I\'m surprised the Imperium doesn\'t utilize mass-driver technology on
> warships when they need to do pin-point bombardment. It CAN be done, the
> physics prove this. Besides, you don\'t have to mess with that nasty Pu 
> (plutonium).

Well, there\'s nothing that says the Imperium *doesn\'t*.

But there *are* some problems. You aren\'t going to get nuke level
strikes from a spinal mass driver. The impact energy is a function of
the mass of the projectile, and the launch velocity. The launch
velocity is dependent on the length of the driver and the acceleration
it can provide (I can dig up the formula). You won\'t get anywhere
*near* lightspeed with a ship mounted weapon (I once did the figures
for a 1000 km longer mass driver and it only got a few percent of c)

But basicly, you have to supply *all* the energy that goes into the
explosion, plus extra for losses in the mass driver. A nuke doesn\'t
cost anywhere *near* as much energy as it releases.

Also, launch from orbit puts in a definite lag between launch and
impact. This can render the mass driver useless against some targets. 

Nudging "big rocks" into impact orbits is a lot more energy efficient,
but has even *longer* time lags. 

