> <sigh> The USPS delivers millions of pieces of mail quickly and
> safely, but once in a while they fail.  It\'s the failures we all
> remember.  Here\'s my USPS failure story...my Mom sent my sister\'s
> family their Christmas presents via USPS three years ago.  The box
> never arrived, but in mid March a *piece* of the box with the
> address on it was delivered to her with a "Sorry, but this is all
> that\'s left" message.  Since than she sends only through UPS.  It
> happens with the private carriers too, but it seems to happen less
> often. 

Well, I\'ve never heard of UPS or any of the other private carriers
having their personnel discovered to have been *dumping* mail in huge
quantities. That is almost a refular occurence with the Post Awful. 

I think we\'d be better off if they dropped the special rates for "junk
mail". I\'d leave the special rates for actual *catalogs* (which is what
it was originally established for!) and even for "mini-catalog" flyers.
But it\'d end all those credit card offers and other such dreck. And by
dropping the mail volume drasticly, I think they\'d actually be able to
deal with mail properly again.

> Ob Trav...Obvious!  Does the X-boat service *ever* fail to deliver
> their messages? 

Only if the ship gets lost/damaged. And I\'d include "message receipts"
in the traffic flow. That is, as messages are logged into the reception
center upon delivery to a world, a "message XXXX received" goes into
the package being prepared to be sent back to whether that X-boat came
from. 

So if something happened, the computers would note that they\'d gotten
one or more X-boats back, but that there was a block of messages that
were overdue for acknowledgement. 

This *does* require retaining messages at each link until they\'ve been
acknowledged by the next link, but that shouldn\'t be a major problem.
And it provides *greatly* increased reliability at a small increase in
cost and complexity. 

And if the messages are stored with some sort of checksum or CRC, then
it also allows for retransmission of messages that somehow get garbled.

> Do they maintain a monopoly on certain classes of message?

Besides official imperial messages (ie mail from the government), I
don\'t see much need. Remember, the X-boat network is supposed to have
*started* much like seberal mail services on Terra. As a way to get
*goverment* dispatches delivered quickly and reliably. Once in place,
they started using "extra" capacity for paid civilian traffic.

Even now you *can* send stuff the old fashioned way. Find someone going
to the right place and pay them to deliver the message. The government
monopoly on thgis sort of "courier service" has grown out of financial
difficulties in the mail system. Something that I don\'t see the X-boat
service having. 

> Are there *specific* commercial carriers of mail and small
> package in the Imperium, or are those roles subsumed into the
> operations of the various MegaCorps?

I thought that was a form of "speculative cargo"? :-)

Seriously, I expect that there are megacorps that deliver not only
across the Imperium, but even into other polities. And there will be
smaller corps that do sector and subsector level mail and package
service. And not all the smaller ones will have their own ships.
They\'ll almost certainly not have them for deliveries to the less
important planets.

So part of the cargo tables should be cargo containers of "private"
packages and/or mail. Also, there should be provisions for ships going
to out of the way places to have packages or even "letters" consigned
to them for delivery (to an agent or even to the destination).

That last makes for a nice adventure hook. 

