>people that can agree to whatever it is you want from them.  If you
>target the whole planet: you get a glowing lifeless ball. Which is
>perfect if your goal is to litter the galaxy with glowing lifeless balls -
>less perfect if you actually want usefull planets to tax and stuff.


Okay, that is if you assume that the Imperium is going to bombard a planet
back into the stone age and erase all life on the surface of a planet. I
made no indication that this might even be the case.

Let\'s put the scenario in another way. Say you\'ve got worlds which don\'t
want to be part of the Imperium, or who are currently part of the Imperium
and wish to regain their independence.

What\'s going to stop them from doing so? What\'s to stop them from, I don\'t
know, sabotaging their own industrial capacity to the extent that they
*can\'t* pay Imperial taxes? What do you do then, do you drop Imperial
Marines to force them to work at gun point? Do you drop Imperial Marine
Engineers onto the planet, build new industrial centers, and then force the
populace to work at gunpoint?

At some point, if you\'re the Imperium, and you\'re as hardnosed as is claimed
in canon, you\'re going to have to deal with the pontentiality of hitting
civilian populations to make it known that you\'re not going to tolerate such
slacking.

>Well if you want to control a city/country/planet somebody has to
>physically be there. But if you can convince your enemy not to fight
>PFC Poppinfresh doesn\'t necesarily have to get muddy.


1.) If you want to control a city / country / planet in a traditional sense,
somebody\'s got to be there. The Imperium doesn\'t *want* to control cities /
countries / planets in the traditional sense. They simply want them to pay
taxes.

2.) Yes, and how would you convince the populace not to fight? Propaganda
campaigns might work, but they can also fail miserably. Perhaps a sufficient
show of force might be in order, like, I dunno, hauling in big rocks and
dropping them on select population centers.

>>How am I to be convinced that the Imperium (or other major interstellar
>>power) won\'t see value in dropping big, cheap rocks on major cities in
>order
>>to get their way?
>
>Because craters don\'t pay taxes.


Neither does a determined populace. So, we\'re back at square one.

>Countries go to war mostly to impose their will on others.

Well, sometimes it is to do more than simply impose their will on other
countries. It\'s been relatively common for a country to go to war to annex
territory. That\'s not an anal distinction, it is far more than a mere
imposition of will.

>Unless a countries aim is genocide less drastic measures will
>usually suffice.

It doesn\'t have to be genocide. Let me state again that total destruction
does not have to follow from rock dropping.

>Having to rebuild a conquered teritory and deal with enemies
>seeking revenge for attrocities commited is a real drag on the
>economy and way of life.


This would be different from the situation in what way after a land war in
what way precisely?

>It\'s so much easier to convince your enemy that you might enhance
>their radiant luminosity if they don\'t accept your reasonable offer of
>protectorate status, and quickly get about the business of
>import/export, than it is to actually wipe them out, wait for the ground
>to cool, plant a fresh colony, and then start up the import/export
>business.


Ah, okay. So now you\'re saying the mere threat of rock dropping will be
enough to bring a world around. The only problem is that from time to time a
world\'s going to say, "Hey! You\'re not *really* gonna whack us with rocks!"

Then what happens exactly... start a land war? Or follow through on the use
of cheap and brutal "terror weapons"?

>This is just the way I see things not holy writ or anything. But it fits my
>conception of the 3I (and must other empires/kingdoms/nations I\'ve
>experienced.)


Where do things such as the firebombing of Dresden, the atomic bombing of
Hiroshima and (tongue planted firmly in cheek) the God smiting of Sodom and
Gommorah fit into those conceptions?
